{"term": "1956", "caseName": "Wilson v. Girard", "caseLink": "https://www.oyez.org/cases/1956/1103", "caseTranscripts": [{"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - July 08, 1957 (Part 2)", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13334", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Robinson, you may proceed.", "start": 0, "stop": 12.752, "duration": 12.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Just as this Court recessed, the half hour was about to stay in connection with the so-called 97% of the waivers, but the fact is that even with all those waivers, we have more American soldiers in jail in any other foreign country in the world.", "start": 12.752, "stop": 35.326, "duration": 22.57}, {"text": "Imagine what we would have there if there were no waivers.", "start": 35.326, "stop": 40.994, "duration": 5.67}, {"text": "And in the back of the appendix, the last appendix we have attached to our brief, Your Honors will note a directive that was issued from one of the commands, by one of the commands in the Japanese area, and the substance of it is to the effect that all men must be more than careful in driving their automobiles through the streets of Japan because on to say that you can be held criminally liable in Japan on the base of criminal negligence, even though it wouldn't give rise to civil liability in the United States.", "start": 40.994, "stop": 78.376, "duration": 37.38}, {"text": "And it goes on to say that if you do not want to join the other men in the armed forces in the Japanese jails, we advice that you express sympathy to the family.", "start": 78.376, "stop": 91.047, "duration": 12.67}, {"text": "And then, they quote from a decision of one of the Japanese Judges, where he imprisoned one of our men and he said the reason for the imprisonment was because he failed to express sympathy to the family after an unfortunate event.", "start": 91.047, "stop": 108.531, "duration": 17.48}, {"text": "And so, waiver or no waiver, the fact remains that we have more difficulty with the Japanese nation insofar as putting our men into their jails than any other country in the world.", "start": 108.531, "stop": 128.229, "duration": 19.7}, {"text": "In addition to that, we have similar contracts or agreements or executive arrangements, whatever we may wish to call them were some 50 odd nations and whether this Court knows it or not.", "start": 128.229, "stop": 144.542, "duration": 16.31}, {"text": "A good many of them are secret.", "start": 144.542, "stop": 148.072, "duration": 3.53}, {"text": "Nobody could see them, no soldier overseas, no what -- with the States in that particular country knows what his rights or liabilities are insofar as jurisdiction is concerned.", "start": 148.072, "stop": 159.864, "duration": 11.79}, {"text": "They are secret even the Senate and the Congress of the United States had difficulty trying to obtain them.", "start": 159.864, "stop": 184.221, "duration": 24.36}, {"text": "As one Congress lady put it, I really challenged the right of the State Department or the Defense Department to make dealings with Americans which -- to make -- to make arrangements dealing with Americans, which have anything in them or any policy back of it or any desire to conciliate or go around which would serve to prevent those from knowing the exact terms, prevent the American people from knowing the exact terms.", "start": 184.221, "stop": 211.679, "duration": 27.46}, {"text": "I cannot understand or accept the necessity of secrecy.", "start": 211.679, "stop": 218.852, "duration": 7.17}, {"text": "And when the government officials of these hearings will question this that -- that these documents, they used the time-worn phrase.", "start": 218.852, "stop": 227.457, "duration": 8.6}, {"text": "They are classified and we can supply no information.", "start": 227.457, "stop": 231.54, "duration": 4.08}, {"text": "Now, imagine, a soldier in the United States Army assigned to some far off land and being told that he may be subject to the jurisdiction of a foreign -- of the land which he -- which he stationed without he or his lawyer or anybody else being able to know what secret arrangement the State and War Departments made with the Government wherein he is stationed.", "start": 231.54, "stop": 259.682, "duration": 28.14}, {"text": "In the case of the Japanese agreement, it is not secret as such.", "start": 259.682, "stop": 266.149, "duration": 6.47}, {"text": "But how did the Japanese arrangement come about?", "start": 266.149, "stop": 270.065, "duration": 3.92}, {"text": "When the NATO Status of Forces contract was submitted to the Senate, and by the way it was submitted to the Senate almost three years after the agreements were made and many Senators questioned why it was being submitted at that time, the Senate, when it ratified, specifically stated that the NATO Status of Forces Agreement shall not be a precedence for similar agreements in any other country.", "start": 270.065, "stop": 303.452, "duration": 33.39}, {"text": "That's not the exact language but that's the text of it.", "start": 303.452, "stop": 306.429, "duration": 2.98}, {"text": "And they also reserved, they also made a reservation that in any case where a United States soldier may be -- may be deprived or denied of any constitutional right that he should not be turned over to a foreign government for trial.", "start": 306.429, "stop": 326.068, "duration": 19.64}, {"text": "Those were the two mandates which the Senate expressed at the time it ratified or consented to the -- the NATO Status of Forces Agreement.", "start": 326.068, "stop": 337.844, "duration": 11.78}, {"text": "At least insofar as the NATO countries are concerned, the -- they are the European countries whose system of justice is more nearly akin to ours than some of the Asiatic countries.", "start": 337.844, "stop": 352.653, "duration": 14.81}, {"text": "But the Congress, nevertheless, imposed those two restrictions on any further action insofar as making these agreements with other countries who are concerned but that did not stop the men who were making them.", "start": 352.653, "stop": 366.422, "duration": 13.77}, {"text": "They continued to make them, some secret, others exposed with all countries in the world and when they were asked why, they were asked by the congressional committees, \"Why did you do this?", "start": 366.422, "stop": 380.609, "duration": 14.19}, {"text": "Why did you surrender this jurisdiction?\"", "start": 380.609, "stop": 383.283, "duration": 2.67}, {"text": "They said, \"It was the best we could get.\"", "start": 383.283, "stop": 385.962, "duration": 2.68}, {"text": "And then, they were asked, “Were there any country say that they would not permit us to station our troops in that country in the event we did not surrender the jurisdiction?”", "start": 385.962, "stop": 398.665, "duration": 12.7}, {"text": "There was no answer.", "start": 398.665, "stop": 401.052, "duration": 2.39}, {"text": "It was -- it was asked at least 10 or 15 times by a various Congressmen and Senators, as to whether or not any country laid down as a condition to the United States having bases or troops within their area, whether we must surrender jurisdiction over our own men and no country was pointed to as having made that demand on the United States.", "start": 401.052, "stop": 427.213, "duration": 26.16}, {"text": "And so, these agreements were made.", "start": 427.213, "stop": 428.999, "duration": 1.79}, {"text": "First, they were wholly unnecessary.", "start": 428.999, "stop": 431.873, "duration": 2.87}, {"text": "Secondly, they violated our -- the international law.", "start": 431.873, "stop": 435.97, "duration": 4.1}, {"text": "And thirdly, they are unconstitutional.", "start": 435.97, "stop": 439.853, "duration": 3.88}, {"text": "And before getting into the unconstitutional question, I want to state that these very officials who point to the justice of foreign countries as being excellent in something which our men must endure when they're serving in the armed forces that these very officials reserved immunity to themselves, the soldiers, they said, may submit to the jurisdiction of a foreign country, but we the officials or anybody connected with the NATO organization, and this is not the group that's in the diplomatic status, they said, we for ourselves will not submit to the foreign jurisdictions.", "start": 439.853, "stop": 479.954, "duration": 40.1}, {"text": "And I think it would be enlightening to the Court to know the theory on which one group of our -- of our citizens were subjected to foreign jurisdiction and on what theory the other was not subjected.", "start": 479.954, "stop": 500.881, "duration": 20.93}, {"text": "And these are questions asked of Mr. Rankin by -- by Congressman (Inaudible) page 352 of the congressional hearing record to which I have referred before.", "start": 500.881, "stop": 516.313, "duration": 15.43}, {"text": "Mr. (Inaudible) From the standpoint of Attorney General's Office, couldn't the same range be made with respect to the military.", "start": 516.313, "stop": 522.154, "duration": 5.84}, {"text": "I'm referring to the arrangements made for the NATO employees.", "start": 522.154, "stop": 526.496, "duration": 4.34}, {"text": "Mr. Rankin \"Well, it is a different right when you don't have the right of the individual because he is not forwarding the interest of the Government.\"", "start": 526.496, "stop": 540.932, "duration": 14.44}, {"text": "Mr. (Inaudible) -- I'm skipping several questions and answers because they deal generally with the subject.", "start": 540.932, "stop": 544.855, "duration": 3.92}, {"text": "Mr. (Inaudible) “But wouldn't you consider the presence of our forces there as furthering also the national interest and wellbeing the same as our diplomatic people?”", "start": 544.855, "stop": 557.828, "duration": 12.97}, {"text": "And someone else answered and said, \"Yes, I do,\" but so and so said something else.", "start": 557.828, "stop": 565.184, "duration": 7.36}, {"text": "Then, there were further questions asked to Mr. Rankin as to how these agreements came about and I'll read two or three questions and answers.", "start": 565.184, "stop": 572.878, "duration": 7.69}, {"text": "Mr. Bentley “If I may resume the question with you again, Mr. Rankin, I am still trying to see if we can't get a definite answer to this question.", "start": 572.878, "stop": 582.065, "duration": 9.19}, {"text": "The Bill of Rights and the Constitution does not follow members of the armed forces overseas.”", "start": 582.065, "stop": 587.689, "duration": 5.62}, {"text": "Mr. Rankin “That's right.”", "start": 587.689, "stop": 589.628, "duration": 1.94}, {"text": "Mr. Bentley “My contention is, sir, that the Military Justice Code and the Uniform Code of Military Justice, likewise does not follow them overseas under the Status of Forces Agreement.”", "start": 589.628, "stop": 601.065, "duration": 11.44}, {"text": "Mr. Rankin “It does as much as it does within this country.”", "start": 601.065, "stop": 607.024, "duration": 5.96}, {"text": "Mr. Bentley “Let's not make a comparison, sir.", "start": 607.024, "stop": 609.933, "duration": 2.91}, {"text": "Let's leave it to the -- let's leave it overseas.", "start": 609.933, "stop": 612.543, "duration": 2.61}, {"text": "What would be -- what -- would that be correct?”", "start": 612.543, "stop": 616.06, "duration": 3.52}, {"text": "Mr. Rankin “I can't answer that yes or no.", "start": 616.06, "stop": 619.225, "duration": 3.17}, {"text": "As long as they are on duty, the code follows them throughout the world.”", "start": 619.225, "stop": 624.564, "duration": 5.34}, {"text": "Mr. Bentley “If they are uniformed and not on duty, it does not follow them, would that be correct?”", "start": 624.564, "stop": 629.309, "duration": 4.75}, {"text": "“That would be correct.”", "start": 629.309, "stop": 631.679, "duration": 2.37}, {"text": "And so, we have testimony given to the effect -- a man in uniform who was not on duty is not subject to our Military Code and we have the statement made in this record that if he is on duty, he is subject to the Military Code.", "start": 631.679, "stop": 651.563, "duration": 19.88}, {"text": "Now, this case, the facts -- in this case, the facts are stipulated.", "start": 651.563, "stop": 656.585, "duration": 5.02}, {"text": "It was stipulated that Girard was on duty.", "start": 656.585, "stop": 660.518, "duration": 3.93}, {"text": "It was stipulated in the court below that he was in the performance of duty.", "start": 660.518, "stop": 668.643, "duration": 8.13}, {"text": "The code provides that if there was any issue of fact in the habeas corpus proceeding, the petitioner must be produced to give any necessary evidence in order to avoid Girard from being -- being brought to the United States to give evidence.", "start": 668.643, "stop": 686.934, "duration": 18.29}, {"text": "They stipulated that whatever was done, the acts, which he committed which gave rise to the offense was committed in the course of official duty.", "start": 686.934, "stop": 697.316, "duration": 10.38}, {"text": "Now, testimony has been given before the Senate, before the Congress that if a man is in the course of the performance of official duty that even under these agreements, assuming for the moment they are valid, he may not be tried by any other Government.", "start": 697.316, "stop": 716.72, "duration": 19.4}, {"text": "Now, to turn to how the Japanese agreements came into effect.", "start": 716.72, "stop": 730.886, "duration": 14.17}, {"text": "There was this security.", "start": 730.886, "stop": 732.135, "duration": 1.25}, {"text": "First, there was the peace treaty, then there was the security pact.", "start": 732.135, "stop": 736.034, "duration": 3.9}, {"text": "The security pact recites in this preempt that in order to protect Japan, not for the benefit of the United States, but in order to -- to protect Japan, the United States would be permitted to retain certain bases and stations, certain of its armed forces there that in connection with the -- I think agreements for the disposition of forces, I have to get the exact language, an administrative agreement would be -- would be entered into.", "start": 736.034, "stop": 768.533, "duration": 32.5}, {"text": "An administrative agreement was entered into.", "start": 768.533, "stop": 771.095, "duration": 2.56}, {"text": "It dealt with the civic matter of the disposition of forces, facilities, rights and so forth, and in addition, had contained there in the clause that exclusive jurisdiction over our armed forces shall continue to remain within the United States.", "start": 771.095, "stop": 789.748, "duration": 18.65}, {"text": "And there was the added clause that in the event, the NATO -- the NATO Status of Forces Treaty should go into effect that the option of Japan, the United States may enter into a similar agreement with Japan or would enter into a similar agreement with Japan.", "start": 789.748, "stop": 805.361, "duration": 15.61}, {"text": "The negotiations leading up to this similar agreement, we do not know, but we do know that a so-called protocol was then entered into, which completely reversed the situation as it had been under the administrative agreement.", "start": 805.361, "stop": 821.313, "duration": 15.95}, {"text": "The Senators of the United States never was called upon and never had the opportunity of seeing this protocol.", "start": 821.313, "stop": 827.429, "duration": 6.12}, {"text": "It was not in existence when they ratified the NATO Status for Forces Agreement with the two reservations.", "start": 827.429, "stop": 834.862, "duration": 7.43}, {"text": "And after the protocol was drawn, it still was not sufficient to want the transfer of jurisdiction from one nation to another.", "start": 834.862, "stop": 845.408, "duration": 10.55}, {"text": "And so, another instrument was entered into, called Agreed Views.", "start": 845.408, "stop": 850.316, "duration": 4.91}, {"text": "These were the officials in -- in Japan, Japanese officials and the American officials sitting down and agreeing to certain views as to how or as to what the meaning of the protocol was and that wasn't sufficient.", "start": 850.316, "stop": 864.591, "duration": 14.27}, {"text": "They then had some minutes of the meetings, which they attached to the protocol and said, that is a part of the protocol.", "start": 864.591, "stop": 873.078, "duration": 8.49}, {"text": "Followed by that -- thereafter, there was the -- a circular which was issued and all these documents put together, the Government now contends and gave the executive department of this Government the power to strip a man who was in a duty status of the protection of the United States Code -- of the United States Military Code and turn him over to the Japanese Government for trial.", "start": 873.078, "stop": 904.604, "duration": 31.53}, {"text": "And it was admitted in a -- a special hearing that was held on the Girard case on June 15th, I think it was of this year before a subcommittee of the Senate, that the power to make the determination as to who would exercise jurisdiction was in Japan and not in us, that the papers were so drawn that while the United States did protest that jurisdiction, this was jurisdiction that was -- went out assuming now that the -- the agreements were valid, that nevertheless the ultimate decision as to where the jurisdiction would lie was in the Japanese Government.", "start": 904.604, "stop": 944.267, "duration": 39.66}, {"text": "And finally, in this particular --", "start": 944.267, "stop": 945.357, "duration": 1.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you -- do you dispute that interpretation of the protocol if it is valid?", "start": 945.357, "stop": 955.035, "duration": 9.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 955.035, "stop": 956.384, "duration": 1.35}, {"text": "The United States has taken the position that because of the documents which followed the Agreed Views and the -- you see the protocol was the third step.", "start": 956.384, "stop": 968.813, "duration": 12.43}, {"text": "The first step, the -- then -- then came the Agreed Views, which was the agreement between the -- the Government -- the Government representatives agreed to in a roundtable of conference and then the menace of that agreement and they claimed pursuant to those minutes attached to the Agreed Views and then the circular, which was issued thereafter that the power was vested in the Japanese Government alone to make the determinations to whether or not it was an on duty or off duty case.", "start": 968.813, "stop": 997.978, "duration": 29.16}, {"text": "And in the brief, there's a reference to the fact that the Turkish Government has taken the same position in -- in another case under a similar arrangement but it did not flow from the protocol as such.", "start": 997.978, "stop": 1009.201, "duration": 11.22}, {"text": "The claim is that it flowed from the Agreed Views document, which they say is law.", "start": 1009.201, "stop": 1014.916, "duration": 5.72}, {"text": "On what theory, I don't know, but they say that is the law and therefore, abiding on us.", "start": 1014.916, "stop": 1020.57, "duration": 5.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why do you say it does not flow from the protocol assuming its validity?", "start": 1020.57, "stop": 1026.555, "duration": 5.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "The right -- there -- there as -- if I recall correctly, Your Honor, there is nothing in the protocol which gives the right to -- to waive.", "start": 1026.555, "stop": 1033.051, "duration": 6.5}, {"text": "I think it comes in the Agreed Views.", "start": 1033.051, "stop": 1034.675, "duration": 1.62}, {"text": "I -- I'm not sure.", "start": 1034.675, "stop": 1036.262, "duration": 1.59}, {"text": "There were so many documents here.", "start": 1036.262, "stop": 1037.525, "duration": 1.26}, {"text": "What does the protocol say on this?", "start": 1037.525, "stop": 1044.021, "duration": 6.5}, {"text": "I'm -- I'm sorry.", "start": 1044.021, "stop": 1045.43, "duration": 1.41}, {"text": "Mr. Carl tells me that it does flow from the protocol but then they changed the definition under Agreed Views.", "start": 1045.43, "stop": 1051.876, "duration": 6.45}, {"text": "They changed the definition of what official duty meant.", "start": 1051.876, "stop": 1058.089, "duration": 6.21}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'd like to conform (Inaudible)", "start": 1058.089, "stop": 1060.745, "duration": 2.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't know.", "start": 1060.745, "stop": 1061.678, "duration": 0.93}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "You don't know?", "start": 1061.678, "stop": 1062.562, "duration": 0.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't know.", "start": 1062.562, "stop": 1062.973, "duration": 0.41}, {"text": "There -- there are so -- there are so many -- there are so many documents here that I -- I couldn't answer all.", "start": 1062.973, "stop": 1067.482, "duration": 4.51}, {"text": "I just -- I just don't know.", "start": 1067.482, "stop": 1068.766, "duration": 1.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Then, if you assume that you admit and agree that the right -- that Japan tried the soldier close from the protocol, your problem is as to the validity of the protocol.", "start": 1068.766, "stop": 1081.36, "duration": 12.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "But I do not agree that the protocol --", "start": 1081.36, "stop": 1082.807, "duration": 1.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understand that you do not --", "start": 1082.807, "stop": 1083.994, "duration": 1.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 1083.994, "stop": 1084.095, "duration": 0.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- and you haven't discussed it yet, I don't (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 1084.095, "stop": 1085.883, "duration": 1.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 1085.883, "stop": 1087.372, "duration": 1.49}, {"text": "That's right, sir.", "start": 1087.372, "stop": 1088.725, "duration": 1.35}, {"text": "Now, let -- let us turn to the constitutional issue involved.", "start": 1088.725, "stop": 1099.151, "duration": 10.43}, {"text": "The Constitution says that the power to --", "start": 1099.151, "stop": 1100.592, "duration": 1.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did you -- did you challenge it only on a constitutional basis?", "start": 1100.592, "stop": 1103.986, "duration": 3.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 1103.986, "stop": 1105.455, "duration": 1.47}, {"text": "We challenged it on the interpretation.", "start": 1105.455, "stop": 1107.926, "duration": 2.47}, {"text": "That's in -- that's part of the brief but the time is running out, Your Honor.", "start": 1107.926, "stop": 1111.321, "duration": 3.39}, {"text": "I -- I won't be able to cover all the ground.", "start": 1111.321, "stop": 1113.278, "duration": 1.96}, {"text": "We challenged it on the constitutional --", "start": 1113.278, "stop": 1114.396, "duration": 1.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "But it seems to me like if -- if I may be permitted to say it --", "start": 1114.396, "stop": 1117.065, "duration": 2.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 1117.065, "stop": 1117.123, "duration": 0.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- because if that's the point that you need to cover or somebody needs to cover on your side whether or not that you say you challenged its validity, you challenge it on the basis that the statute does not authorize it or the treaty does not authorize it --", "start": 1117.123, "stop": 1133.483, "duration": 16.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 1133.483, "stop": 1133.52, "duration": 0.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- that's to be discussed.", "start": 1133.52, "stop": 1134.289, "duration": 0.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's covered also.", "start": 1134.289, "stop": 1135.024, "duration": 0.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "And if you discuss it on the basis of its unconstitutionality, but after you point out why you think it's unconstitutional.", "start": 1135.024, "stop": 1142.314, "duration": 7.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's what I'm -- that's what I'm going to.", "start": 1142.314, "stop": 1144.168, "duration": 1.85}, {"text": "The -- the treaty doesn't authorize it because the NATO Treaty that the Senate consented to had the reservations that it shall not be a question for any further treaties of -- of similar nature.", "start": 1144.168, "stop": 1159.379, "duration": 15.21}, {"text": "And even if as Mr. Rankin says, “The agreement for jurisdiction, the Administrative Agreement, was within the knowledge of the Senators who voted to ratify the NATO Agreement that -- that particular agreement held exclusive jurisdiction in the United States.", "start": 1159.379, "stop": 1180.593, "duration": 21.21}, {"text": "And then when the protocol was entered into, which was never brought to -- to the Senate and it was entered into by the Ambassador, the American Ambassador in Japan, he simply reversed the situation as it was and conferred almost exclusive jurisdiction on the Japanese Government with the exception of this on duty cases and one of two case involving security and property and persons of the United States.", "start": 1180.593, "stop": 1206.733, "duration": 26.14}, {"text": "But --", "start": 1206.733, "stop": 1207.845, "duration": 1.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did you say that the Administrative Agreement, they had exclusive jurisdiction in the United States?", "start": 1207.845, "stop": 1214.019, "duration": 6.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 1214.019, "stop": 1214.97, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But it also said such jurisdiction made in any case be waived by the United States.", "start": 1214.97, "stop": 1220.885, "duration": 5.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understand that, Your Honor.", "start": 1220.885, "stop": 1222.706, "duration": 1.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "We're they qualified and part --", "start": 1222.706, "stop": 1224.306, "duration": 1.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Pardon, sir?", "start": 1224.306, "stop": 1225.133, "duration": 0.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "An exclusive jurisdiction that may be waived is something else than an exclusive jurisdiction period.", "start": 1225.133, "stop": 1231.514, "duration": 6.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, the -- the waiver raised an entirely different issue whether or not the part respecting in waiver is legal or constitutional.", "start": 1231.514, "stop": 1239.616, "duration": 8.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that -- that's the subject to which I think that Justice Black in part of it asked you to address yourself.", "start": 1239.616, "stop": 1246.729, "duration": 7.11}, {"text": "All I'm suggesting is it is not correct to say that if one is restricted to the Administrative Agreement that if the United States exclusive jurisdiction --", "start": 1246.729, "stop": 1256.691, "duration": 9.96}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm -- I don't --", "start": 1256.691, "stop": 1256.875, "duration": 0.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- is to qualify the exclusive jurisdiction.", "start": 1256.875, "stop": 1258.558, "duration": 1.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't recall, Your Honor, whether there's anything in there about waiver or not if Your Honor has read it.", "start": 1258.558, "stop": 1261.377, "duration": 2.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But it -- it is in there.", "start": 1261.377, "stop": 1262.797, "duration": 1.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I don't recall.", "start": 1262.797, "stop": 1262.85, "duration": 0.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "You're not supposed to read it.", "start": 1262.85, "stop": 1264.322, "duration": 1.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't -- Your Honor, I've read so many documents for the last two weeks.", "start": 1264.322, "stop": 1267.381, "duration": 3.06}, {"text": "I just can't remember the exact words of any specific document.", "start": 1267.381, "stop": 1269.826, "duration": 2.44}, {"text": "I'm trying to generalize as best I can for memory what the particular document says and I'm sure that it says that the exclusive jurisdiction in the United States and if Your Honor says, it's provisions for waiver in their way, I -- I don't recall it.", "start": 1269.826, "stop": 1283.083, "duration": 13.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I have no inside knowledge, except for the documents given.", "start": 1283.083, "stop": 1285.935, "duration": 2.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I don't recall.", "start": 1285.935, "stop": 1286.942, "duration": 1.01}, {"text": "What -- what did that thing say?", "start": 1286.942, "stop": 1288.607, "duration": 1.66}, {"text": "Anyhow --", "start": 1288.607, "stop": 1289.723, "duration": 1.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, assuming that there is a provision for exclusive jurisdiction, which can be waived in the Administrative Agreement, do you challenge the validity of the Administrative Agreement on the ground that it was not authorized by the Senate and the Treaty?", "start": 1289.723, "stop": 1305.404, "duration": 15.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir, and all the documents that follow, we challenged on this basis and we have to go back to the fundamental law.", "start": 1305.404, "stop": 1314.03, "duration": 8.63}, {"text": "The Constitution says that the right to make rules and regulations for the Government of our armed forces is in the Congress.", "start": 1314.03, "stop": 1322.633, "duration": 8.6}, {"text": "That means the Senate and the House of Representatives combined, a Congress has enacted a code, which is to govern our armed forces insofar as discipline is concerned.", "start": 1322.633, "stop": 1337.42, "duration": 14.79}, {"text": "And they put a clause in there to the effect that this code -- I don't recall the words -- the words in substance out of this Code shall govern in all parts of the world.", "start": 1337.42, "stop": 1349.709, "duration": 12.29}, {"text": "It was obviously in the intent of the Congress who were vested with constitutional power to declare crimes in the modes of -- of the procedure for its punishment and the modes of appeal and the types of evidence, all of which is set forth in the United States Code in the -- the -- that is the United States Military Code, in the manual for courts-martial which is an adjunct to the Code states what the jurisdiction is.", "start": 1349.709, "stop": 1378.123, "duration": 28.41}, {"text": "It says it's in -- it's in the court-martial.", "start": 1378.123, "stop": 1381.089, "duration": 2.97}, {"text": "We take the position that when the Constitution vested that power in Congress, that is the House of Representatives and the -- the Senate combined, that both the executive -- that the executive alone and the executive combined with the Senate could not take any action which would take away the prerogatives of the -- of the Congress which the Constitution vested in them.", "start": 1381.089, "stop": 1411.049, "duration": 29.96}, {"text": "When it says that this Code shall govern our armed forces all over the world, it meant exactly that.", "start": 1411.049, "stop": 1417.401, "duration": 6.35}, {"text": "It prescribed the character of the crimes which will be punished.", "start": 1417.401, "stop": 1420.958, "duration": 3.56}, {"text": "It -- it prescribed the procedure that would be gone through.", "start": 1420.958, "stop": 1424.553, "duration": 3.6}, {"text": "It refers to -- as this Court well knows, it's very detailed on the whole subject.", "start": 1424.553, "stop": 1431.203, "duration": 6.65}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What in view of that would be so that it says that a member of the armed forces accused of an offense against civil authority may be delivered upon request to the civil authority at the trial.", "start": 1431.203, "stop": 1441.038, "duration": 9.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 1441.038, "stop": 1441.522, "duration": 0.48}, {"text": "Historically, Mr. Justice Brennan, that came about in this way if I recall correctly.", "start": 1441.522, "stop": 1448.644, "duration": 7.12}, {"text": "Originally, under the old Articles of War, this particular section had reference to delivery to the civil law authorities within the continental limits of the United States only.", "start": 1448.644, "stop": 1462.295, "duration": 13.65}, {"text": "And then a case arose where an individual left Germany and returned to United States.", "start": 1462.295, "stop": 1469.853, "duration": 7.56}, {"text": "At that time, Germany was under, more or less a civilian administration as against the former military occupation, we have the Allied High Commission functioning there, and the subject matter of being able to -- to take this individual back to Germany and deliver him to the civil law -- to our civil law authorities in Germany for trial there came up and the limitation that was contained in the old Articles of War, limiting the right to deliver to areas within continental limits of the United States only was taken out.", "start": 1469.853, "stop": 1507.988, "duration": 38.13}, {"text": "The historical background of that enactment will indicate to Your Honors that it -- it was not the intent of the Senate to give unlimited political power or discretion in the President or the executive to transfer any person or to take away the protection of the Military Code from anyone of our men in the armed forces.", "start": 1507.988, "stop": 1530.519, "duration": 22.53}, {"text": "And I say this that if in fact it is interpreted that that particular section -- I think it's Article XIV, I'm not sure, Your Honor, at that particular section authorize or permits the executive to strip a soldier of his -- of his protective rights under the Military Code that that section is unconstitutional because the -- the -- there is no procedure established for so doing, one.", "start": 1530.519, "stop": 1568.063, "duration": 37.54}, {"text": "Secondly, no branch in the Government or even the three branches of the Government combined have it within their power to take the constitutional rights away from any individual.", "start": 1568.063, "stop": 1580.29, "duration": 12.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "If a soldier -- if a soldier commits a crime in Germany while in -- in Germany and then comes back to the United States, can the United States extradite him to Germany even without an extradition treaty?", "start": 1580.29, "stop": 1599.155, "duration": 18.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, that came up in the Mobley-Handy case.", "start": 1599.155, "stop": 1601.643, "duration": 2.49}, {"text": "That's the case I have --", "start": 1601.643, "stop": 1603.234, "duration": 1.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Come up in several cases, come up again and again.", "start": 1603.234, "stop": 1604.323, "duration": 1.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It was not passed upon by this Court.", "start": 1604.323, "stop": 1606.014, "duration": 1.69}, {"text": "I don't not think.", "start": 1606.014, "stop": 1607.927, "duration": 1.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, on the fact of case.", "start": 1607.927, "stop": 1609.665, "duration": 1.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Pardon, Your Honor?", "start": 1609.665, "stop": 1610.726, "duration": 1.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "The fact -- the famous factory case of --", "start": 1610.726, "stop": 1613.284, "duration": 2.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't -- I don't recall that one.", "start": 1613.284, "stop": 1615.376, "duration": 2.09}, {"text": "I don't think --", "start": 1615.376, "stop": 1615.481, "duration": 0.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Voice Overlap) can he do that?", "start": 1615.481, "stop": 1617.223, "duration": 1.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't think so, Your Honor.", "start": 1617.223, "stop": 1618.026, "duration": 0.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "You don't think so.", "start": 1618.026, "stop": 1618.788, "duration": 0.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't think so.", "start": 1618.788, "stop": 1619.282, "duration": 0.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That was settled very early in this country's history in the case that it was much debated in the House --", "start": 1619.282, "stop": 1625.966, "duration": 6.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't -- I don't --", "start": 1625.966, "stop": 1626.188, "duration": 0.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- of Representative and Senate, the famous Robbins case --", "start": 1626.188, "stop": 1629.754, "duration": 3.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "If -- if --", "start": 1629.754, "stop": 1630.227, "duration": 0.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- as against the claim of jury trial and all the rest of it even without an extradition treaty.", "start": 1630.227, "stop": 1637.88, "duration": 7.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, we have extradition treaties, of course, to cover the Senate matter of transporting citizens from one nation to another.", "start": 1637.88, "stop": 1645.162, "duration": 7.28}, {"text": "The Valentine case in which Your Honors are unquestionably familiar, laid down the landmark rule that the executive did not have the power to transfer an individual out of this country and I think in that case, French citizens were involved.", "start": 1645.162, "stop": 1661.703, "duration": 16.54}, {"text": "To the French Government upon the demand of a latter Government accept that an extradition treaty so specifically provided.", "start": 1661.703, "stop": 1669.534, "duration": 7.83}, {"text": "In that case, the opinion was written by Chief Justice Hughes, my recollection is that the -- the holding is to the effect that even if there were discretionary power vested in the President that unless there was a mandate or a decree of the Congress whereby he was authorized to act that the individual could not be turned over.", "start": 1669.534, "stop": 1695.169, "duration": 25.63}, {"text": "In the Valentine case, the individual bought -- brought a petition for habeas corpus and the power of the President to transfer him, even under an extradition treaty was tested, and the individual was sustained, the power was not there.", "start": 1695.169, "stop": 1710.046, "duration": 14.88}, {"text": "In another case which is referred to in the brief, an alien, a Mexican that came into this country -- I don't recall the exact phrase, but he was here in the present figure that -- decided that he was detrimental to the best interest of the United States, I think he was in Texas, and an order was issued in the name of the President to the commanding officer that that man be held in confinement.", "start": 1710.046, "stop": 1737.268, "duration": 27.22}, {"text": "The argument was and he was acting as Commander in Chief, the same -- advance in this case, he was arguing -- he was acting as Commander in Chief of the armed forces and he can hold anyone in confinement or act as he surfeit with the individual, particularly an enemy in this country or not an enemy, a -- an alien.", "start": 1737.268, "stop": 1756.326, "duration": 19.06}, {"text": "In that case, the District Judge who wrote the opinion stated that it was, well, it had been on the bench a long time and he felt that he was being called upon to perform one of the most difficult duties he had during the period he was on the bench.", "start": 1756.326, "stop": 1774.076, "duration": 17.75}, {"text": "He nevertheless, directed that the individual would be free holding that even a -- an arrest that the direction of the President would not be binding on the individual.", "start": 1774.076, "stop": 1783.956, "duration": 9.88}, {"text": "That is for the courts to decide whether or not there is any law by which an individual may be held in confinement.", "start": 1783.956, "stop": 1791.15, "duration": 7.19}, {"text": "I -- I see I'm running -- I'm running out of my time.", "start": 1791.15, "stop": 1793.422, "duration": 2.27}, {"text": "I want to touch, if Your Honors please, upon the subject matter of what constitutional rights are taken away.", "start": 1793.422, "stop": 1800.806, "duration": 7.38}, {"text": "First of all, there's not only the question of -- of due process.", "start": 1800.806, "stop": 1805.471, "duration": 4.66}, {"text": "There is the question of the equal protection of the laws.", "start": 1805.471, "stop": 1809.28, "duration": 3.81}, {"text": "Let's assume that in this particular case, instead of an individual, a small G.I. like Girard was involved.", "start": 1809.28, "stop": 1815.88, "duration": 6.6}, {"text": "It was an officer of high rank or even our own Commanding General in the Far East Command that he was in the Camp Weir area and in the course of attempting to scare someone from the military post, a -- a trespasser who was there, and by the way, this was a trespass because there was signs there that no -- no foreigners were permitted to come on the area, no -- note after his nozzle -- the bullet come out again.", "start": 1815.88, "stop": 1842.388, "duration": 26.51}, {"text": "He accidentally killed someone.", "start": 1842.388, "stop": 1846.3, "duration": 3.91}, {"text": "To me, it would be the most humiliating sight to imagine that one of -- to imagine one of our high ranking officers be in trial before the civilian courts of a former enemy nation and there is nothing in these agreements that they're valid that would prevent the Japanese Government from making demand that they'd be permitted to try, our general or some high official in -- in the military who happened to be stationed in the area, unless the President of the United States in that case would agree not to waive.", "start": 1846.3, "stop": 1882.756, "duration": 36.46}, {"text": "And then, we have a situation where a political decision may deny to a person the equal protection of the laws.", "start": 1882.756, "stop": 1888.415, "duration": 5.66}, {"text": "In the one case because of the rank, the individual would not be turned over.", "start": 1888.415, "stop": 1892.547, "duration": 4.13}, {"text": "In the other case because he is a lowly G.I., he is turned over.", "start": 1892.547, "stop": 1896.832, "duration": 4.29}, {"text": "And yet, if -- what the appellant -- what the appellants in this case contend and their exact -- their exact contentions so there'd be no -- no question about any -- any misquotation, they say, “The decision of the United States not to exercise jurisdiction in this case is a discretionary decision of the Executive Branch and the conduct of foreign affairs and the military defense of the United States and as such is a political decision not subject to judicial review.”", "start": 1896.832, "stop": 1932.205, "duration": 35.37}, {"text": "We don't think that any individual, any American citizen can be taken outside the pail of the rights that are guaranteed by the Constitution by a political decision.", "start": 1932.205, "stop": 1943.392, "duration": 11.19}, {"text": "They say it was done hereby a political decision.", "start": 1943.392, "stop": 1945.376, "duration": 1.98}, {"text": "That's not our words.", "start": 1945.376, "stop": 1946.897, "duration": 1.52}, {"text": "Those are the words of the -- of the appellants.", "start": 1946.897, "stop": 1952.039, "duration": 5.14}, {"text": "And when you get to a point where individuals' rights are determined by political decisions of the Executive Branch of Government, I think, we are embarking upon a dangerous road to the destruction of the constitutional rights of all persons.", "start": 1952.039, "stop": 1970.866, "duration": 18.83}, {"text": "The -- the Constitution as has been said not only by this Court and Mr. Justice Frankfurter doesn't -- as of the opinion is not the opinion of the whole Court, which is true, but by the highest military court in the United States, they had this subject before them, the case I referred to in the brief, where they said constitutional safeguards follow our soldiers wherever they are in any land and they pointed out how impossible it was for a man in our military service to be afforded the same protection in the courts of a foreign country as he -- as he is in this country.", "start": 1970.866, "stop": 2019.146, "duration": 48.28}, {"text": "The Government points to seven rights which they say an individual has when he's on trial on foreign countries being the equivalent of constitutional rights, the right to a speedy trial.", "start": 2019.146, "stop": 2032.416, "duration": 13.27}, {"text": "I think Mr. Justice Nolan -- Senator Nolan commented on that.", "start": 2032.416, "stop": 2036.298, "duration": 3.88}, {"text": "He said, “Even -- even a Communist can be entitled to that” and he said the right to be -- to -- to have a copy of the charges.", "start": 2036.298, "stop": 2046.028, "duration": 9.73}, {"text": "Well, it is a fact that in one case it's come up.", "start": 2046.028, "stop": 2049.621, "duration": 3.59}, {"text": "The charges were -- in Japan, the charges that were served upon the man the very day he appeared in Court.", "start": 2049.621, "stop": 2055.447, "duration": 5.83}, {"text": "They then referred to the -- I'll -- I'll give you the seven rights which we'll say the equivalent of all our constitutional safeguards.", "start": 2055.447, "stop": 2070.646, "duration": 15.2}, {"text": "They say three witnesses must confront the accused.", "start": 2070.646, "stop": 2076.054, "duration": 5.41}, {"text": "Well, actually in practice, we know so in France, I don't know whether it's so in -- in Japan, but witnesses do not in every case, every criminal case confront the accused.", "start": 2076.054, "stop": 2087.652, "duration": 11.6}, {"text": "A dossier is made up by the magistrate in -- in the court below and it's handed up to the higher judge and the accused is brought in.", "start": 2087.652, "stop": 2098.973, "duration": 11.32}, {"text": "The -- in any event, even if he is confronted by the witnesses, what good would it do?", "start": 2098.973, "stop": 2105.658, "duration": 6.68}, {"text": "He doesn't know what this man is saying.", "start": 2105.658, "stop": 2107.275, "duration": 1.62}, {"text": "There were no rules of evidence as we understand that prescribed what he may say then they referred to -- a right a compulsory process but they add, “If the witness is within the jurisdiction.”", "start": 2107.275, "stop": 2119.98, "duration": 12.7}, {"text": "But what if a man is charged with murder and the witness happens to be one -- one mile all over the borderline?", "start": 2119.98, "stop": 2124.393, "duration": 4.41}, {"text": "There's no way of getting him.", "start": 2124.393, "stop": 2126.749, "duration": 2.36}, {"text": "And under certain part -- under the laws of certain countries and again I don't know whether it's true in Japan or not, you may produce a witness but then you can't make him testify.", "start": 2126.749, "stop": 2136.43, "duration": 9.68}, {"text": "Here, we have our normal court procedure which requires a witness to testify when you bring him and you may compel him to testify.", "start": 2136.43, "stop": 2142.718, "duration": 6.29}, {"text": "That is not so in all the countries of the world.", "start": 2142.718, "stop": 2148.486, "duration": 5.77}, {"text": "Then, they say there is the right of legal representation of one's own choice.", "start": 2148.486, "stop": 2153.968, "duration": 5.48}, {"text": "If an example of what happened in this case, any criteria of the right to which -- in which they were referred to here, a Japanese counsel was appointed for Girard and when he discharged him, he publicly announced that he was not going to be discharged and if he was, the Court will reappoint him anyhow.", "start": 2153.968, "stop": 2173.149, "duration": 19.18}, {"text": "That is another right, the appellants point to as being guaranteed this individual insofar as foreign courts are concerned and then he has the right to have an interpreter if he wants it and a right to communicate with his own Government.", "start": 2173.149, "stop": 2186.761, "duration": 13.61}, {"text": "Those are the seven basic rights to which the appellants referred as the -- as being the -- the same as constitutional safeguards.", "start": 2186.761, "stop": 2196.929, "duration": 10.17}, {"text": "And if Your Honors uphold the power of the present act in this case, what is there to stop him from stripping away these rights and saying, \"No, we won't give him that.", "start": 2196.929, "stop": 2206.759, "duration": 9.83}, {"text": "We'll give him one right when he's in solitary confinement.", "start": 2206.759, "stop": 2209.501, "duration": 2.74}, {"text": "We'll let someone visit him once a year.\"", "start": 2209.501, "stop": 2212.029, "duration": 2.53}, {"text": "If the power is there, he may go that far.", "start": 2212.029, "stop": 2214.931, "duration": 2.9}, {"text": "The question here is one of power, what are the limitations upon that power?", "start": 2214.931, "stop": 2221.544, "duration": 6.61}, {"text": "The Government officials when questioned on this subject matter of these so-called rights that were the substitute -- substitute for our Bill of Rights, they -- they asked this witness if he was an Assistant Secretary of Defense.", "start": 2221.544, "stop": 2243.081, "duration": 21.54}, {"text": "They asked him the specific -- I'll be in just a moment.", "start": 2243.081, "stop": 2257.665, "duration": 14.58}, {"text": "Yes, Senator Ferguson asked Mr. Nash who is an Assistant Secretary of Defense and who said that -- in his own testimony, he was one of the top lawyers in connection with these agreements.", "start": 2257.665, "stop": 2269.361, "duration": 11.7}, {"text": "Senator Ferguson “Do you consider the presumption of innocence does not enter into due process?”", "start": 2269.361, "stop": 2274.214, "duration": 4.85}, {"text": "Answer “I think that if a man has a chance to prove his own case, to develop his own case and prove his own facts that that would be all, it would be absolute required in elemental justice and equity.", "start": 2274.214, "stop": 2287.834, "duration": 13.62}, {"text": "Yes, sir.”", "start": 2287.834, "stop": 2290.065, "duration": 2.23}, {"text": "Now, there we have the views of an Assistant Secretary of Defense given before the Senate as to what the rights of an individual are before a foreign court.", "start": 2290.065, "stop": 2302.419, "duration": 12.35}, {"text": "We take the position that there has been a usurpation of power in connection with the execution of these agreements that the power to make rules and regulations for the Government of the armed forces of this nation vest -- is vested solely in the Congress.", "start": 2302.419, "stop": 2318.826, "duration": 16.41}, {"text": "And that the President may not take that -- that right away.", "start": 2318.826, "stop": 2323.887, "duration": 5.06}, {"text": "The President and the Senate combined may not take that right away, but those are rights -- that there were rights, which are guaranteed under the Constitution and while it has been said many times, the Constitution does not extend beyond the territory limits of the United States.", "start": 2323.887, "stop": 2341.017, "duration": 17.13}, {"text": "It would appear that the more recent opinions of this Court as to the effect that it does follow the individual under certain particular circumstances.", "start": 2341.017, "stop": 2350.01, "duration": 8.99}, {"text": "There are cases when it would not, a tourist going to France, of course, or in any other -- to any other country is not protected by the Constitution.", "start": 2350.01, "stop": 2358.402, "duration": 8.39}, {"text": "He is there with his own volition.", "start": 2358.402, "stop": 2360.508, "duration": 2.11}, {"text": "One of the government witnesses said that he could see no difference between a tourist going to France and a soldier who is drafted into the armed forces being ordered to go to France that they are both equally subject to the local jurisdiction.", "start": 2360.508, "stop": 2373.571, "duration": 13.06}, {"text": "And then, one question further on it, they were asked, “Well, how about -- how about an offense when a man is on duty?”", "start": 2373.571, "stop": 2380.778, "duration": 7.21}, {"text": "And this exact case -- the exact situation was used as an example by one of the witnesses.", "start": 2380.778, "stop": 2390.763, "duration": 9.99}, {"text": "They said that if a man was on --", "start": 2390.763, "stop": 2392.883, "duration": 2.12}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Where are you reading from now?", "start": 2392.883, "stop": 2394.93, "duration": 2.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Extracts of the testimony from -- by government witnesses.", "start": 2394.93, "stop": 2396.933, "duration": 2}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "What page of the brief?", "start": 2396.933, "stop": 2401.433, "duration": 4.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I was looking for it but I didn't have the page.", "start": 2401.433, "stop": 2403.387, "duration": 1.95}, {"text": "I think the -- the statement was made -- oh, at page 5A of the appendix, Your Honor.", "start": 2403.387, "stop": 2416.195, "duration": 12.81}, {"text": "Senator Ferguson asked the question to Mr. Fargo.", "start": 2416.195, "stop": 2418.261, "duration": 2.07}, {"text": "I am interested in the point that Mr. Fargo made with respect to exclusive jurisdiction on military reservations.", "start": 2418.261, "stop": 2423.888, "duration": 5.63}, {"text": "There's another subject now.", "start": 2423.888, "stop": 2424.829, "duration": 0.94}, {"text": "There's an area of jurisdiction.", "start": 2424.829, "stop": 2428.357, "duration": 3.53}, {"text": "Mr. Fargo “That is not right.", "start": 2428.357, "stop": 2431.981, "duration": 3.62}, {"text": "If he is on army post engaged on duty, we have exclusive jurisdiction.”", "start": 2431.981, "stop": 2440.022, "duration": 8.04}, {"text": "That's what the Senate was told and they were told many other things to which reference have been made before and reference has made in the brief but I -- I would not -- I will not have time to further go into the subject.", "start": 2440.022, "stop": 2454.484, "duration": 14.46}, {"text": "I want to spend a few minutes if Your Honors --", "start": 2454.484, "stop": 2455.927, "duration": 1.44}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Could I ask you a question to that point?", "start": 2455.927, "stop": 2457.147, "duration": 1.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2457.147, "stop": 2458.246, "duration": 1.1}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "As I understand your argument, it's premised basically on the proposition that as a matter of international law as you call it, the United States had exclusive jurisdiction in Japan over its own troops.", "start": 2458.246, "stop": 2474.02, "duration": 15.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is correct, sir.", "start": 2474.02, "stop": 2475.343, "duration": 1.32}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Violation of Japanese law, violation of American law, violation of both Japanese and American laws --", "start": 2475.343, "stop": 2480.635, "duration": 5.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 2480.635, "stop": 2481.245, "duration": 0.61}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- as a matter of law --", "start": 2481.245, "stop": 2482.528, "duration": 1.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 2482.528, "stop": 2482.662, "duration": 0.13}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- as a matter of international law and I suppose in that premise, it hasn't accepted what becomes to your argument.", "start": 2482.662, "stop": 2488.216, "duration": 5.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well --", "start": 2488.216, "stop": 2488.394, "duration": 0.18}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "The constitutional argument.", "start": 2488.394, "stop": 2489.817, "duration": 1.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It does -- it does not necessarily fall.", "start": 2489.817, "stop": 2491.817, "duration": 2}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, what happens to it?", "start": 2491.817, "stop": 2494.007, "duration": 2.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "If -- if the premise that we had exclusive jurisdiction is not accepted, then we can fondle with the question as to who has the power to strip an American citizen of constitutional rights.", "start": 2494.007, "stop": 2506.83, "duration": 12.82}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "What is there in the Constitution assuming that your premise is wrong that forbids the trial of an American abroad for a violation of the laws of another country?", "start": 2506.83, "stop": 2518.419, "duration": 11.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "The Articles of War, the so-called Military Code.", "start": 2518.419, "stop": 2521.935, "duration": 3.52}, {"text": "The -- the individual, the citizen didn't go there voluntarily.", "start": 2521.935, "stop": 2527.475, "duration": 5.54}, {"text": "The citizen is subject and I refer to the specific -- this particular case.", "start": 2527.475, "stop": 2532.064, "duration": 4.59}, {"text": "Now, he is subject to the Uniform Code of Military Justice and nobody except possibly the Congress with the approval of the President could take away his right under the Uniform Code of Military Justice.", "start": 2532.064, "stop": 2547.454, "duration": 15.39}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "But how can the United States Constitution take away the right of Japan to try one of our citizens where an infraction of Japanese laws committed by a citizen, an American citizen in Japan?", "start": 2547.454, "stop": 2561.605, "duration": 14.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Japan, first of all, this is a subject matter, which is reserved to Mr. Carroll, would not have jurisdiction over the Camp Weir area and Japan even under these agreements assuming they are violently executed and constitutional did not have jurisdiction over this particular offense.", "start": 2561.605, "stop": 2578.483, "duration": 16.88}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh, you mean it doesn't come under the agreements.", "start": 2578.483, "stop": 2581.708, "duration": 3.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Assuming the agreements are valid, Your Honor.", "start": 2581.708, "stop": 2584.849, "duration": 3.14}, {"text": "Japan did not have jurisdiction under the -- under the agreements nor did Japan have jurisdiction over the Camp Weir area.", "start": 2584.849, "stop": 2591.236, "duration": 6.39}, {"text": "I'm going far off field because that's a subject that Mr. Carroll is going to take up both the personal immunity and the territorial immunity.", "start": 2591.236, "stop": 2599.392, "duration": 8.16}, {"text": "I want to raise just one more civic and that's -- that is in connection with our cross-appeal.", "start": 2599.392, "stop": 2608.124, "duration": 8.73}, {"text": "The action -- the proceedings were brought for a writ of habeas corpus.", "start": 2608.124, "stop": 2614.132, "duration": 6.01}, {"text": "The District Court granted a substantial part -- granted relief but not the specific relief asked for.", "start": 2614.132, "stop": 2626.947, "duration": 12.82}, {"text": "The relief asked for was that this man to be discharged from custody.", "start": 2626.947, "stop": 2634.291, "duration": 7.34}, {"text": "It may be said that we obtained all that we would want under the circumstances but that is not correct.", "start": 2634.291, "stop": 2642.988, "duration": 8.7}, {"text": "The fact is this man is still held in custody even though there has been an injunction issued against the government officials from transferring him to the foreign government.", "start": 2642.988, "stop": 2654.091, "duration": 11.1}, {"text": "He is not on the court-martial charges.", "start": 2654.091, "stop": 2656.836, "duration": 2.74}, {"text": "There is no reason why he shouldn't be free to go as any other soldier is free to go and move about.", "start": 2656.836, "stop": 2662.834, "duration": 6}, {"text": "Now, the argument of the respondents in answer is two-fold.", "start": 2662.834, "stop": 2668.166, "duration": 5.33}, {"text": "First, they say that the Court had no jurisdiction issued therein, the same old errands against the clock coming up from the Eisenhower Forest, all of this Court is very familiar with.", "start": 2668.166, "stop": 2680.35, "duration": 12.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "May I ask you a question in that connection, Mr. Robinson?", "start": 2680.35, "stop": 2682.663, "duration": 2.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2682.663, "stop": 2683.888, "duration": 1.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "Suppose that you were free too and did leave Camp Weir and were then seized by the Japanese --", "start": 2683.888, "stop": 2693.021, "duration": 9.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It would not be good.", "start": 2693.021, "stop": 2693.815, "duration": 0.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- would we have this question at all then?", "start": 2693.815, "stop": 2695.986, "duration": 2.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 2695.986, "stop": 2696.263, "duration": 0.28}, {"text": "It would not be good.", "start": 2696.263, "stop": 2696.989, "duration": 0.73}, {"text": "That -- well, the -- the writ requires them to deliver him before the Court.", "start": 2696.989, "stop": 2707.241, "duration": 10.25}, {"text": "That's here in Washington.", "start": 2707.241, "stop": 2708.388, "duration": 1.15}, {"text": "We applied for the writ to bring him before the Court.", "start": 2708.388, "stop": 2710.531, "duration": 2.14}, {"text": "Now, the Code says that if there's any issue of fact even on the hearing, they must produce them before the Court.", "start": 2710.531, "stop": 2717.861, "duration": 7.33}, {"text": "What they are saying in substance, Your Honor, I might follow the logic and the -- and the legal reasoning of what you've said, what they are saying is what Hitler said when he put thousands and thousands of people in jail saying they were there in protective custody.", "start": 2717.861, "stop": 2734.549, "duration": 16.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "I --", "start": 2734.549, "stop": 2734.819, "duration": 0.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's what they're doing --", "start": 2734.819, "stop": 2735.983, "duration": 1.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't think --", "start": 2735.983, "stop": 2736.133, "duration": 0.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- in saying --", "start": 2736.133, "stop": 2736.524, "duration": 0.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- I have made my question clear.", "start": 2736.524, "stop": 2740.098, "duration": 3.57}, {"text": "You sought and obtained an order prohibiting the United States from turning over Girard to the Japanese, didn't you?", "start": 2740.098, "stop": 2751.386, "duration": 11.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Actually, it was the writ of habeas corpus, that's correct, (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 2751.386, "stop": 2752.957, "duration": 1.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Voice Overlap) -- all right.", "start": 2752.957, "stop": 2754.429, "duration": 1.47}, {"text": "Now, if the -- if he went outside this camp and were taken into custody for the Japanese, wouldn't that -- wouldn't they then try him?", "start": 2754.429, "stop": 2765.486, "duration": 11.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh, sure but that's --", "start": 2765.486, "stop": 2765.995, "duration": 0.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "He wouldn't have this case, would he?", "start": 2765.995, "stop": 2767.239, "duration": 1.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "He -- he wouldn't do that but he is not only restricted to the camp area, Your Honor.", "start": 2767.239, "stop": 2771.242, "duration": 4}, {"text": "It's one thing to stay within a camp area voluntarily and it's one thing to have a police officer breathing down your back everywhere you move.", "start": 2771.242, "stop": 2778.514, "duration": 7.27}, {"text": "According to the press, he had police officers with him when they got married the other day.", "start": 2778.514, "stop": 2783.319, "duration": 4.8}, {"text": "That's what we're complaining about and we say the position of the Government, they have a right to hold a man in protective custody.", "start": 2783.319, "stop": 2789.359, "duration": 6.04}, {"text": "It's not for them to say whether a man wants to be protected.", "start": 2789.359, "stop": 2792.358, "duration": 3}, {"text": "We don't assume that Girard will leave this area, this sanctuary that he has this -- this area within Camp Weir and move outside where the Japanese can seize him.", "start": 2792.358, "stop": 2803.714, "duration": 11.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your whole argument thus far was that he must be tried by court-martial, is that right?", "start": 2803.714, "stop": 2810.116, "duration": 6.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 2810.116, "stop": 2811.026, "duration": 0.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you mean, neither -- neither Japan nor the United States has -- has any means of trying him for this --", "start": 2811.026, "stop": 2816.539, "duration": 5.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, this Court -- the Code -- the Code would follow him but there's nothing that's said that the court-martial must try him.", "start": 2816.539, "stop": 2821.071, "duration": 4.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "No -- no, but --", "start": 2821.071, "stop": 2822.59, "duration": 1.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "He's subject to the court-martial, yes, sir.", "start": 2822.59, "stop": 2823.539, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "He's subject to court-martial.", "start": 2823.539, "stop": 2825.288, "duration": 1.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, if the Government is --", "start": 2825.288, "stop": 2825.849, "duration": 0.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And you say that -- you say that even if you're right thus far, he must be released at once without giving the American military authorities an opportunity --", "start": 2825.849, "stop": 2835.349, "duration": 9.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 2835.349, "stop": 2835.429, "duration": 0.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- to hold him in jurisdictionally?", "start": 2835.429, "stop": 2836.897, "duration": 1.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, I didn't say that, Your Honor.", "start": 2836.897, "stop": 2838.121, "duration": 1.22}, {"text": "If he --", "start": 2838.121, "stop": 2838.151, "duration": 0.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that's what -- that's what surrender would mean necessarily.", "start": 2838.151, "stop": 2842.399, "duration": 4.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, Your Honor.", "start": 2842.399, "stop": 2843.008, "duration": 0.61}, {"text": "He -- he is still -- he is still subject to military control.", "start": 2843.008, "stop": 2847.471, "duration": 4.46}, {"text": "What we are --", "start": 2847.471, "stop": 2847.649, "duration": 0.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But he can't be detained until an appropriate military proceeding is started.", "start": 2847.649, "stop": 2852.394, "duration": 4.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 2852.394, "stop": 2852.415, "duration": 0.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But all the cases are against him.", "start": 2852.415, "stop": 2856.635, "duration": 4.22}, {"text": "But take all the immigration cases, which have held --", "start": 2856.635, "stop": 2859.818, "duration": 3.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm dealing with the Military Code only.", "start": 2859.818, "stop": 2861.157, "duration": 1.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I know, but the --", "start": 2861.157, "stop": 2861.68, "duration": 0.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't know about the (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 2861.68, "stop": 2862.043, "duration": 0.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- question is habeas corpus, whether, even if the detention is illegal.", "start": 2862.043, "stop": 2867.131, "duration": 5.09}, {"text": "There must be immediate surrender or whether this Court can deal with the matter according to right of justice --", "start": 2867.131, "stop": 2873.949, "duration": 6.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh, no --", "start": 2873.949, "stop": 2873.977, "duration": 0.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- and say in due course you can -- if in due course you bring proper proceedings, you may do so and you don't have --", "start": 2873.977, "stop": 2880.317, "duration": 6.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I agree with you --", "start": 2880.317, "stop": 2880.334, "duration": 0.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- to make the matter at large.", "start": 2880.334, "stop": 2881.535, "duration": 1.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor misunderstood me I think or I misunderstood Your Honor.", "start": 2881.535, "stop": 2884.282, "duration": 2.75}, {"text": "No, this Court is not bound to -- to release him immediately.", "start": 2884.282, "stop": 2887.731, "duration": 3.45}, {"text": "This Court has a right under the -- under the Habeas Corpus Act to make such provision as is just and proper under the circumstances.", "start": 2887.731, "stop": 2895.182, "duration": 7.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that's what the District Court has done.", "start": 2895.182, "stop": 2897.242, "duration": 2.06}, {"text": "It's given --", "start": 2897.242, "stop": 2897.615, "duration": 0.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 2897.615, "stop": 2898.253, "duration": 0.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "It has given a declaration of right, which if sustained makes clear that he can't be surrendered to Japan and therefore, it must appropriately be dealt with by American authorities.", "start": 2898.253, "stop": 2908.865, "duration": 10.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, there's a case in our brief, Your Honor, two or three of them, where a man was held and I'll just go with the rest and then I -- I must stop but I -- I'll --", "start": 2908.865, "stop": 2917.256, "duration": 8.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I suggest you deal with the case of Mahler against Eby in 264 U.S.", "start": 2917.256, "stop": 2922.916, "duration": 5.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, this -- this is a rather late case.", "start": 2922.916, "stop": 2924.651, "duration": 1.73}, {"text": "I don't recall the name of it, Your Honor, but in that case, a -- a -- an individual was convicted of murder in the State Court of Colorado and after the conviction, that is after the event, the Punishment Code was changed and obviously the change of the Punishment Code, it became -- it was an ex post facto law.", "start": 2924.651, "stop": 2949.592, "duration": 24.94}, {"text": "He made application for a writ in the federal court and the federal -- and the case, I think, it came to this Court, I'm -- I'm not sure, the writ was granted.", "start": 2949.592, "stop": 2963.223, "duration": 13.63}, {"text": "The ruling was to the effect, but if there is no basis for holding him or if the basis is illegal, he must be released but from a practical proposition.", "start": 2963.223, "stop": 2976.276, "duration": 13.05}, {"text": "We will have the Attorney General of the State notify that the exact time was released so that he may determine whether he should be held on some other ground.", "start": 2976.276, "stop": 2984.561, "duration": 8.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "In other words, the writ wasn't issued according to your own statement.", "start": 2984.561, "stop": 2987.228, "duration": 2.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It was -- it was issued, Your Honor.", "start": 2987.228, "stop": 2989.06, "duration": 1.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, not according to your statement a minute ago.", "start": 2989.06, "stop": 2991.185, "duration": 2.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Your Honor.", "start": 2991.185, "stop": 2991.73, "duration": 0.55}, {"text": "It was issued and the Court added --", "start": 2991.73, "stop": 2994.939, "duration": 3.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "They said we need an issue because the Attorney General will take appropriate action.", "start": 2994.939, "stop": 2998.366, "duration": 3.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 2998.366, "stop": 2998.996, "duration": 0.63}, {"text": "The -- the writ -- the writ was issued and a -- an order of the Court said that the Attorney General should be notified of the time and place of his release so that he may take any action he sees fit, but the writ issued --", "start": 2998.996, "stop": 3013.457, "duration": 14.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I suggest you look at Mahler against Eby in 264 U.S.", "start": 3013.457, "stop": 3017.538, "duration": 4.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, it isn't -- I don't know whether it is referred to in the other brief or not.", "start": 3017.538, "stop": 3020.509, "duration": 2.97}, {"text": "I -- and I -- I don't know whether we referred to it.", "start": 3020.509, "stop": 3022.024, "duration": 1.51}, {"text": "But in any event, what we're objecting to is having these police officers breathing down his back all the time when the lower court has already ruled that he may not be held to be turned over to the Japanese Government for trial and when the United States Government has taken no action with respect to trying him.", "start": 3022.024, "stop": 3041.755, "duration": 19.73}, {"text": "If they filed court-martial charges against him, well, certainly, they have right to detain him under the manual of the courts-martial.", "start": 3041.755, "stop": 3049.227, "duration": 7.47}, {"text": "The -- it is not necessary for our position to go as far as asserting that it's our opinion that all these NATO Status of Forces Agreements are really -- they're unconstitutional.", "start": 3049.227, "stop": 3065.447, "duration": 16.22}, {"text": "Certainly, those that did not receive Senate consent, the agreement involved in this particular case and the document on which they seek to turn Girard over to the Japanese Government, the so-called protocol and Agreed Views that were made under the protocol, was never submitted to the Senate and the Senate had expressly stated when it passed the NATO Status of Forces Agreement that that would not be oppressed into any further agreements.", "start": 3065.447, "stop": 3098.853, "duration": 33.41}, {"text": "Now, at least, they could have been done if it is the policy of the United States to strip our soldiers overseas of the benefits of the Uniform Code of Military Justice, the least they could have been done would have been to submit this so-called protocol to the Senate to see if they wanted to change their original mandate.", "start": 3098.853, "stop": 3117.097, "duration": 18.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, is it true that the protocol contains word for word the status of forces covenant of the NATO treaty?", "start": 3117.097, "stop": 3129.026, "duration": 11.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't know.", "start": 3129.026, "stop": 3130.84, "duration": 1.81}, {"text": "I think it's similar but I -- I don't --", "start": 3130.84, "stop": 3133.148, "duration": 2.31}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Exact isn't it --", "start": 3133.148, "stop": 3134.128, "duration": 0.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Isn't it (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 3134.128, "stop": 3134.557, "duration": 0.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't know.", "start": 3134.557, "stop": 3135.507, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- specifically?", "start": 3135.507, "stop": 3138.592, "duration": 3.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Carroll would take that up.", "start": 3138.592, "stop": 3139.868, "duration": 1.28}, {"text": "He -- he's probably more familiar.", "start": 3139.868, "stop": 3141.038, "duration": 1.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Robinson, before you -- just before you sit down, this morning at the opening of your argument, I understood you to say that the Solicitor General had made far joint false statements to this Court for the purpose of deceiving it and I understood you to say you would demonstrate that in your argument --", "start": 3141.038, "stop": 3165.073, "duration": 24.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 3165.073, "stop": 3165.194, "duration": 0.12}, {"text": "I -- I didn't say that.", "start": 3165.194, "stop": 3166.377, "duration": 1.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, I've -- I've listened for -- very attentively for bill in particulars along those lines but -- and, of course, if it's true, it should be said.", "start": 3166.377, "stop": 3175.783, "duration": 9.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I didn't say that.", "start": 3175.783, "stop": 3177.264, "duration": 1.48}, {"text": "If -- if my words were such, Your Honor, I -- I withdraw it.", "start": 3177.264, "stop": 3179.506, "duration": 2.24}, {"text": "I -- I would have intend to say anything of that nature.", "start": 3179.506, "stop": 3182.344, "duration": 2.84}, {"text": "(Voice Overlap) --", "start": 3182.344, "stop": 3182.355, "duration": 0.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "You said having to reflect upon the --", "start": 3182.355, "stop": 3184.505, "duration": 2.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No question about it.", "start": 3184.505, "stop": 3184.724, "duration": 0.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- integrity of the Solicitor General or the representation he was making for the Government.", "start": 3184.724, "stop": 3189.448, "duration": 4.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct, Your Honor.", "start": 3189.448, "stop": 3190.305, "duration": 0.86}, {"text": "Oh, no, there -- there was no intention to reflect on -- on the Solicitor General.", "start": 3190.305, "stop": 3193.688, "duration": 3.38}, {"text": "What I said, if I recall correctly, was that certain Senators and certain Congressmen in these congressional hearings have said in substance that the government witnesses, which appeared before us, gave testimony which was misleading and confusing both on law and on fact.", "start": 3193.688, "stop": 3211.395, "duration": 17.71}, {"text": "I think -- I think the record will bare that and I -- I made no --", "start": 3211.395, "stop": 3213.208, "duration": 1.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "If there is no representation by you --", "start": 3213.208, "stop": 3215.196, "duration": 1.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 3215.196, "stop": 3215.386, "duration": 0.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- I -- there's no use pursuing it further, but I was going to say, if there was any such impression intended by you that I think, in all fairness, you should give a bill of particulars at this time so we could --", "start": 3215.386, "stop": 3227.473, "duration": 12.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "If -- if even --", "start": 3227.473, "stop": 3227.509, "duration": 0.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- at least answer it.", "start": 3227.509, "stop": 3228.568, "duration": 1.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, if even there was such an inference, I offer my --", "start": 3228.568, "stop": 3230.618, "duration": 2.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, yes.", "start": 3230.618, "stop": 3230.916, "duration": 0.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- apologies to this Court and the Solicitor General --", "start": 3230.916, "stop": 3232.427, "duration": 1.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well --", "start": 3232.427, "stop": 3232.987, "duration": 0.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- because --", "start": 3232.987, "stop": 3233.093, "duration": 0.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "May be my -- it may have been --", "start": 3233.093, "stop": 3234.785, "duration": 1.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Something --", "start": 3234.785, "stop": 3235.024, "duration": 0.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- my mistake.", "start": 3235.024, "stop": 3235.196, "duration": 0.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- something may have been said in the heat of argument, certainly no such intention because I don't know that.", "start": 3235.196, "stop": 3239.785, "duration": 4.59}, {"text": "All -- all I know was what -- what the -- what certain Senators and Congressmen said in the record but I don't think there was any specific reference to Mr. Rankin as such.", "start": 3239.785, "stop": 3249.954, "duration": 10.17}, {"text": "And -- and I apologize for -- for conveying any such impression, the impression which Your Honor says was conveyed.", "start": 3249.954, "stop": 3256.097, "duration": 6.14}, {"text": "Thank you.", "start": 3256.097, "stop": 3264.635, "duration": 8.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Carroll, you may proceed.", "start": 3264.635, "stop": 3266.749, "duration": 2.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you.", "start": 3266.749, "stop": 3268.119, "duration": 1.37}, {"text": "Well, I see my time is a little more limited than I anticipated.", "start": 3268.119, "stop": 3271.693, "duration": 3.57}, {"text": "I will try to cover them all.", "start": 3271.693, "stop": 3273.191, "duration": 1.5}, {"text": "I think largely the argument has gotten a little off field of -- of the issues involved in this case, which to me appear to be very simple issues.", "start": 3273.191, "stop": 3285.94, "duration": 12.75}, {"text": "There are a couple of questions that I want to answer that I made notes about and I think perhaps before I get into the issues, I'd like to answer that last question that was asked having to do with the identity of language between the NATO agreement and this agreement.", "start": 3285.94, "stop": 3301.771, "duration": 15.83}, {"text": "Well, one of the big troubles in this case which has not been brought out has been this.", "start": 3301.771, "stop": 3307.211, "duration": 5.44}, {"text": "There -- substantially, the language is the same as to official duties, but the claim of the Japanese is based upon an alteration of the term \"official duties\" as altered in the so-called Agreed Views.", "start": 3307.211, "stop": 3325.908, "duration": 18.7}, {"text": "Now, if anybody ever heard of Agreed Views as a means of international law, well, they are way ahead of me, but in the hearing, before the subcommittee of the armed services and I think it's attached as an exhibit in this particular manner, Your Honors will find just what has happened on page 17.", "start": 3325.908, "stop": 3353.437, "duration": 27.53}, {"text": "I don't know whether that's before the Court and -- no, this is in the hearing of the subcommittee on armed services before the United States Senate.", "start": 3353.437, "stop": 3363.151, "duration": 9.71}, {"text": "Now, in these hearings on page --", "start": 3363.151, "stop": 3366.272, "duration": 3.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "You mean, on this -- on this matter?", "start": 3366.272, "stop": 3368.32, "duration": 2.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, on this matter, on --", "start": 3368.32, "stop": 3371.077, "duration": 2.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "The other day, before -- before two Senators, whoever they were, Senator Ervin and -- and --", "start": 3371.077, "stop": 3376.796, "duration": 5.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is correct, sir.", "start": 3376.796, "stop": 3377.526, "duration": 0.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 3377.526, "stop": 3378.552, "duration": 1.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, Mr. Dechert from the Defense Department outlines in that, the entire history of the documents involved.", "start": 3378.552, "stop": 3387.895, "duration": 9.34}, {"text": "Now, these documents as it's outlined in our brief are -- are as follows.", "start": 3387.895, "stop": 3392.661, "duration": 4.77}, {"text": "The -- the Peace Treaty, the Multi-lateral Peace Treaty, then the Security Treaty, then the Administrative Agreement, then the protocol, then some minutes, which were the result of the hearings at the time that the protocol was entered into and then, some Agreed Views.", "start": 3392.661, "stop": 3414, "duration": 21.34}, {"text": "Now, these Agreed Views are the views of the representatives of -- of Japan and ourselves under Article XVI of the Administrative Agreement which calls for the appointing appointment of a Joint Committee and the language is, “The Joint Committee shall be established as a means for consultation between the United States and Japan in all matters requiring mutual consultation regarding the implementation of this agreement.", "start": 3414, "stop": 3441.248, "duration": 27.25}, {"text": "In particular, the Joint Committee shall serve as the means for consultation and determine the facilities and areas of Japan, which are required for the use of the United States in carrying out the purpose stated in Article I of the Security Treaty.”", "start": 3441.248, "stop": 3452.624, "duration": 11.38}, {"text": "Then number two, “The Joint Committee shall be composed of a representative of the United States and Japan, each of whom shall have one or more deputies and staff.", "start": 3452.624, "stop": 3461.925, "duration": 9.3}, {"text": "The Joint Committee shall be so organized that it shall meet immediately at any time at the request of the representative of either the United States or Japan.”", "start": 3461.925, "stop": 3471.04, "duration": 9.11}, {"text": "Now, this Joint Committee got up some agreed minutes and on page 18 of this report or some Agreed Views rather.", "start": 3471.04, "stop": 3480.396, "duration": 9.36}, {"text": "Agreed View Number 39 is the basis of the Japanese claim that this was not in the -- in a -- that this act was not in accord with official duty.", "start": 3480.396, "stop": 3491.212, "duration": 10.82}, {"text": "Now, it falls squarely within a definition of official duty as defined in the protocol and in the NATO agreements, but that official -- that definition has been changed by this Agreed View Number 39, which reads --", "start": 3491.212, "stop": 3508.323, "duration": 17.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is there any --", "start": 3508.323, "stop": 3508.46, "duration": 0.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- as follows.", "start": 3508.46, "stop": 3509.078, "duration": 0.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- is there any definition in the Administrative Agreement or in the NATO Agreement as to what official duty is?", "start": 3509.078, "stop": 3516.534, "duration": 7.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 3516.534, "stop": 3516.942, "duration": 0.41}, {"text": "They --", "start": 3516.942, "stop": 3517.264, "duration": 0.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Then, how can it -- how can it contradict what's -- what's not defined?", "start": 3517.264, "stop": 3520.674, "duration": 3.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, if I read the language to you, Your Honor, I think you'll see how it changes the ordinary accepted meaning of official duty.", "start": 3520.674, "stop": 3527.082, "duration": 6.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I --", "start": 3527.082, "stop": 3528.476, "duration": 1.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "May I -- may I read --", "start": 3528.476, "stop": 3529.036, "duration": 0.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I mean I would like to renew my question.", "start": 3529.036, "stop": 3531.394, "duration": 2.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, may I read the --", "start": 3531.394, "stop": 3531.821, "duration": 0.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Voice Overlap) --", "start": 3531.821, "stop": 3532.298, "duration": 0.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- the language -- I think it answers your question.", "start": 3532.298, "stop": 3534.402, "duration": 2.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Will you please -- let me put my question.", "start": 3534.402, "stop": 3537.623, "duration": 3.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes -- yes, sir, excuse me.", "start": 3537.623, "stop": 3538.356, "duration": 0.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I asked whether official duty was defined by the underlying documents and you say no.", "start": 3538.356, "stop": 3544.916, "duration": 6.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, the language --", "start": 3544.916, "stop": 3546.01, "duration": 1.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Has it been defined?", "start": 3546.01, "stop": 3548.27, "duration": 2.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, the -- not -- not other than in the language that it -- it stated here in the -- in the protocol which official duty --", "start": 3548.27, "stop": 3556.606, "duration": 8.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Does -- does it define it there?", "start": 3556.606, "stop": 3558.419, "duration": 1.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, its -- it -- I'll give you the exact phrase if you call out that definition.", "start": 3558.419, "stop": 3571.916, "duration": 13.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "Its set forth on page 25A of the Government's brief.", "start": 3571.916, "stop": 3575.395, "duration": 3.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Offenses in -- in two, on 25A, offenses arising out of any act or omission done in the performance of official duty.", "start": 3575.395, "stop": 3586.324, "duration": 10.93}, {"text": "Now, that's the --", "start": 3586.324, "stop": 3588.5, "duration": 2.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Where is that?", "start": 3588.5, "stop": 3589.109, "duration": 0.61}, {"text": "What -- where is that from?", "start": 3589.109, "stop": 3590.656, "duration": 1.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's from the protocol.", "start": 3590.656, "stop": 3593.036, "duration": 2.38}, {"text": "That's the amendment to the -- that is the amendment to the -- the Administrative Agreement.", "start": 3593.036, "stop": 3600.492, "duration": 7.46}, {"text": "Now, that's the language there.", "start": 3600.492, "stop": 3601.808, "duration": 1.32}, {"text": "Now, note what they have done to change that language and it's based upon this change that they claim the right to have a -- a draw deliberate demand.", "start": 3601.808, "stop": 3613.041, "duration": 11.23}, {"text": "The term official duty as referred to in paragraph 3 (a) (2) of the protocol and official minutes relating thereto is understood to be any duty or service required or authorized to be done by statute, regulation, the order of -- of a superior or a military usage --", "start": 3613.041, "stop": 3635.304, "duration": 22.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'll renew --", "start": 3635.304, "stop": 3635.455, "duration": 0.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- a military usage.", "start": 3635.455, "stop": 3635.818, "duration": 0.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- my question to you.", "start": 3635.818, "stop": 3637.062, "duration": 1.24}, {"text": "Does -- is there anything in the protocol that defined the phrase in the performance of official duty?", "start": 3637.062, "stop": 3643.848, "duration": 6.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 3643.848, "stop": 3644.184, "duration": 0.34}, {"text": "I think that (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 3644.184, "stop": 3645.005, "duration": 0.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Very well then.", "start": 3645.005, "stop": 3645.686, "duration": 0.68}, {"text": "Then -- then what you're saying, if I understand you, is that the phrase in the performance of official duty as such technical define closed meaning that the protocol elaboration of it is in defiance of it.", "start": 3645.686, "stop": 3659.544, "duration": 13.86}, {"text": "Is that what you're saying?", "start": 3659.544, "stop": 3659.97, "duration": 0.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is correct.", "start": 3659.97, "stop": 3661.794, "duration": 1.82}, {"text": "I say that --", "start": 3661.794, "stop": 3662.652, "duration": 0.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But it doesn't --", "start": 3662.652, "stop": 3662.885, "duration": 0.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- I say official --", "start": 3662.885, "stop": 3663.561, "duration": 0.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- it doesn't contradict it unless you say official duty is so self-defining that the Committee can't define it more particularly.", "start": 3663.561, "stop": 3671.431, "duration": 7.87}, {"text": "Is that what you're saying?", "start": 3671.431, "stop": 3672, "duration": 0.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is what I'm saying, under our standards of official duty, under -- and recognized in our military service, I think the definition is very clear.", "start": 3672, "stop": 3679.422, "duration": 7.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "You mean I can go to some book where I can find -- where I can find the definition of official duty that will satisfy every lawyer and every judge, is that right?", "start": 3679.422, "stop": 3687.576, "duration": 8.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I think you can, sir.", "start": 3687.576, "stop": 3688.821, "duration": 1.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I can find hundreds of cases which there are conflict of application of that phrase.", "start": 3688.821, "stop": 3692.714, "duration": 3.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I don't doubt that there's a conflict of its application, but there is a definition --", "start": 3692.714, "stop": 3695.252, "duration": 2.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, then, can this Committee -- can't this Committee then-- being an agency for taking care of conflicts define more particularly what is generally defined?", "start": 3695.252, "stop": 3705.304, "duration": 10.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't think so when they restrict the definition to say that official duty means something that a man is specifically told to do.", "start": 3705.304, "stop": 3714.836, "duration": 9.53}, {"text": "I don't think that's the common ordinary meaning of the term official duty.", "start": 3714.836, "stop": 3719.372, "duration": 4.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you think we ought independently here, as though we were sitting at a -- at a trial court charging a jury, define what official duty means?", "start": 3719.372, "stop": 3728.616, "duration": 9.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think as a matter of law, you have to recognize the language and the common -- the common understanding of that language and I think that's one of the very issues of this case.", "start": 3728.616, "stop": 3738.572, "duration": 9.96}, {"text": "This -- this language to an American and to an American soldier in particular has a definite meaning.", "start": 3738.572, "stop": 3746.049, "duration": 7.48}, {"text": "To the Japanese, it doesn't have a -- has -- have a definite meaning.", "start": 3746.049, "stop": 3750.319, "duration": 4.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But as I understand you, this was an agreed meaning between American --", "start": 3750.319, "stop": 3753.443, "duration": 3.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh.", "start": 3753.443, "stop": 3753.882, "duration": 0.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- than Japanese.", "start": 3753.882, "stop": 3754.297, "duration": 0.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "But by who, the Joint Committee or some -- subordinate Japanese clerk and some subordinate American clerk, who in this Joint Committee or one of its subcommittees has the right to make a definition that has the effect of law.", "start": 3754.297, "stop": 3768.456, "duration": 14.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Carroll, it is agreed by the Solicitor General.", "start": 3768.456, "stop": 3772.508, "duration": 4.05}, {"text": "It is agreed that the position of this Government is that this man was on official duty.", "start": 3772.508, "stop": 3779.474, "duration": 6.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 3779.474, "stop": 3780.238, "duration": 0.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Therefore, they agree with you that this was within the most technical definition that you can give to official duty and, nevertheless, this Government exercised its duty or its right of waiver.", "start": 3780.238, "stop": 3791.373, "duration": 11.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm only pointing out, Your Honor, that the claim of the Japanese to him is on this basis of this amended interpretation.", "start": 3791.373, "stop": 3796.58, "duration": 5.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But that doesn't matter if this Government concedes your point and says, “Nevertheless, it has authority.”", "start": 3796.58, "stop": 3801.105, "duration": 4.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "What you say is true.", "start": 3801.105, "stop": 3803.031, "duration": 1.93}, {"text": "Now, I want to point out one other thing about --", "start": 3803.031, "stop": 3804.827, "duration": 1.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Carroll, may I ask -- may I ask this?", "start": 3804.827, "stop": 3807.212, "duration": 2.38}, {"text": "What pertinence does this document quoted on page 37A of the Government's brief have?", "start": 3807.212, "stop": 3816.391, "duration": 9.18}, {"text": "It's on stationary of the United States Army Forces Far East and United States Army Administration and Military Justice and related matters.", "start": 3816.391, "stop": 3825.333, "duration": 8.94}, {"text": "Now, that purports to -- to define what a line of duty means, does it not?", "start": 3825.333, "stop": 3833.307, "duration": 7.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "It -- it does.", "start": 3833.307, "stop": 3834.037, "duration": 0.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "And that -- is that by the -- come from headquarters of the -- of our army in -- in Japan?", "start": 3834.037, "stop": 3842.907, "duration": 8.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I -- apparently, it does.", "start": 3842.907, "stop": 3845.105, "duration": 2.2}, {"text": "I -- I don't know the source of it.", "start": 3845.105, "stop": 3846.414, "duration": 1.31}, {"text": "They -- from this document, it says, “United States Armed -- Army Forces, Far Eastern Inc., United States Army (Rear), Circular 22-1.”", "start": 3846.414, "stop": 3855.442, "duration": 9.03}, {"text": "Now, I -- I don't know the authority for the publication of this or who published it, but apparently, those two headquarters are responsible for its promulgation.", "start": 3855.442, "stop": 3864.629, "duration": 9.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "It says the term official duty is used in Article XVII, the Official Minutes and the Agreed Views is not meant to include all acts by members of the armed forces and civilian component during periods violated on duty, but is meant to apply only to acts which are required to be done as a function of those duties which the individuals are performing.", "start": 3864.629, "stop": 3889.648, "duration": 25.02}, {"text": "Thus, a substantial departure from the acts a person is required to perform in a particular duty usually will indicate an act outside of his “official duty”.", "start": 3889.648, "stop": 3901.163, "duration": 11.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think --", "start": 3901.163, "stop": 3901.548, "duration": 0.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, was that the official document for the Government of the armed forces in Japan or not?", "start": 3901.548, "stop": 3907.98, "duration": 6.43}, {"text": "I don't --", "start": 3907.98, "stop": 3908.411, "duration": 0.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I --", "start": 3908.411, "stop": 3908.593, "duration": 0.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- I don't (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 3908.593, "stop": 3908.804, "duration": 0.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- think Your Honors put your finger upon exactly what I'm saying.", "start": 3908.804, "stop": 3911.953, "duration": 3.15}, {"text": "This document is published apparently by the army in order to conform with these so-called Agreed Views, the definition of official duty.", "start": 3911.953, "stop": 3923.545, "duration": 11.59}, {"text": "In other words, it's much more restrict than the ordinary understanding of the word official duties.", "start": 3923.545, "stop": 3931.463, "duration": 7.92}, {"text": "That phrase as it is generally understood is much broader than this and apparently, Your Honor, I -- I can only -- only speak from seeing the date of this which is the 24th of January, 1956.", "start": 3931.463, "stop": 3943.092, "duration": 11.63}, {"text": "Apparently, they on -- having in mind this restricted definition of official duties under the Agreed Views has then promulgated this to -- for the army to conform with this restricted definition, but my -- our point is --", "start": 3943.092, "stop": 3961.225, "duration": 18.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Suppose that's correct.", "start": 3961.225, "stop": 3963.504, "duration": 2.28}, {"text": "The Government must agree and stipulate it that this man was accurate.", "start": 3963.504, "stop": 3968.744, "duration": 5.24}, {"text": "I mean the official duty has resumed within the meaning of this definition.", "start": 3968.744, "stop": 3973.403, "duration": 4.66}, {"text": "The definition is it would not be official duty if he had deviated from -- from his job --", "start": 3973.403, "stop": 3979.172, "duration": 5.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "From that viewpoint, of course, we are better off.", "start": 3979.172, "stop": 3981.219, "duration": 2.05}, {"text": "Your -- Your Honor is correct and that's the respecting terms.", "start": 3981.219, "stop": 3983.286, "duration": 2.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "In other words, they have stipulated that's the official duty in connection with the meaning which the army has given it.", "start": 3983.286, "stop": 3988.774, "duration": 5.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "They're -- they're bound by that stipulation but I'm pointing out something else.", "start": 3988.774, "stop": 3993.267, "duration": 4.49}, {"text": "The reason I pointed that out was an answer to your question, Your Honor, as to whether or not the language was identical between the NATO treaties and these treaties.", "start": 3993.267, "stop": 4001.381, "duration": 8.11}, {"text": "There is this further restriction on official duties.", "start": 4001.381, "stop": 4004.409, "duration": 3.03}, {"text": "The official duty phrase in the NATO Agreements has not been so restricted as it has been here.", "start": 4004.409, "stop": 4012.249, "duration": 7.84}, {"text": "That was the reason I brought that matter out but I agree with you Mr. Justice Black that that's the -- that's the effect of the stipulation upon the part of the Government.", "start": 4012.249, "stop": 4024.085, "duration": 11.84}, {"text": "They have stipulated as to the much more narrow viewpoint because they've stipulated as to their interpretation of official duties.", "start": 4024.085, "stop": 4032.104, "duration": 8.02}, {"text": "Now, we have in this case a very substantial question of -- of jurisdiction and that comes about in connection with this Camp Weir.", "start": 4032.104, "stop": 4042.082, "duration": 9.98}, {"text": "Now, this Camp Weir, if Your Honors will turn to the brief of the appellee in the appendix on page 40A and 41A over to 42A, we have here an affidavit of this -- of Robert Dechert who is General Counsel of the Department of Defense and he tells us here that this was used, this is property that was used by the Japanese army during World War II, and he tells us that we seized at any states and it was seized by our forces on April the 11th, 1946.", "start": 4042.082, "stop": 4080.634, "duration": 38.55}, {"text": "It's been held by our forces and then used by them as an army base.", "start": 4080.634, "stop": 4086.752, "duration": 6.12}, {"text": "And then, he goes on to tell us that the facilities and areas, the use of which is to be granted by Japan to the United States of America in accordance with paragraph (1) of Article II of the Administrative Agreement signed at Tokyo includes this particular property.", "start": 4086.752, "stop": 4105.069, "duration": 18.32}, {"text": "And I want to call your attention to paragraph (2) on page 41A.", "start": 4105.069, "stop": 4110.819, "duration": 5.75}, {"text": "It is confirmed that the facilities or areas indicated pending in the schedule refer to those facilities or areas, the continued use of which is to be granted to the United States in accordance with the notes exchanged between Mr. Katsuo Okazaki, Minister of the State of Japan and Mr. Dean Rusk, special representative of the President.", "start": 4110.819, "stop": 4133.743, "duration": 22.92}, {"text": "Then, they named the camp and gave you the number and they say on the following page under that same paragraph, the notes exchanged between Mr. Rusk and Mr. Okazaki referred to in the agreement quoted above provided that facilities and areas used by the United States prior to the date of the Administrative Agreement would continue to be used on the same basis as used theretofore until a formal agreement was reached on such facilities or areas or until such facilities or areas were released by the United States.", "start": 4133.743, "stop": 4168.465, "duration": 34.72}, {"text": "Now, we have -- we have to have in mind that theretofore this area was used by the United States with exclusive jurisdiction over that area.", "start": 4168.465, "stop": 4178.872, "duration": 10.41}, {"text": "And here, they have contracted to give us the continued use of this on the same basis as we previously have the use of this particular maneuvering camp area and -- and -- well, I don't want to take issue with the Solicitor General, I want to call the attention of the Court to the facts stated herein that this property was exclusively under the jurisdiction and granted exclusively to the United States.", "start": 4178.872, "stop": 4214.335, "duration": 35.46}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is that by virtue of the Administrative Agreement?", "start": 4214.335, "stop": 4216.788, "duration": 2.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "By virtue of -- but -- not by virtue of the Administrative Agreement alone but by virtue of the contract that we entered into for the use of these properties if you will read further in this agreement.", "start": 4216.788, "stop": 4231.518, "duration": 14.73}, {"text": "It says, “No formal agreement has ever been reached on Camp Weir maneuver area because the Japanese and United States representatives of the Joint Committee have not been able to reach an agreement on the exact boundaries of the area.”", "start": 4231.518, "stop": 4244.502, "duration": 12.98}, {"text": "The dispute over boundaries arises principally from the Japanese demand that areas encroached upon by local farmers to be released from the maneuver area.", "start": 4244.502, "stop": 4252.725, "duration": 8.22}, {"text": "At sometime late 1951 or early 1952, the United States agreed to permit the National Safety Police which later became the Japanese Self-Defense Force to use certain portions of -- of Camp Weir maneuver area for an artillery and army school.", "start": 4252.725, "stop": 4272.677, "duration": 19.95}, {"text": "This agreement provided that the National Safety Police would be required to vacate the premises on 60 days notice by the United States.", "start": 4272.677, "stop": 4281.371, "duration": 8.69}, {"text": "A new agreement containing the same 60-day vacate notice provision was effected on March 30th, 1954.", "start": 4281.371, "stop": 4289.112, "duration": 7.74}, {"text": "This agreement was terminated, effective October 15th, 1954 by notice -- by giving notice to vacate on August 12, 1954, and I skip to the last sentence, at the time of the Girard incident, the area was being used solely by the United States forces.", "start": 4289.112, "stop": 4306.359, "duration": 17.25}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Insofar as criminal jurisdiction is concerned over that area, it was subject to the terms of the Administrative Agreement and later of the protocol, isn't it?", "start": 4306.359, "stop": 4316.13, "duration": 9.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't think -- well, I -- yes, it was subject to --", "start": 4316.13, "stop": 4318.852, "duration": 2.72}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "There's no --", "start": 4318.852, "stop": 4319.206, "duration": 0.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- the terms of the --", "start": 4319.206, "stop": 4319.628, "duration": 0.42}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- dependent source of criminal jurisdiction with reference to this particular area other than the agreements that we've been discussing all day, isn't that right?", "start": 4319.628, "stop": 4328.092, "duration": 8.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is correct, but you see, these -- these agreements, if I can use the term, are very weasel-worded to say the least.", "start": 4328.092, "stop": 4337.469, "duration": 9.38}, {"text": "It's very difficult to -- to know exactly what they mean until you go into them in -- in some detail.", "start": 4337.469, "stop": 4345.493, "duration": 8.02}, {"text": "Now, let's take the Security Treaty, the Security Treaty in connection and prior to this particular camp, the Security Treaty language states that Japan -- there is danger to -- in Japan -- in Japan in this situation and Japan desires a Security Treaty with the United States.", "start": 4345.493, "stop": 4370.652, "duration": 25.16}, {"text": "Japan desires as a provisional arrangement for its defense that the United States of America should maintain the armed forces of its own in and about Japan so as to deter on the attacks upon Japan.", "start": 4370.652, "stop": 4381.03, "duration": 10.38}, {"text": "And then on Article I, Japan grants and the United States of America accepts the right upon the coming into force of the treaty of peace and of this Treaty to dispose United States land, air and sea forces in and about Japan.", "start": 4381.03, "stop": 4394.227, "duration": 13.2}, {"text": "Well, that's as far as the Treaty goes.", "start": 4394.227, "stop": 4396.43, "duration": 2.2}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "All I --", "start": 4396.43, "stop": 4396.552, "duration": 0.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "There, we --", "start": 4396.552, "stop": 4396.999, "duration": 0.45}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- all I was trying to get at was to make sure that I understood it correctly.", "start": 4396.999, "stop": 4402.212, "duration": 5.21}, {"text": "You're not advanced are you in your argument as to criminal jurisdiction by the -- what you read from the arrangements covering this area beyond what you have to stand on or assert under the other agreements as to jurisdiction.", "start": 4402.212, "stop": 4420.432, "duration": 18.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh, no sir, because there is a rule of law and it comes under this principle of uti possidetis.", "start": 4420.432, "stop": 4428.034, "duration": 7.6}, {"text": "Now, that principle of law is applicable in this particular case where we had an -- where you have an area of land and the authority of international law here is very clear, which I'll cite to the Court, where you have an area within another country and in -- you exercise jurisdiction -- exclusive jurisdiction over that area at the time of the peace treaty.", "start": 4428.034, "stop": 4452.433, "duration": 24.4}, {"text": "If the peace treaty doesn't make a contrary provision as to that area, then you continue to exercise that jurisdiction and the other country has waived its right to reassert jurisdiction over that particular area.", "start": 4452.433, "stop": 4466.244, "duration": 13.81}, {"text": "Well, that's a rule of international law that falls under this doctrine of uti possidetis and the authorities for that, I -- I will just briefly submit to the Court, the -- and -- and we -- I just don't have time to differentiate this from the things that you surrender as the Military Act, but by the principle, and this is whole on international law, the Seventh Edition, 599, by the principle commonly called uti possidetis is understood that the simple conclusion of peace, if no expressed stipulation accompanies it or insofar as expressed stipulations do not extend this and the two belligerence as absolute property, whatever they respectively have had under their actual control in the case of territory and things attached to it in the -- and in the case of (Inaudible), whatever they have in their legal possession at the moment, occupied territory, for example, is transferred to the occupying power.", "start": 4466.244, "stop": 4528.888, "duration": 62.64}, {"text": "Now, the cases on it are a legion.", "start": 4528.888, "stop": 4530.601, "duration": 1.71}, {"text": "There's a number of cases and I understand from the Chief Justice, we can submit these in a memoranda and I will submit the authorities on that point.", "start": 4530.601, "stop": 4538.922, "duration": 8.32}, {"text": "And I want to call your attention --", "start": 4538.922, "stop": 4540.114, "duration": 1.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Are those cases that they deal with jurisdiction?", "start": 4540.114, "stop": 4543.271, "duration": 3.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Their cases which deal with the --", "start": 4543.271, "stop": 4545.417, "duration": 2.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Suppose questions of (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 4545.417, "stop": 4546.899, "duration": 1.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- retaining the same rights.", "start": 4546.899, "stop": 4548.778, "duration": 1.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- because I know rights is the most -- the most traitorous of all.", "start": 4548.778, "stop": 4551.924, "duration": 3.15}, {"text": "What do you mean by the same rights?", "start": 4551.924, "stop": 4553.624, "duration": 1.7}, {"text": "I want to know whether these are cases in which an -- in the first place, these are -- when you say a treaty of peace, these are an occupying -- an occupying country or a conquering country has criminal jurisdiction after the treaty of peace of crimes committed on the -- on part of a territory of the defeated belligerent on the soil of which it happens to have soldiers, any of those cases of that sort?", "start": 4553.624, "stop": 4582.798, "duration": 29.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I thought -- no, not -- not in -- specially dealing with criminal jurisdiction, but --", "start": 4582.798, "stop": 4589.058, "duration": 6.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's what we're dealing with here.", "start": 4589.058, "stop": 4590.754, "duration": 1.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, I understand that, but the general rule of law is that if you occupy this particular area and you occupy it with exclusive jurisdiction that condition continues.", "start": 4590.754, "stop": 4602.143, "duration": 11.39}, {"text": "All that -- all that the doctrine uti possidetis does is -- is to continue the -- the matter in the same status of which it was at the time of the conclusion of peace.", "start": 4602.143, "stop": 4611.65, "duration": 9.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "This -- the agreement which you read from Mr. Dechert's affidavit shows that they have to make an arrangement toward it.", "start": 4611.65, "stop": 4617.122, "duration": 5.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, whether (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 4617.122, "stop": 4617.997, "duration": 0.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "So that they can keep something they had but they got something they didn't have.", "start": 4617.997, "stop": 4621.19, "duration": 3.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, let's just take a look at the -- at the peace treaty now or rather the -- the Administrative Agreement and see just where -- how this falls within the -- the terms of it.", "start": 4621.19, "stop": 4632.787, "duration": 11.6}, {"text": "I think it's on page -- I think it's on Article III, this one.", "start": 4632.787, "stop": 4652.02, "duration": 19.23}, {"text": "Now, on Article III, let's -- on the Administrative Agreement on Article II, first, Japan agrees to grant the United States the use of the facilities and areas necessary to carry out the purpose stated in Article I of the Security Treaty.", "start": 4652.02, "stop": 4666.01, "duration": 13.99}, {"text": "In Article III, (1), which is the only one that's printed on page 16A of the brief of the brief -- of the -- of the Government, the United States shall have the rights, power and authority within the facilities and areas which are necessary or appropriate for their establishment use, operation, defense or control.", "start": 4666.01, "stop": 4688.336, "duration": 22.33}, {"text": "Now, here in the Administrative Agreement is a specific declaration in Article III of the rights, power and authority of the United States over the particular areas.", "start": 4688.336, "stop": 4699.864, "duration": 11.53}, {"text": "Here's an area which we had full authority over.", "start": 4699.864, "stop": 4702.961, "duration": 3.1}, {"text": "Here's an area that's transferred to us.", "start": 4702.961, "stop": 4705.014, "duration": 2.05}, {"text": "We're continuing in its possession and here's Article III of the -- of the Administrative Agreement, specifically recognizing that we shall have the rights, power and authority within the facilities and areas which are necessary or appropriate for their establishment, use, operation, defense or control.", "start": 4705.014, "stop": 4725.323, "duration": 20.31}, {"text": "In other words, this article distinguishes a difference -- different situation from offenses, which might be committed outside of those areas.", "start": 4725.323, "stop": 4734.53, "duration": 9.21}, {"text": "In -- it says that we shall have all the necessary powers.", "start": 4734.53, "stop": 4737.463, "duration": 2.93}, {"text": "Now, we considered it necessary to have on our military bases all over the world full jurisdiction and I -- I feel that Article III brings -- is a specific recognition of the acceptance of a condition which -- which had previously existed on this particular area and that it recognizes that we have exclusive jurisdiction insofar as that area is concerned or any other area that was similarly occupied.", "start": 4737.463, "stop": 4769.654, "duration": 32.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Although the Administrative Agreement carrying out a treaty brought to the knowledge of the Senate could be opposite.", "start": 4769.654, "stop": 4775.765, "duration": 6.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, the Administrative Agreement does not say the opposite.", "start": 4775.765, "stop": 4778.863, "duration": 3.1}, {"text": "I'm -- I'm reading from the --", "start": 4778.863, "stop": 4779.823, "duration": 0.96}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "It makes arrangement for determining when there is conflict who should see what right he have.", "start": 4779.823, "stop": 4785.685, "duration": 5.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't think that was ever within the contemplation of the Administrative Agreement because Article XVI reads as follows, “It is the duty of members of the United States armed forces, the civilian component and their defendants to -- to respect the law of Japan and to abstain from any activity inconsistent with the spirit of this agreement and in particular, from any political activity in Japan.”", "start": 4785.685, "stop": 4812.712, "duration": 27.03}, {"text": "Now, it only says there, it is the duty of the members of the United States armed forces.", "start": 4812.712, "stop": 4817.86, "duration": 5.15}, {"text": "You must remember that this agreement went beyond, if I may finish the sentence, went beyond the --", "start": 4817.86, "stop": 4825.506, "duration": 7.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "You have five -- you have five minutes more.", "start": 4825.506, "stop": 4827.86, "duration": 2.35}, {"text": "It's the red light.", "start": 4827.86, "stop": 4828.848, "duration": 0.99}, {"text": "That is --", "start": 4828.848, "stop": 4829.06, "duration": 0.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, sir.", "start": 4829.06, "stop": 4829.169, "duration": 0.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- the end of your time Mr. --", "start": 4829.169, "stop": 4830.548, "duration": 1.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "This -- this agreement went beyond the NATO Agreements.", "start": 4830.548, "stop": 4834.875, "duration": 4.33}, {"text": "This went to a civilian component.", "start": 4834.875, "stop": 4841.541, "duration": 6.67}, {"text": "This agreement went to a civilian the components.", "start": 4841.541, "stop": 4844.368, "duration": 2.83}, {"text": "It -- it gave exclusive jurisdiction to the United States not only to our armed forces but to civilian components and to defendants and the only defendants that excluded were Japanese defendants.", "start": 4844.368, "stop": 4856.231, "duration": 11.86}, {"text": "Then, the question that was asked a short time ago about the fact that it said that such jurisdiction may in any case be waived by the United States was included in here, but who is here to say whether or not such jurisdiction may in any case be waived by the United States applied to the soldier and of the -- of this matter or was intended to apply to the much broader group that was encompassed in the group classified as having or which we had exclusive jurisdiction.", "start": 4856.231, "stop": 4893.68, "duration": 37.45}, {"text": "In other words, that provision for waiver may well have gone to any -- one of our civilians or one of our soldiers who was injured out on the streets or some place.", "start": 4893.68, "stop": 4904.562, "duration": 10.88}, {"text": "But in this case, you have to remember, he was a soldier on duty, assigned to guard duty on an area which had been under our exclusive jurisdiction, on an area which we say under international law we -- we retained exclusive jurisdiction who if he didn't carry out his guard duty was subject to courts-martial and who in carrying out his guard duty as stipulated to by the prosecution accidentally injured this woman or killed this woman.", "start": 4904.562, "stop": 4934.455, "duration": 29.89}, {"text": "Now, how can we possibly turn a soldier who has carried out his duty under the penalty of a criminal prosecution by our own country to turn him over to a foreign country for trial?", "start": 4934.455, "stop": 4947.094, "duration": 12.64}, {"text": "The answer to it is going to be very simple.", "start": 4947.094, "stop": 4949.219, "duration": 2.13}, {"text": "If one of the members of the State Department turns to a marine guard in the future who is guarding while an angry mob is charging down into one of our embassies and he says to him, ”Shoot them when they come over to threshold.”", "start": 4949.219, "stop": 4961.502, "duration": 12.28}, {"text": "The marine is going to say, “Here, shoot him yourself mister, I don't want to be tried.”[Laughs].", "start": 4961.502, "stop": 4967.1, "duration": 5.6}, {"text": "That's going to be the answer and it will destroy the entire morale of our -- of our whole military service.", "start": 4967.1, "stop": 4972.928, "duration": 5.83}, {"text": "If we order this man to do -- to -- to do an act and he does it in the performance of his duty, he is entitled to have our country deterred, whether or not that was the proper performance of his duty.", "start": 4972.928, "stop": 4985.742, "duration": 12.81}, {"text": "And I want to just call one more thing to your attention, the assistant -- one of the Assistant Judge Advocate Generals went to Japan and was asked the question by the newspapers or any court-martial proceedings have been brought against Girard and his answer was that so far there was no indication as to any reason for him being tried by courts-martial and that's the nub of this whole case.", "start": 4985.742, "stop": 5013.924, "duration": 28.18}, {"text": "Girard was in the performance of his official duty.", "start": 5013.924, "stop": 5017.294, "duration": 3.37}, {"text": "The army decided not to try him.", "start": 5017.294, "stop": 5019.526, "duration": 2.23}, {"text": "The Japanese set up a clamor to try him because they don't agree with our definition of -- of official duty.", "start": 5019.526, "stop": 5025.948, "duration": 6.42}, {"text": "And so, we are now said -- we are now told, “You must turn Girard over to the Japanese because the Japanese don't -- do not agree with our definition of official duty.", "start": 5025.948, "stop": 5037.658, "duration": 11.71}, {"text": "And if you do this, it will destroy the morale of the armed services of this country probably forever.”", "start": 5037.658, "stop": 5045.626, "duration": 7.97}, {"text": "Now, that's the -- that's the answer to it.", "start": 5045.626, "stop": 5047.178, "duration": 1.55}, {"text": "It's just that simple and I thank you very much for the -- for the time that I've taken before this Court.", "start": 5047.178, "stop": 5053.832, "duration": 6.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's all right.", "start": 5053.832, "stop": 5054.287, "duration": 0.45}, {"text": "Mr. Carroll, on submission of your authorities, it won't be necessary for you to write any brief or to quote for many of your authorities if you can just submit to us by tomorrow morning a list of these authorities that you've relied on here in the argument and you may do it, of course, by -- in typewritten form.", "start": 5054.287, "stop": 5072.469, "duration": 18.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Your Honor.", "start": 5072.469, "stop": 5073.036, "duration": 0.57}, {"text": "It will be done.", "start": 5073.036, "stop": 5076.29, "duration": 3.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Solicitor General.", "start": 5076.29, "stop": 5077.981, "duration": 1.69}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "May it please the Court.", "start": 5077.981, "stop": 5088.283, "duration": 10.3}, {"text": "First, I would like to make it very clear the position of the United States Government regarding to the treaty of peace with Japan.", "start": 5088.283, "stop": 5097.383, "duration": 9.1}, {"text": "It's on 5A of the Government's brief and in that treaty in Article I, Chapter 1, subparagraph (b), the United States Government and the allied powers recognized the full sovereignty of the Japanese people over Japan and its territorial waters.", "start": 5097.383, "stop": 5126.608, "duration": 29.23}, {"text": "In that Act or in that same Treaty, we agreed that we would withdraw our forces within 90 days, so that we recognize the complete sovereignty of Japan the moment that Treaty was signed and ratified to all of Japan and its territorial waters and we don't claim any impingement upon that agreement whatsoever.", "start": 5126.608, "stop": 5158.555, "duration": 31.95}, {"text": "Now, we did agree within 90 days, we would withdraw our forces and then we had the Security Treaty, which permitted us to leave forces under the terms of that Treaty order.", "start": 5158.555, "stop": 5172.31, "duration": 13.76}, {"text": "If we didn't have that Treaty, we wouldn't have been permitted to leave those forces under the terms of that agreement and then, the Administrative Agreement that was made under which provided in greater detail.", "start": 5172.31, "stop": 5189.342, "duration": 17.03}, {"text": "Next, I'd like to turn to the case, the Canadian case that was referred to and is reported in 4 Dominion Law Reports at page 11.", "start": 5189.342, "stop": 5207.967, "duration": 18.63}, {"text": "It was a decision by the Supreme Court of Canada in the nature of an advisory opinion, this Court was not rendered, but the Court did not accept the position advocated by the United States in the brief that it tendered to the Court.", "start": 5207.967, "stop": 5228.772, "duration": 20.81}, {"text": "There was a divided Court and the decision was three to two against the position of the Government.", "start": 5228.772, "stop": 5238.344, "duration": 9.57}, {"text": "I'd like to just briefly read the syllabi of the Court because it shows the thinking of the Court and if the Court -- if this Court cares to go into it, you will find a number of authorities that the Government deals with and the position that the Canadian Court took and what it relied on, how it examined this entire subject and felt that the whole idea of immunity of foreign force was an imposition or a reduction of the sovereignty in contrary to the idea of control of such matters and prosecution for criminal offenses by the country in which the -- such forces were located.", "start": 5238.344, "stop": 5284.938, "duration": 46.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Solicitor, in the -- I have the other form of the report and I do not notice in the appearances that United States appeared before the Supreme Court of Canada.", "start": 5284.938, "stop": 5297.687, "duration": 12.75}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I have been advised there wasn't any formal appearance at all but the United States submitted a memorandum and --", "start": 5297.687, "stop": 5305.772, "duration": 8.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "One or two, three, four, five, six appearances for different parties --", "start": 5305.772, "stop": 5309.368, "duration": 3.6}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 5309.368, "stop": 5309.599, "duration": 0.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- but not for the United States.", "start": 5309.599, "stop": 5311.302, "duration": 1.7}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "And I also was advised that it was not done by the Department of Justice, although, I'm not sure just how it was handled.", "start": 5311.302, "stop": 5319.067, "duration": 7.77}, {"text": "But in -- I think that the correct characterization (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 5319.067, "stop": 5323.278, "duration": 4.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "The Department of Justice didn't do this?", "start": 5323.278, "stop": 5325.041, "duration": 1.76}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I heard that it was the Department of State that submitted it and I think the correct --", "start": 5325.041, "stop": 5329.923, "duration": 4.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "In reference to it in any of the judgments of the Court.", "start": 5329.923, "stop": 5332.294, "duration": 2.37}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, it does not.", "start": 5332.294, "stop": 5333.615, "duration": 1.32}, {"text": "The correct characterization of it was that it was an advocate's brief that was a position that had been taken by the United States in various efforts to get better terms in regard to agreements concerning immunity and it was not accepted in this Court.", "start": 5333.615, "stop": 5355.227, "duration": 21.61}, {"text": "It never been accepted by any nation in the world up to date that we've been able to find.", "start": 5355.227, "stop": 5361.105, "duration": 5.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's what -- that's what struck me that it -- saying if United States made a representation before the Supreme Court of Canada, no appearance, no reference should be made, no -- there should be no specific appearances and no reference in any of their judgments.", "start": 5361.105, "stop": 5375.846, "duration": 14.74}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 5375.846, "stop": 5377.028, "duration": 1.18}, {"text": "Now, this Court has said in a number of cases that international law is not merely what the writers may say it ought to be, but its not -- and it's what the law is, what you can find from the decisions and also what the practice it is amongst the nations of the world and that's how this Court determines what international law is and it doesn't make any difference on how much you theorize about what immunity you have from the law -- criminal law of another country if you can't persuade that country that that is the law.", "start": 5377.028, "stop": 5413.877, "duration": 36.85}, {"text": "You aren't going to get very far with that kind of a theory.", "start": 5413.877, "stop": 5418.253, "duration": 4.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I interrupted you when you started to tell the Court what the -- what the rulings were if you permit me to say so and you agreed that one thing they all agreed on was Chief Justice Marshall's opinion with which the Chief Justice read before lunch and they all agreed that there's an implied consent ahead.", "start": 5418.253, "stop": 5437.163, "duration": 18.91}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 5437.163, "stop": 5437.88, "duration": 0.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 5437.88, "stop": 5438.923, "duration": 1.04}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "And they were not willing to extend that to Canada as to the United States and in the concurring opinion of one of the justice of the court.", "start": 5438.923, "stop": 5451.624, "duration": 12.7}, {"text": "He said that we're involved in one of their nationals, there is certainly would be no immunity even though they would recognize it as between the United States' own people on the basis, so that was the position that the -- the Court took.", "start": 5451.624, "stop": 5470.825, "duration": 19.2}, {"text": "Now, both sides have cited louder parts, treaties on Oppenheim's International Law, but we have cited the Eighth Edition in our brief on page 25 and the opposing counsel have cited the Seventh Edition.", "start": 5470.825, "stop": 5492.05, "duration": 21.23}, {"text": "I don't how it happened that it was handled in this manner by a lot of facts, but if you turn from the place where he recites what is cited by counsel for the respondent, in the Seventh Edition some 48 pages later.", "start": 5492.05, "stop": 5508.886, "duration": 16.84}, {"text": "In the Eighth Edition, you'll find the following language.", "start": 5508.886, "stop": 5513.086, "duration": 4.2}, {"text": "However, the view which has the support of the bulk of practice is that in principle, members of visiting forces are subject to a criminal jurisdiction of local courts and that any derogations from that principle require specific agreement of the local state by figure or otherwise.", "start": 5513.086, "stop": 5540.158, "duration": 27.07}, {"text": "Now, it's generally recognized that the executive has the authority in regard to diplomatic immunity, one of the examples that counsels cited, to waive them that in this clear exchange case that Chief Justice Marshall has discusses the fact that one of the aspects of this problem is the representing of the sovereign, its diplomatic representative.", "start": 5540.158, "stop": 5572.048, "duration": 31.89}, {"text": "And generally, he is immune from the criminal laws of a country, which he attends, but that is subject to waiver and this Court has held in several cases and in the case -- the Kent case.", "start": 5572.048, "stop": 5587.876, "duration": 15.83}, {"text": "The United States did waive it and permitted Kent to be tried by the British courts in regard to certain secret documents that they claimed to have been stolen and this, the Court denied his application for consideration of that case.", "start": 5587.876, "stop": 5606.592, "duration": 18.72}, {"text": "And in the area of extradition, the Court has recognized the discretion of the State to decide, plan the person charged should be delivered up and it's entirely within the discretion of the executive to make that decision and the Court has so recognized.", "start": 5606.592, "stop": 5631.259, "duration": 24.67}, {"text": "We do have an extradition treaty with Japan that we have had for some 17 years and under all of those principles, which we think are comparable, there would be a discretionary authority in the executive to determine whether or not to act -- for the Government to act or to permit the other country to the same situations dealt with and been recognized by this Court in regard to the Attorney General's power to deliver up a prisoner who is held in a federal penitentiary for state prosecution.", "start": 5631.259, "stop": 5667.61, "duration": 36.35}, {"text": "And as a matter for his discretion, even though there is no statute concerning, that he can exercise that discretion and deliver the man up so he can be prosecuted under the state offense and that that penalty shall be -- shall follow whatever action he has been -- whatever action has been imposed upon him for the federal offense so that the whole area of this discretionary authority of the State in regard to these problems have been recognized by the Court and applied.", "start": 5667.61, "stop": 5702.282, "duration": 34.67}, {"text": "Now, there was a question in regard to how many waivers had occurred with Japanese -- with Japan and the character of those waivers.", "start": 5702.282, "stop": 5716.026, "duration": 13.74}, {"text": "The Government was asked if it would supply information to counsel for the respond in regard to this and we made an effort just to see if it could be supplied and we found that the information was not in a form that it could possibly be -- be supplied with any -- any reasonable period of time because it would mean going back to every soldier's file and try to find out any one that had -- any record of being charged and try to find out just what happened in his particular case.", "start": 5716.026, "stop": 5749.387, "duration": 33.36}, {"text": "And with 5400 cases within one year, it was quite impossible to do.", "start": 5749.387, "stop": 5754.554, "duration": 5.17}, {"text": "So the best that we can do is refer to the annual report to the Senate Armed Services Committee on the exercise of the criminal jurisdiction over United States service personnel by foreign courts, December 1, 1955 to November 30, 1956 presented by George W. Hickam Jr., Major General of United States Army, the Judge Advocate General, Department of the Army, and this is in a hearing.", "start": 5754.554, "stop": 5781.673, "duration": 27.12}, {"text": "This isn't in our brief.", "start": 5781.673, "stop": 5783.459, "duration": 1.79}, {"text": "It was in a hearing report before a subcommittee of the Committee on armed services, United States Senate 85th Congress per session dated April 9th, 1957.", "start": 5783.459, "stop": 5798.071, "duration": 14.61}, {"text": "It's got an imprint on it, 91290, maybe of any assistance.", "start": 5798.071, "stop": 5805.682, "duration": 7.61}, {"text": "In that -- in regard to Japan, on page 37 with a notation effective since October 28th 1953, the Defense Department describes as follows.", "start": 5805.682, "stop": 5823.312, "duration": 17.63}, {"text": "During the period of this report, there were 5544 cases involving United States personnel subject to the jurisdiction of Japanese Courts, (3013 of these cases were traffic violations).", "start": 5823.312, "stop": 5840.537, "duration": 17.23}, {"text": "Japan waived its jurisdiction in 5409 or 97.56% of these cases.", "start": 5840.537, "stop": 5848.407, "duration": 7.87}, {"text": "It tried 111 cases.", "start": 5848.407, "stop": 5850.925, "duration": 2.52}, {"text": "These trials resulted in 54 fines only, 42 suspended sentences to confinement and 15 unsuspended sentences to confinement.", "start": 5850.925, "stop": 5861.892, "duration": 10.97}, {"text": "There is no further delineation of the character of their offenses.", "start": 5861.892, "stop": 5885.447, "duration": 23.56}, {"text": "The only other reference that I care to make is in regard to Article XIV and counsel has stated to the Court that applied as the Uniform Code states in all places.", "start": 5885.447, "stop": 5902.763, "duration": 17.32}, {"text": "The language is this chapter applies in all places.", "start": 5902.763, "stop": 5907.183, "duration": 4.42}, {"text": "In Article XIV, which is a part of the code, shows the attitude and position of the Congress in regard to this matter and the civil authorities as follows.", "start": 5907.183, "stop": 5919.576, "duration": 12.39}, {"text": "It reads, under such regulations as the secretary concerned maybe -- may prescribe a member of the armed forces accused of an offense against civil authority may be delivered upon request to the civil authority for trial so that if the Court cares to turn to that for authority, it seems clear what the attitude of the Congress is as it has expressed.", "start": 5919.576, "stop": 5945.831, "duration": 26.26}, {"text": "And in adopting Article XIV, the Court -- the Congress expressly removed the geographical limitations that were in the old Article 74 of the Military Code.", "start": 5945.831, "stop": 5962.078, "duration": 16.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Was there anything in the history that indicated that it was intended by the change to make it applicable so as to turn over people to foreign countries?", "start": 5962.078, "stop": 5973.436, "duration": 11.36}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I couldn't say except I don't -- do not -- I'm not able to say that the history as recited here to the Court by response counsel is not correct in regard to that and it seems to me that indicates that the Congress was trying to meet a situation where he would be delivered up to the civil government in Germany which is different than an entirely different sovereigns since we were still in charge of that civil government.", "start": 5973.436, "stop": 6001.573, "duration": 28.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "What was the date of the change, Mr. --", "start": 6001.573, "stop": 6009.318, "duration": 7.74}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "1950.", "start": 6009.318, "stop": 6010.67, "duration": 1.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "950?", "start": 6010.67, "stop": 6011.488, "duration": 0.82}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 6011.488, "stop": 6012.958, "duration": 1.47}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Solicitor, Mr. Carroll's last argument as I understood it was in effect that the position the Government has taken as to the conduct of Girard being in performance of his duty for the purposes of this case, shows that the Government would not consider or the military would not consider this a violation of the Military Code, this incident, which would subject Girard to court-martial charges, is that so?", "start": 6012.958, "stop": 6045.311, "duration": 32.35}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's a great surprise to me.", "start": 6045.311, "stop": 6049.17, "duration": 3.86}, {"text": "I would think that it would be a violation of the Military Code and that -- in case that this Court decided that he should not be prosecuted under law of Japan that -- that the prosecution would be followed up in that manner --", "start": 6049.17, "stop": 6065.896, "duration": 16.73}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "In other words, there's nothing --", "start": 6065.896, "stop": 6066.15, "duration": 0.25}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- but I have not made any inquiry on it.", "start": 6066.15, "stop": 6068.196, "duration": 2.05}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, if there's nothing in the Government's position, that's what I want to get clear to the effect that he would not be subject to court-martial charges --", "start": 6068.196, "stop": 6075.957, "duration": 7.76}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Not at all.", "start": 6075.957, "stop": 6076.362, "duration": 0.4}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- in the event, he was not specific.", "start": 6076.362, "stop": 6080.23, "duration": 3.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Solicitor General, if you have any authorities that you've referred to that you like to submit, you may do so and type writing for -- by tomorrow morning if you please.", "start": 6080.23, "stop": 6090.384, "duration": 10.15}, {"text": "Mr. Carroll, was there any new point that brief -- you might want to raise briefly if --", "start": 6090.384, "stop": 6097.965, "duration": 7.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, Your Honor.", "start": 6097.965, "stop": 6098.242, "duration": 0.28}, {"text": "I just like to answer that Kent case.", "start": 6098.242, "stop": 6100.018, "duration": 1.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right, you may do then.", "start": 6100.018, "stop": 6102.539, "duration": 2.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl J. Carroll", "textObjs": [{"text": "The Kent case, Your Honor, which has been cited here takes up a lot of page in this brief, is simply this.", "start": 6102.539, "stop": 6108.79, "duration": 6.25}, {"text": "An employee in May of 1940 -- I believe is 1941 of the State Department and in the embassy office was found to be engaged in espionage or at least turning over classified information to agents of Nazi Germany.", "start": 6108.79, "stop": 6134.792, "duration": 26}, {"text": "He was immediately fired.", "start": 6134.792, "stop": 6136.941, "duration": 2.15}, {"text": "The -- the documents or some of the incriminating evidence was found in his -- amongst his belongings in the embassy building.", "start": 6136.941, "stop": 6145.506, "duration": 8.57}, {"text": "He was fired and this was in May and in -- I believe either August or September, he was prosecuted by the British authorities.", "start": 6145.506, "stop": 6158.462, "duration": 12.96}, {"text": "Britain then was at war with Germany and we were not at war with Germany.", "start": 6158.462, "stop": 6162.664, "duration": 4.2}, {"text": "The case stands for nothing at all insofar as the issues of this case are concerned.", "start": 6162.664, "stop": 6170.435, "duration": 7.77}, {"text": "I thought that point should be called to Your Honors attention and I think that's about all we have at the time you allowed us.", "start": 6170.435, "stop": 6177.997, "duration": 7.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you.", "start": 6177.997, "stop": 6179.216, "duration": 1.22}, {"text": "The Court will now adjourn until a further order of the Court.", "start": 6179.216, "stop": 6188.951, "duration": 9.73}]}]}, {"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - July 08, 1957 (Part 1)", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13350", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "1103, Charles E. Wilson, Secretary of Defense et al., Petitioners, versus William S.Girard, United States Army Specialist 3/C and William S. Girard in 1108, Petitioner, versus Charles E. Wilson et al.", "start": 0, "stop": 24.329, "duration": 24.33}, {"text": "You may proceed, Mr. Solicitor General.", "start": 24.329, "stop": 28.828, "duration": 4.5}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "May it please the Court.", "start": 28.828, "stop": 32.411, "duration": 3.58}, {"text": "I noticed Mr. Carroll left the courtroom, Your Honor, Shall I proceed?", "start": 32.411, "stop": 37.057, "duration": 4.65}, {"text": "He was just admitted.", "start": 37.057, "stop": 38.677, "duration": 1.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh, oh.", "start": 38.677, "stop": 39.93, "duration": 1.25}, {"text": "We -- we'll wait for him Mr. Solicitor General, I wasn't aware of that.", "start": 39.93, "stop": 73.255, "duration": 33.32}, {"text": "Mr. Solicitor General you may proceed.", "start": 73.255, "stop": 76.192, "duration": 2.94}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "May it please the Court.", "start": 76.192, "stop": 80.775, "duration": 4.58}, {"text": "The issue in this case is whether the United States has the right to decline to prosecute a soldier and let him be prosecuted under Japanese law where there is concurring jurisdiction.", "start": 80.775, "stop": 95.788, "duration": 15.01}, {"text": "And should the United States Court review that decision?", "start": 95.788, "stop": 102.372, "duration": 6.58}, {"text": "The facts are these.", "start": 102.372, "stop": 104.874, "duration": 2.5}, {"text": "January 30th of 1957, a military unit of the United States was maneuvering on Camp Weir in Japan.", "start": 104.874, "stop": 116.607, "duration": 11.73}, {"text": "This maneuver area was an area that was part at the time assigned to the United States to use.", "start": 116.607, "stop": 125.422, "duration": 8.81}, {"text": "About 40% of the time was used by the Japanese defense troops.", "start": 125.422, "stop": 131.943, "duration": 6.52}, {"text": "And the balance, a substantial portion at that time was used by Japanese civilians for farming and other purposes.", "start": 131.943, "stop": 142.113, "duration": 10.17}, {"text": "At this time, during the maneuvers, there were so many Japanese nationals in the area that the commander decided that it was unsafe to continue to use live ammunition in the maneuvers.", "start": 142.113, "stop": 156.295, "duration": 14.18}, {"text": "And he directed that blank ammunition be used from that time on.", "start": 156.295, "stop": 162.077, "duration": 5.78}, {"text": "During an interval in the maneuvers, the respondent and another soldier by the name of Nickel were directed to guard a machine gun and some field jackets on a hill.", "start": 162.077, "stop": 177.546, "duration": 15.47}, {"text": "They proceeded to this ridge and then the respondent placed a blank cartridge in his grenade launcher and using a blank, he discharged it.", "start": 177.546, "stop": 195.109, "duration": 17.56}, {"text": "He put two times toward Japanese nationals in that area.", "start": 195.109, "stop": 200.855, "duration": 5.75}, {"text": "The second shot out of the grenade launcher of this empty cartridge case struck a Japanese married woman in the back and caused her death.", "start": 200.855, "stop": 215.856, "duration": 15}, {"text": "The commander of the unit of the respondent certified that this act, the killing, was an act in pursuit -- in the performance of the respondent's duties.", "start": 215.856, "stop": 232.557, "duration": 16.7}, {"text": "This was done on February 7th.", "start": 232.557, "stop": 235.573, "duration": 3.02}, {"text": "On February 9th, the Japanese protested the certificate and claimed that the machine gun was never at any time threatened by the Japanese that there was no effort to interfere or molest it.", "start": 235.573, "stop": 251.983, "duration": 16.41}, {"text": "And the action was not done in performance of official duty.", "start": 251.983, "stop": 256.649, "duration": 4.67}, {"text": "And it was not necessary to fire this empty cartridge out of the grenade launcher in the protection or a guard of the machine gun and these field jackets.", "start": 256.649, "stop": 270.41, "duration": 13.76}, {"text": "There was a procedure set up by the two Governments whereby a Joint Committee would inquire into the question if there was a dispute.", "start": 270.41, "stop": 280.081, "duration": 9.67}, {"text": "And for the --", "start": 280.081, "stop": 280.141, "duration": 0.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "So, before you get to that, there is in the record, an affidavit of the chief counsel of the Department of Defense, which shows more precisely what the facts of the case are.", "start": 280.141, "stop": 295.473, "duration": 15.33}, {"text": "Would you mind stating the circumstances under which those came in the record?", "start": 295.473, "stop": 299.524, "duration": 4.05}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Mr. Chief Justice.", "start": 299.524, "stop": 302.083, "duration": 2.56}, {"text": "That affidavit recites in detail the fact that there were certain witnesses who have stated, including the -- the soldier Nickel that they were directed and the soldiers proceeded to throw out these empty cartridges to invite or entice the Japanese civilians to come and try to get them and take them away to sell and recover what value they could out of it.", "start": 302.083, "stop": 329.503, "duration": 27.42}, {"text": "And that there was actually a -- an invitation for them to come forward and pick them up prior to the time of the discharge of this empty cartridge out of the grenade launcher.", "start": 329.503, "stop": 341.82, "duration": 12.32}, {"text": "And that goes into considerable detail in reciting these facts.", "start": 341.82, "stop": 346.442, "duration": 4.62}, {"text": "And it was presented to the lower court and was sealed at the request to the Government to protect the respondent from any adverse effect upon his trial.", "start": 346.442, "stop": 356.921, "duration": 10.48}, {"text": "The Government has no other interest in having it sealed.", "start": 356.921, "stop": 359.933, "duration": 3.01}, {"text": "And it is in this Court for its consideration in a sealed form if the Court cares to go into that detail.", "start": 359.933, "stop": 367.064, "duration": 7.13}, {"text": "But there was a very real conflict as to even the two soldiers involved in regard to the facts.", "start": 367.064, "stop": 376.753, "duration": 9.69}, {"text": "And whether there was enticement and whether these Japanese civilians were invited in fact to come forward and then have this empty cartridge launched against them out of the grenade launcher.", "start": 376.753, "stop": 390.54, "duration": 13.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is there any objection to having it sealed by the respondent?", "start": 390.54, "stop": 394.669, "duration": 4.13}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, it was examined according to the proceedings that I read in the court below over at recess.", "start": 394.669, "stop": 401.362, "duration": 6.69}, {"text": "And at first, counsel indicated that they didn't want to consider at all but finally they appeared to agree that they would prefer to have it sealed rather than open to the public for examination.", "start": 401.362, "stop": 413.854, "duration": 12.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is there any objection to its being sealed before this Court?", "start": 413.854, "stop": 416.986, "duration": 3.13}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "As far as the Government is concerned, we are willing to have it considered by the Court fully.", "start": 416.986, "stop": 422.477, "duration": 5.49}, {"text": "The only purpose of having it sealed was to protect the respondent in his trial in case it occurred in Japan or court-martial depending upon the decision of this Court.", "start": 422.477, "stop": 432.554, "duration": 10.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "I assume then, General, from your statement that the affidavit is before us for all purposes.", "start": 432.554, "stop": 438.87, "duration": 6.32}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "It is as far as the Government is concerned.", "start": 438.87, "stop": 441.551, "duration": 2.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I --", "start": 441.551, "stop": 442.42, "duration": 0.87}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I cannot speak for the other side but --", "start": 442.42, "stop": 444.551, "duration": 2.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I -- does -- is there any legal reason -- is there any legal reason why this should not be made public if it becomes necessary to do so in the writing of an opinion in this case?", "start": 444.551, "stop": 464.837, "duration": 20.29}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, there is not.", "start": 464.837, "stop": 466.253, "duration": 1.42}, {"text": "The only problem is whether he -- the respondent will be prejudiced by it and it seems to us that if he is, the fact that he brings the matter here to this Court for its consideration, the Court is entitled to have all of the facts before it.", "start": 466.253, "stop": 481.338, "duration": 15.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But to that point comes before (Inaudible) can speak.", "start": 481.338, "stop": 483.867, "duration": 2.53}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 483.867, "stop": 485.829, "duration": 1.96}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Was there any closing affidavit made controverting this fact?", "start": 485.829, "stop": 491.605, "duration": 5.78}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "They -- no.", "start": 491.605, "stop": 493.726, "duration": 2.12}, {"text": "There was a denial.", "start": 493.726, "stop": 494.969, "duration": 1.24}, {"text": "And I think the record is that there is a -- a denial by the respondent that there was any enticement on his part.", "start": 494.969, "stop": 503.986, "duration": 9.02}, {"text": "The affidavit does show that the other soldier goes in to some detail in describing how he was instructed by the respondent to throw out the cartridges and invite the Japanese civilians to come forward and pick them up.", "start": 503.986, "stop": 521.837, "duration": 17.85}, {"text": "But he continues to -- the respondent continues to deny that.", "start": 521.837, "stop": 525.217, "duration": 3.38}, {"text": "I think that's right.", "start": 525.217, "stop": 525.257, "duration": 0.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did the respondent wholly apart from the -- the legal relevance and not -- did respondent speak to raise issues of fact for the District Court?", "start": 525.257, "stop": 538.089, "duration": 12.83}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that a fair answer to that Mr. Justice is that the respondent did seek to raise issues of fact.", "start": 538.089, "stop": 545.081, "duration": 6.99}, {"text": "And that the Government stipulated that insofar as this particular proceeding was concerned, and for no other purpose, that this act was in the performance of official duty and thereby eliminated that kind of an issue of fact.", "start": 545.081, "stop": 564.04, "duration": 18.96}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Was the controversy about issue of the fact merely as to that question?", "start": 564.04, "stop": 568.04, "duration": 4}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, that's my understanding.", "start": 568.04, "stop": 571.161, "duration": 3.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "So that you admitted, the Government for purpose of legal questions, admitted the issue on which there was a contest.", "start": 571.161, "stop": 579.085, "duration": 7.92}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 579.085, "stop": 579.433, "duration": 0.35}, {"text": "And the lower court found that there was no issue of fact in passing upon the case.", "start": 579.433, "stop": 586.03, "duration": 6.6}, {"text": "Now, on the certificate by the commanding officer of the respondent continues in effect.", "start": 586.03, "stop": 593.115, "duration": 7.09}, {"text": "The Government has taken the position at all times that there was never any authorization for the use of the grenade launcher and the rifle in this manner in ejecting a empty cartridge against any personnel of any kind.", "start": 593.115, "stop": 612.729, "duration": 19.61}, {"text": "And it is not -- it has not been claimed up to date by the respondent that he was authorized or directed to do anything of that nature.", "start": 612.729, "stop": 620.317, "duration": 7.59}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "But for the purposes of the case here, you're not raising any question but that this action was in line of this man's duty.", "start": 620.317, "stop": 630.652, "duration": 10.34}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 630.652, "stop": 631.109, "duration": 0.46}, {"text": "We are -- we stipulated --", "start": 631.109, "stop": 631.726, "duration": 0.62}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "In other words we -- we take the case as if he's there with specific instructions to shoot this woman given by his commanding officer, isn't that right?", "start": 631.726, "stop": 639.602, "duration": 7.88}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, it isn't necessary that there would be a direction or an order to do the shooting for it to be an act in the performance of official duty.", "start": 639.602, "stop": 649.086, "duration": 9.48}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't understand.", "start": 649.086, "stop": 649.567, "duration": 0.48}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "We only go so far as to stipulate that it was an act in the performance of official duty.", "start": 649.567, "stop": 655.138, "duration": 5.57}, {"text": "What -- what that means under the record and under the facts here.", "start": 655.138, "stop": 659.367, "duration": 4.23}, {"text": "So that now, it is important as we think --", "start": 659.367, "stop": 661.985, "duration": 2.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't -- I don't quite understand the -- your position there.", "start": 661.985, "stop": 667.385, "duration": 5.4}, {"text": "How could it be in the line in the performance of his official duty unless it was done in allegiance and expressed or an implied order.", "start": 667.385, "stop": 676.879, "duration": 9.49}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I understood the question of Mr. Justice Harlan to be possibly the implied order as distinguished -- a direct order as distinguished from an implied order.", "start": 676.879, "stop": 689.88, "duration": 13}, {"text": "It could be under the line of official duty if it was something that was required under the agreed rules that the Joint Committee had established.", "start": 689.88, "stop": 700.563, "duration": 10.68}, {"text": "Even though no officer had ever instructed him to do this particular act.", "start": 700.563, "stop": 705.51, "duration": 4.95}, {"text": "And the inquiry, as I understand it, from Mr. Justice Harlan, is whether or not he was directed or ordered to do this act.", "start": 705.51, "stop": 712.023, "duration": 6.51}, {"text": "And we do not agree that he was ever ordered or directed or he was even authorized to use this rifle and the grenade launcher in this -- in this manner.", "start": 712.023, "stop": 720.911, "duration": 8.89}, {"text": "But we do -- did stipulate a law and continue to abide by it by here.", "start": 720.911, "stop": 727.515, "duration": 6.6}, {"text": "That he was -- the act was in performance of official duty in accordance with the Protocol.", "start": 727.515, "stop": 734.538, "duration": 7.02}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'll put it this way.", "start": 734.538, "stop": 736.083, "duration": 1.54}, {"text": "Is the effect of your stipulation -- would you concede that within the meaning of the decree, the United States had primary jurisdiction?", "start": 736.083, "stop": 750.173, "duration": 14.09}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That was our contention, yes, throughout.", "start": 750.173, "stop": 751.605, "duration": 1.43}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I mean, you concede that.", "start": 751.605, "stop": 752.533, "duration": 0.93}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "And we concede that, yes.", "start": 752.533, "stop": 753.511, "duration": 0.98}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 753.511, "stop": 754.296, "duration": 0.79}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, --", "start": 754.296, "stop": 754.684, "duration": 0.39}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Simply -- simply the question is then whether there has been a waiver and whether the waiver was -- was --", "start": 754.684, "stop": 762.017, "duration": 7.33}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Authorized and proper.", "start": 762.017, "stop": 762.409, "duration": 0.39}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 762.409, "stop": 763.377, "duration": 0.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is where it was the claim of the United States if they had primary jurisdiction.", "start": 763.377, "stop": 768.308, "duration": 4.93}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 768.308, "stop": 769.435, "duration": 1.13}, {"text": "Now -- but there is --", "start": 769.435, "stop": 770.36, "duration": 0.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "You make -- you make a distinction I think it's between a soldier and officer being liable, being found to be acting within the course of his duties.", "start": 770.36, "stop": 782.448, "duration": 12.09}, {"text": "And the Government of the United States, instructing a soldier to do something which might have -- which might be, to say the least, not a very -- a very nice thing for the Government of the United States to instruct its soldiers to do that.", "start": 782.448, "stop": 798.455, "duration": 16.01}, {"text": "In other words, single liability for an act done in the course of duty is very different from saying you go ahead and shoot a woman.", "start": 798.455, "stop": 804.274, "duration": 5.82}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 804.274, "stop": 805.964, "duration": 1.69}, {"text": "Now, we think that it is important to the consideration of the case, these other facts of whether there was enticement or an invitation to come forward and pick up this blank or empty cartridges in that it bears upon the whole posture of the situation when the executive decided to decline to prosecute or to waive the jurisdiction assume that the United States had a right of the primary jurisdiction to prosecute in this situation because there had to be a consideration by the executive of the position of Japan that this was not within the requirements of official duty.", "start": 805.964, "stop": 850.572, "duration": 44.61}, {"text": "And that this was not authorized.", "start": 850.572, "stop": 853.131, "duration": 2.56}, {"text": "And it was not necessary because there was no threat to the machine gun and field jackets to do anything of this character.", "start": 853.131, "stop": 862.018, "duration": 8.89}, {"text": "All of that had to be considered by the executive in passing upon the question of whether or not to decline jurisdiction or waive jurisdiction, which were rights that belonged to the State rather than any individual.", "start": 862.018, "stop": 876.761, "duration": 14.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Harold Burton", "textObjs": [{"text": "And if it were not in the line of duty by then it is considered that it was the primary jurisdiction was liable to Japan, is that right?", "start": 876.761, "stop": 882.512, "duration": 5.75}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "There's no question about that under the Protocol.", "start": 882.512, "stop": 885.425, "duration": 2.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "General, do you make any distinction between something that is in line of duty and -- and an act that was merely done while on duty?", "start": 885.425, "stop": 896.032, "duration": 10.61}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, there is a distinction and the Protocol deals specifically with an act done in the performance of official duty.", "start": 896.032, "stop": 903.865, "duration": 7.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 903.865, "stop": 905.141, "duration": 1.28}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "There have been a number of cases discussed in newspapers about where a man might be on duty but do something so far removed from what would be in performance of that duty.", "start": 905.141, "stop": 918.498, "duration": 13.36}, {"text": "That it couldn't be within the requirements of the Protocol for primary jurisdiction.", "start": 918.498, "stop": 923.059, "duration": 4.56}, {"text": "But that would --", "start": 923.059, "stop": 923.079, "duration": 0.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, if you discussed the conventional question of law of agency whether a man is -- whether the principal is responsible or whether the agent is on a frolic of his own.", "start": 923.079, "stop": 931.634, "duration": 8.56}, {"text": "That's all this, isn't it?", "start": 931.634, "stop": 932.841, "duration": 1.21}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that's pretty generally the -- the responding of superior problems what's --", "start": 932.841, "stop": 938.203, "duration": 5.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, General, the reason I asked you the question was because I recall you stated that the commanding officer had at all times taken the position that the respondent had no authority.", "start": 938.203, "stop": 954.685, "duration": 16.48}, {"text": "And it was not -- not the custom for him to put any blank cartridge in his grenade -- in his hand grenade.", "start": 954.685, "stop": 963.354, "duration": 8.67}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "His grenade launcher.", "start": 963.354, "stop": 964.09, "duration": 0.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "His grenade launcher rather.", "start": 964.09, "stop": 965.913, "duration": 1.82}, {"text": "Now, the -- would that statement on your part indicate that you make any distinction between a man doing an act merely while his on duty on the one hand and on the other hand, an act done pursuant to duty.", "start": 965.913, "stop": 981.648, "duration": 15.74}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, because the -- let me clarify in regard to that.", "start": 981.648, "stop": 986.572, "duration": 4.92}, {"text": "The position not only the commanding officer of the man but of the Government itself, the Defense Department is that there never was any authority for using this empty cartridge in the grenade launcher in the manner it was done.", "start": 986.572, "stop": 1000.687, "duration": 14.12}, {"text": "And it was their position.", "start": 1000.687, "stop": 1002.616, "duration": 1.93}, {"text": "And the controversy all the time between Japan and the United States was whether this ever did come within the requirements of the Protocol on regard to primary jurisdiction for the United States Court-Martial.", "start": 1002.616, "stop": 1015.531, "duration": 12.91}, {"text": "And that if it was something that was unauthorized, that gave validity to their contention all the way along that there wasn't any authority and he had no right to do this and it couldn't comply with the requirements of the Treaty.", "start": 1015.531, "stop": 1031.357, "duration": 15.83}, {"text": "And the United States was continually asserting the other position before the Joint Committee in order that it should try to claim the primary jurisdiction.", "start": 1031.357, "stop": 1041.499, "duration": 10.14}, {"text": "But the two countries couldn't agree in the Joint Committee in the provisions that were made under the Protocol for implementing but that was true.", "start": 1041.499, "stop": 1053.724, "duration": 12.22}, {"text": "And so they went on for a period of -- from the middle of March to the middle of May arguing about it, whether or not it was in fact within the performance of official duty.", "start": 1053.724, "stop": 1067.558, "duration": 13.83}, {"text": "And if not, it was clear under the Treaty that Japan would have the primary jurisdiction.", "start": 1067.558, "stop": 1074.427, "duration": 6.87}, {"text": "And this was -- this was a case of concurrent jurisdiction because it was a violation of both the Japanese law and the Military Code.", "start": 1074.427, "stop": 1083.225, "duration": 8.8}, {"text": "And if -- if it was not in the performance of official duty, it was clearly something that Japan would have a right to prosecute under the Protocol under section 3 (b).", "start": 1083.225, "stop": 1095.222, "duration": 12}, {"text": "And if it was, we would be -- we would have the right, the primary right.", "start": 1095.222, "stop": 1100.246, "duration": 5.02}, {"text": "And in any event, the Protocol provided that we could waive it or we could decline to exercise the jurisdiction.", "start": 1100.246, "stop": 1108.231, "duration": 7.98}, {"text": "So, we had that constant controversy in the Joint Committee that was assigned to try to resolve this kind of problem in the period between the middle of March and the middle of May.", "start": 1108.231, "stop": 1119.972, "duration": 11.74}, {"text": "And the Japanese continued to assert their position that it just could not be in accordance with the requirements of the performance of official duty.", "start": 1119.972, "stop": 1128.52, "duration": 8.55}, {"text": "And the agreed statement of what is required for that by the United States and Japan was that it had to be some act required by the particular duty.", "start": 1128.52, "stop": 1138.582, "duration": 10.06}, {"text": "And the Japanese asserted it just couldn't comply with that.", "start": 1138.582, "stop": 1141.836, "duration": 3.25}, {"text": "And we continued, we still have that certificate in effect even after the day and continued to assert in a -- a conference between the two parties and the Joint Committee that it was in the performance of official duty.", "start": 1141.836, "stop": 1155.442, "duration": 13.61}, {"text": "We didn't convince them.", "start": 1155.442, "stop": 1157.076, "duration": 1.63}, {"text": "They didn't convince us.", "start": 1157.076, "stop": 1158.677, "duration": 1.6}, {"text": "So, it then came down to the proposition of what the executives should do to try to resolve this international incident --", "start": 1158.677, "stop": 1166.051, "duration": 7.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1166.051, "stop": 1166.19, "duration": 0.14}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- between the two contending countries.", "start": 1166.19, "stop": 1168.775, "duration": 2.59}, {"text": "And the executive looking at the facts, looking at the contentions on both sides and the lack of harmony between the -- the parties and the various witnesses as to what happened and the contention of -- of substance that there had been enticement -- inducement to -- to come and get the empty cartridges before the act, considering all of it and the feeling of the Japanese and the fact that they had some 90% -- 97% of the time in 5400 incidents when in a year's time given away to the United States and waived their primary jurisdictions, the executive finally decided to waive this jurisdiction.", "start": 1168.775, "stop": 1215.005, "duration": 46.23}, {"text": "And the Secretary of Defense and the Secretary of State and then the President himself reviewed the matter and approved the action to decline the jurisdiction and proceed to notify Japan of the waiver.", "start": 1215.005, "stop": 1227.272, "duration": 12.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1227.272, "stop": 1228.058, "duration": 0.79}, {"text": "Well, now, General, what -- what I was trying to get clear in -- in my mind was -- was this.", "start": 1228.058, "stop": 1233.648, "duration": 5.59}, {"text": "Leaving -- leaving the question of waiver entirely out of the case for the moment --", "start": 1233.648, "stop": 1240.321, "duration": 6.67}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1240.321, "stop": 1241.335, "duration": 1.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- is there in this case a legal differentiation between an act done merely while on duty on the one hand and an act done pursuant to duty on the other?", "start": 1241.335, "stop": 1259.968, "duration": 18.63}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, it is the position of the Government that even if it was an act done in the performance of official duty or an act done in the line of duty which is not the technical words of the Treaty and therefore probably would give Japan jurisdiction.", "start": 1259.968, "stop": 1279.882, "duration": 19.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1279.882, "stop": 1280.492, "duration": 0.61}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That the United States has the power and authority under the law to decline jurisdiction and waive it regardless --", "start": 1280.492, "stop": 1288.938, "duration": 8.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1288.938, "stop": 1289.932, "duration": 0.99}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- of that point.", "start": 1289.932, "stop": 1290.807, "duration": 0.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "But -- but do you give us one position on which we can stand either that -- either that it was done pursuant to duty or -- or something different from that (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 1290.807, "stop": 1303.398, "duration": 12.59}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I think our stipulation clearly binds us in this Court that this act complies with the requirement of the Protocol for an act done in the performance of duty as far as the posture of this case before this Court is concerned.", "start": 1303.398, "stop": 1320.391, "duration": 16.99}, {"text": "And so, the Court must take that as far as that element is concerned and assume that regardless of what the facts of the dispute regarding the facts that --", "start": 1320.391, "stop": 1332.885, "duration": 12.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1332.885, "stop": 1333.253, "duration": 0.37}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- this act is or was done in performance of official duty and therefore, complied with the requirement for primary jurisdiction of the Protocol.", "start": 1333.253, "stop": 1344.008, "duration": 10.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1344.008, "stop": 1344.777, "duration": 0.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Are you saying, if I understand your answer to the Chief Justice on this.", "start": 1344.777, "stop": 1348.902, "duration": 4.13}, {"text": "That for purposes of this case, the Government says that 3A -- 3A-2 was satisfied.", "start": 1348.902, "stop": 1363.829, "duration": 14.93}, {"text": "This is an act of -- an act in the performance of official duty.", "start": 1363.829, "stop": 1371.001, "duration": 7.17}, {"text": "That you admit that, for purposes of the legal question raised by such an admission or stipulation.", "start": 1371.001, "stop": 1379.388, "duration": 8.39}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 1379.388, "stop": 1379.859, "duration": 0.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But are you saying that non-constant, it doesn't follow that assuming that a tort action could be brought, assuming -- I know that -- assuming that a tort action could be brought to the District Court of United States under the Federal Tort Act.", "start": 1379.859, "stop": 1397.081, "duration": 17.22}, {"text": "I know I'm making an assumption.", "start": 1397.081, "stop": 1399.685, "duration": 2.6}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1399.685, "stop": 1399.904, "duration": 0.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That the Government could take the position by way of defense that in fact the Government is not liable.", "start": 1399.904, "stop": 1408.135, "duration": 8.23}, {"text": "That this so far traveled out of the responsibility of the Government as -- as the principal of this soldier that under (Inaudible) certain laws of agency and tort, the Government would not be liable.", "start": 1408.135, "stop": 1421.188, "duration": 13.05}, {"text": "Is that the line you're drawing?", "start": 1421.188, "stop": 1422.391, "duration": 1.2}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is right, Mr. Justice.", "start": 1422.391, "stop": 1423.743, "duration": 1.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "What was in duty?", "start": 1423.743, "stop": 1423.767, "duration": 0.02}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "What?", "start": 1423.767, "stop": 1426.296, "duration": 2.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "What was the soldier's duty?", "start": 1426.296, "stop": 1428.666, "duration": 2.37}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "The -- the soldier is instructed --", "start": 1428.666, "stop": 1430.31, "duration": 1.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "You said in the performance of his official duty.", "start": 1430.31, "stop": 1432.527, "duration": 2.22}, {"text": "What was it?", "start": 1432.527, "stop": 1433.306, "duration": 0.78}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Duty was to guard the machine gun and the field jackets --", "start": 1433.306, "stop": 1437.66, "duration": 4.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "From what?", "start": 1437.66, "stop": 1438.217, "duration": 0.56}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- on the ridge.", "start": 1438.217, "stop": 1439.434, "duration": 1.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "From what?", "start": 1439.434, "stop": 1440.184, "duration": 0.75}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "From anyone who might try to damage them or take them away, anything of that character.", "start": 1440.184, "stop": 1448.711, "duration": 8.53}, {"text": "The Japanese contended that --", "start": 1448.711, "stop": 1449.824, "duration": 1.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Either what you are contending is that he went further than he should have gone in the performance of his duty guarding and shot what he shouldn't have shot.", "start": 1449.824, "stop": 1458.32, "duration": 8.5}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that's what the Japanese contended Mr. Justice.", "start": 1458.32, "stop": 1460.597, "duration": 2.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1460.597, "stop": 1461.625, "duration": 1.03}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I'm not free in this Court to contend that this is an issue before this Court any longer.", "start": 1461.625, "stop": 1468.567, "duration": 6.94}, {"text": "I do want to -- the -- understood however, that I do think the facts of enticing and the detail of all of those facts have a real bearing on whether it was reasonable for the executive to take the action that he did regarding the question of declining to exercise jurisdiction or waiving jurisdiction.", "start": 1468.567, "stop": 1491.874, "duration": 23.31}, {"text": "But when you come to the question of where the primary jurisdiction is found under the Protocol, I think that we are bound by our stipulation in the lower court and in this Court that it was --", "start": 1491.874, "stop": 1503.247, "duration": 11.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But what the Chief Justice's question was directed, was that latter fact.", "start": 1503.247, "stop": 1507.207, "duration": 3.96}, {"text": "And he explicitly put to one side for the time being the question of waiver.", "start": 1507.207, "stop": 1511.601, "duration": 4.39}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- that's what -- the way I understood it, Mr. Justice.", "start": 1511.601, "stop": 1514.428, "duration": 2.83}, {"text": "I just want to be clear all the time that I was reserving the other consideration because I think it's important to the case.", "start": 1514.428, "stop": 1522.177, "duration": 7.75}, {"text": "Now --", "start": 1522.177, "stop": 1523.897, "duration": 1.72}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Then where -- where is the exact language of the stipulation in the record you made below?", "start": 1523.897, "stop": 1535.27, "duration": 11.37}, {"text": "Isn't that colloquy with the trial judge?", "start": 1535.27, "stop": 1537.68, "duration": 2.41}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1537.68, "stop": 1538.251, "duration": 0.57}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1538.251, "stop": 1538.861, "duration": 0.61}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1538.861, "stop": 1555.2, "duration": 16.34}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think the last answer at the bottom of page 46A and falling on 47A would give you the commitment that the Government made at that time.", "start": 1555.2, "stop": 1568.916, "duration": 13.72}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that in the fact is actually the language, isn't it, substantially of 3A-2?", "start": 1568.916, "stop": 1575.703, "duration": 6.79}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is correct, Mr. Justice.", "start": 1575.703, "stop": 1582.606, "duration": 6.9}, {"text": "Now, it seems to the Government that the -- the legal questions involved in the case are these.", "start": 1582.606, "stop": 1590.7, "duration": 8.09}, {"text": "The primary question is whether or not under international law there is any immunity from -- in the respondent from the laws of Japan for an offense committed in Japan.", "start": 1590.7, "stop": 1609.307, "duration": 18.61}, {"text": "There's no question of what the offense was committed in Japan.", "start": 1609.307, "stop": 1612.631, "duration": 3.32}, {"text": "And that the respondent has always been in Japan since the offense was committed.", "start": 1612.631, "stop": 1618.155, "duration": 5.52}, {"text": "So, we have to turn to international law to determine whether or not there is any immunity from the laws of Japan for the respondent or any soldier located in that country without a Protocol or treaties or agreements of any kind.", "start": 1618.155, "stop": 1639.715, "duration": 21.56}, {"text": "And we believe that in the first place, it's the position of the United States Government, both the Executive and the Legislative branches that there is no immunity under international law for even a friendly force in a -- a foreign country such as Japan.", "start": 1639.715, "stop": 1660.902, "duration": 21.19}, {"text": "And that goes back to the Schooner Exchange Case that that this Court has dealt with not directly but by reference from the Covert and (Inaudible) cases in which the Court referred to the fact that there would -- would not be immunity.", "start": 1660.902, "stop": 1677.394, "duration": 16.49}, {"text": "And it was recognized in the Schooner Exchange case by this Court that any interference or any claim of immunity whatsoever in the country, with a friendly force would be a reduction in the sovereignty of that country.", "start": 1677.394, "stop": 1693.552, "duration": 16.16}, {"text": "And it would be taken onto the other country that claimed it, a portion of that sovereign.", "start": 1693.552, "stop": 1699.371, "duration": 5.82}, {"text": "And, of course, in that case, the Chief Justice Marshall recognized that even if there was an implied immunity which he recognized as to the Schooner Exchange itself that that could be modified at any time by the sovereign of the country where the friendly force was.", "start": 1699.371, "stop": 1718.322, "duration": 18.95}, {"text": "The host country by any agreement or by proceeding to by force or by submitting the particular force to his courts and thereby, remove any implied immunity that there might be.", "start": 1718.322, "stop": 1738.171, "duration": 19.85}, {"text": "Now, that the Government has not been able to find any country, any sovereign country in the world that recognizes the right of an immunity under international law.", "start": 1738.171, "stop": 1752.073, "duration": 13.9}, {"text": "So that it is -- has been the position of the United States both in the Legislative and the Executive branches in the consideration of the NATO Status of Forces Treaty that there is no immunity of -- under international law on the laws of the host country as to a friendly force.", "start": 1752.073, "stop": 1774.155, "duration": 22.08}, {"text": "Now, there -- there is a conflict between some of the writers in regard to that.", "start": 1774.155, "stop": 1779.861, "duration": 5.71}, {"text": "But they cite no authority of any practice where any country has been willing to recognize such a limitation upon their sovereign.", "start": 1779.861, "stop": 1791.142, "duration": 11.28}, {"text": "And I think the outstanding examples in regard to the position of the United States are, that back in 1942, we considered this question in the Congress.", "start": 1791.142, "stop": 1805, "duration": 13.86}, {"text": "And the application concerning the military courts of various countries at that time and also the fact that Britain, as a part of the war effort had granted a complete immunity to United States forces.", "start": 1805, "stop": 1827.883, "duration": 22.88}, {"text": "And the British at the time, they adopted such a position stated that it was a very great departure from their practice and traditions.", "start": 1827.883, "stop": 1836.936, "duration": 9.05}, {"text": "It was only done because of the exigencies of the war and the position they were in at the time.", "start": 1836.936, "stop": 1843.58, "duration": 6.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Solicitor I take it that foreign forces -- foreign friendly forces at various times have from time to time been stationed, for all I know, I do not know but I assume are stationed now in the United States.", "start": 1843.58, "stop": 1857.228, "duration": 13.65}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is correct.", "start": 1857.228, "stop": 1857.417, "duration": 0.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is that so?", "start": 1857.417, "stop": 1858.133, "duration": 0.72}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 1858.133, "stop": 1859.227, "duration": 1.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Has there been any arrangement and any provisions, any light to be shed as to the claims we make regarding offenses by foreign forces stationed on our soil?", "start": 1859.227, "stop": 1870.338, "duration": 11.11}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "The most that we have ever conceded with regard to the soil of the United States is that and provided in the NATO Status of Forces Agreement which is reciprocal in that it provides the same kind of immunity limited in the same way that was -- that is discussed in this case in regard to Japan.", "start": 1870.338, "stop": 1896.821, "duration": 26.48}, {"text": "We grant, as to the particular force and acts of the -- that are committed by that force against its own people while on the base and so forth and we get the primary jurisdiction but --", "start": 1896.821, "stop": 1915.676, "duration": 18.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "With the same limitation about in the performance of duty?", "start": 1915.676, "stop": 1918.821, "duration": 3.14}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1918.821, "stop": 1919.606, "duration": 0.79}, {"text": "It's --", "start": 1919.606, "stop": 1919.726, "duration": 0.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I --", "start": 1919.726, "stop": 1920.018, "duration": 0.29}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- its entirely reciprocal between --", "start": 1920.018, "stop": 1921.927, "duration": 1.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But controversies may arise as they arise in the courts of law all the time as to whether it is or it isn't in the performance of duty.", "start": 1921.927, "stop": 1928.82, "duration": 6.89}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1928.82, "stop": 1929.41, "duration": 0.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And when there's a conflict, he now can say, Canada, others from Canadian troops unless it is classified material.", "start": 1929.41, "stop": 1935.149, "duration": 5.74}, {"text": "I never know when anything is classified in this [Laughter].", "start": 1935.149, "stop": 1937.877, "duration": 2.73}, {"text": "Is that classified?", "start": 1937.877, "stop": 1937.911, "duration": 0.03}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "We often have Canadians.", "start": 1937.911, "stop": 1939.227, "duration": 1.32}, {"text": "We often have Canadian troops.", "start": 1939.227, "stop": 1940.281, "duration": 1.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "We have Canadians.", "start": 1940.281, "stop": 1941.259, "duration": 0.98}, {"text": "Now, is there -- may there be a conflict between a commanding officer and the -- our -- our military and the Canadian military as to whether an act is or isn't done?", "start": 1941.259, "stop": 1952.562, "duration": 11.3}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, of course.", "start": 1952.562, "stop": 1953.5, "duration": 0.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And how is that resolved?", "start": 1953.5, "stop": 1955.389, "duration": 1.89}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, we claimed in, under the NATO Status of Forces Agreement that we have the right as to other countries to decide when the primary jurisdiction lay because of performance of official duty.", "start": 1955.389, "stop": 1972.749, "duration": 17.36}, {"text": "And we were not successful in maintaining that position.", "start": 1972.749, "stop": 1976.103, "duration": 3.35}, {"text": "The -- when the matter came before the British Courts, the parliament, British Parliament -- Parliament, they just would not accept.", "start": 1976.103, "stop": 1984.456, "duration": 8.35}, {"text": "And they insisted that there be a provision that their courts could pass upon the question of whether or not the -- it was satisfied as to performance of official duty.", "start": 1984.456, "stop": 1994.774, "duration": 10.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "We didn't ask the Canadian troops on our soils.", "start": 1994.774, "stop": 1997.567, "duration": 2.79}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "And -- oh, well.", "start": 1997.567, "stop": 1998.601, "duration": 1.03}, {"text": "Then after that, the Canadians asserted a similar position.", "start": 1998.601, "stop": 2003.674, "duration": 5.07}, {"text": "And it came up for discussion in our Congress in one of the committees of the Senate.", "start": 2003.674, "stop": 2010.689, "duration": 7.02}, {"text": "And Senator Hickman commented upon it and said that in Iowa, they certainly wouldn't be satisfied to have the Canadian Corps decide whether or not some Canadian soldier that would kill someone in Iowa would be acting in the line of duty.", "start": 2010.689, "stop": 2029.277, "duration": 18.59}, {"text": "And they would want in Iowa, certainly, to have the Iowa courts pass upon that question.", "start": 2029.277, "stop": 2035.355, "duration": 6.08}, {"text": "And in this Protocol, it's provided that the Japanese court would have the right to pass upon that question.", "start": 2035.355, "stop": 2043.222, "duration": 7.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is as to -- as to the Executive as taking its position.", "start": 2043.222, "stop": 2046.894, "duration": 3.67}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right and --", "start": 2046.894, "stop": 2048.26, "duration": 1.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Were there the same situations in reference to these Canadian soldiers in Iowa?", "start": 2048.26, "stop": 2053.284, "duration": 5.02}, {"text": "Suppose this kind of a situation arose in Iowa.", "start": 2053.284, "stop": 2056.3, "duration": 3.02}, {"text": "Would the same -- the same kind of arrangements govern and the same kind of decision is taken?", "start": 2056.3, "stop": 2062.55, "duration": 6.25}, {"text": "That is, Canada claimed it was not within the -- within the performance -- as in the performance of his duty.", "start": 2062.55, "stop": 2070.039, "duration": 7.49}, {"text": "And he would claim it was.", "start": 2070.039, "stop": 2072.598, "duration": 2.56}, {"text": "And -- and then there might be a deadlock between -- within the committee and it might be resolved between the Governments.", "start": 2072.598, "stop": 2078.379, "duration": 5.78}, {"text": "Does that happen as to Canada, the same country?", "start": 2078.379, "stop": 2081.127, "duration": 2.75}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, it could.", "start": 2081.127, "stop": 2082.672, "duration": 1.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But then the Court comes in, in case there is a trial in the -- in the Court.", "start": 2082.672, "stop": 2088.083, "duration": 5.41}, {"text": "The Court would also then go into this question whether on the merits as it were.", "start": 2088.083, "stop": 2092.571, "duration": 4.49}, {"text": "It was or wasn't in the performance of duty.", "start": 2092.571, "stop": 2094.678, "duration": 2.11}, {"text": "And would not be concluded by the military determination, is that it?", "start": 2094.678, "stop": 2098.629, "duration": 3.95}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that's true.", "start": 2098.629, "stop": 2099.643, "duration": 1.01}, {"text": "Although our State Department contends that there would still be a possibility of having it resolved on a diplomatic level --", "start": 2099.643, "stop": 2106.377, "duration": 6.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But that's the --", "start": 2106.377, "stop": 2107.385, "duration": 1.01}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- but if it didn't -- it couldn't be resolved there and they insisted upon it, then we would get down to the place where the courts would have to act.", "start": 2107.385, "stop": 2115.287, "duration": 7.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But as I understand it -- as I understand it, if I have it clearly.", "start": 2115.287, "stop": 2119.671, "duration": 4.38}, {"text": "You say that with reference to foreign troops Canadian, English, French, Australian or what not stationed in this country the same kind of -- of -- the same provisions of Treaty ,Protocol, agreement, et cetera, same kind of machinery, the same kind of determination and the same kind of relationship between the two Governments, is that right?", "start": 2119.671, "stop": 2144.371, "duration": 24.7}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 2144.371, "stop": 2145.296, "duration": 0.92}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Could I ask a question there?", "start": 2145.296, "stop": 2146.98, "duration": 1.68}, {"text": "Before the status of forces agreements went in to effect, what was the situation with respect to Canadians and Britishers in here?", "start": 2146.98, "stop": 2154.25, "duration": 7.27}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "We would not recognize any immunity from our laws, whatsoever.", "start": 2154.25, "stop": 2160.159, "duration": 5.91}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "We had visiting Canadians during the war before -- before the Status of force -- Forces Agreement went to effect received no immunity, did they?", "start": 2160.159, "stop": 2169.928, "duration": 9.77}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "We -- we did recognize providing there was a presidential determination that was necessary that they could court-martial such visiting troops.", "start": 2169.928, "stop": 2181.409, "duration": 11.48}, {"text": "But we never recognized any immunity from our courts either state or federal.", "start": 2181.409, "stop": 2187.278, "duration": 5.87}, {"text": "In fact, we expressly rejected any such concept.", "start": 2187.278, "stop": 2190.711, "duration": 3.43}, {"text": "And it was suggested by Senator Revercomb in the Senate when they were considering the -- this particular provision allowing their courts-martial to discipline their troops but that kind of a procedure instead of half the immunity.", "start": 2190.711, "stop": 2206.751, "duration": 16.04}, {"text": "At that time, he suggested that since the British were willing to grant complete immunity to us from their courts that we should make the same grant for visiting forces of the British within the United States.", "start": 2206.751, "stop": 2221.653, "duration": 14.9}, {"text": "And the Congress rejected that idea.", "start": 2221.653, "stop": 2225.564, "duration": 3.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "General -- oh, pardon me.", "start": 2225.564, "stop": 2227.109, "duration": 1.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Harold Burton", "textObjs": [{"text": "You point out in this case that waiver and if the waiver is valid, all this controversy drops out of sight doesn't it?", "start": 2227.109, "stop": 2233.127, "duration": 6.02}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2233.127, "stop": 2235, "duration": 1.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "General, if I may revert to the Canadian incident, so-called, again.", "start": 2235, "stop": 2242.34, "duration": 7.34}, {"text": "Assume that the Canadian forces were in this country and that an offense was committed identical with this in all respects.", "start": 2242.34, "stop": 2254.548, "duration": 12.21}, {"text": "Is there any precedent for determining or for saying whether this country would insist upon trying the defendant or whether it would turn him over to the Canadian Government?", "start": 2254.548, "stop": 2275.56, "duration": 21.01}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, the only precedent is the position of the Congress in this -- when this matter came up as to immunity that I know of and I can't conceive that our people would be satisfied to recognize any limitations of the constitution of -- of Canada or the statutes of Canada that would be binding upon the courts of this country in regard to whether we were trying or committing some homicide against our people.", "start": 2275.56, "stop": 2307.523, "duration": 31.96}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2307.523, "stop": 2308.342, "duration": 0.82}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's -- the Congress rejected the idea explicitly.", "start": 2308.342, "stop": 2313.193, "duration": 4.85}, {"text": "And we have only recognized this to the extent of the NATO force -- Status of --", "start": 2313.193, "stop": 2319.251, "duration": 6.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2319.251, "stop": 2319.474, "duration": 0.22}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- Forces Treaty --", "start": 2319.474, "stop": 2320.363, "duration": 0.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2320.363, "stop": 2320.655, "duration": 0.29}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- where there's considerable limitations on it and there are provisions for protecting --", "start": 2320.655, "stop": 2327.892, "duration": 7.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2327.892, "stop": 2328.035, "duration": 0.14}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- the interest of the respective countries.", "start": 2328.035, "stop": 2331.634, "duration": 3.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "But General what I -- what I really have in mind was this, not -- not a legal precedent but is there any administrative precedent in the country?", "start": 2331.634, "stop": 2341.647, "duration": 10.01}, {"text": "Has anything of this kind ever happened in this country to your knowledge where we acted one way or the other in a situation comparable to this?", "start": 2341.647, "stop": 2353.791, "duration": 12.14}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, I don't know of any --", "start": 2353.791, "stop": 2354.775, "duration": 0.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2354.775, "stop": 2355.501, "duration": 0.73}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- Mr. Chief Justice --", "start": 2355.501, "stop": 2356.247, "duration": 0.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2356.247, "stop": 2356.43, "duration": 0.18}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- but we'll examine that.", "start": 2356.43, "stop": 2358.372, "duration": 1.94}, {"text": "I haven't heard of any at all.", "start": 2358.372, "stop": 2359.535, "duration": 1.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2359.535, "stop": 2359.724, "duration": 0.19}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think it would have come to our attention during the consideration of this case.", "start": 2359.724, "stop": 2363.123, "duration": 3.4}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Mr. Solicitor, it's maybe actually the same question but I think you told us that in cases within primary Japanese jurisdiction, they've actually surrendered in 97% I think you said.", "start": 2363.123, "stop": 2378.691, "duration": 15.57}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, there were 5400 cases in one year's time ending November 30 of 1956, as I recall.", "start": 2378.691, "stop": 2385.295, "duration": 6.6}, {"text": "And 97.5% of the time the Japanese waived their primary rights.", "start": 2385.295, "stop": 2390.071, "duration": 4.78}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Which -- which is to say then, they send those soldiers over to our forces for court-martial?", "start": 2390.071, "stop": 2395.757, "duration": 5.69}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2395.757, "stop": 2396.169, "duration": 0.41}, {"text": "Now, mainly --", "start": 2396.169, "stop": 2396.72, "duration": 0.55}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Voice Overlap) --", "start": 2396.72, "stop": 2396.903, "duration": 0.18}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- those were traffic offenses and lesser offenses.", "start": 2396.903, "stop": 2401.132, "duration": 4.23}, {"text": "But there were some of real substance.", "start": 2401.132, "stop": 2403.412, "duration": 2.28}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, now since the Status of Forces Agreements, we have had foreign troops stationed to this country, have we not?", "start": 2403.412, "stop": 2410.526, "duration": 7.11}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2410.526, "stop": 2411.749, "duration": 1.22}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I take it some of them had gotten in difficulties of one kind or another?", "start": 2411.749, "stop": 2415.829, "duration": 4.08}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2415.829, "stop": 2416.668, "duration": 0.84}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What have we done?", "start": 2416.668, "stop": 2417.517, "duration": 0.85}, {"text": "Have we tried them or have we turned them over to their nations for court-martial?", "start": 2417.517, "stop": 2424.698, "duration": 7.18}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Our practice has not been so liberal.", "start": 2424.698, "stop": 2428.022, "duration": 3.32}, {"text": "We have not waived in very many cases.", "start": 2428.022, "stop": 2434.111, "duration": 6.09}, {"text": "There's one British case that I know of in which there was a waiver in order that -- in the homicide case where a soldier and a girl went out in a taxicab.", "start": 2434.111, "stop": 2448.566, "duration": 14.45}, {"text": "And they killed the taxicab driver.", "start": 2448.566, "stop": 2451.24, "duration": 2.67}, {"text": "And they -- the girl would obviously be a subject to the British law and the soldier would not under the Treaty and we waived in that situation.", "start": 2451.24, "stop": 2462.109, "duration": 10.87}, {"text": "They were both tried in Britain as", "start": 2462.109, "stop": 2465.344, "duration": 3.24}, {"text": "(Voice Overlap) --", "start": 2465.344, "stop": 2465.442, "duration": 0.1}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, then I -- what -- what I'm thinking of, in our own country where the foreign troops has been involved in incidents, which ordinarily would have been exclusively for disposition in American courts.", "start": 2465.442, "stop": 2480.248, "duration": 14.81}, {"text": "Have we disposed of them in American courts or have we turned them over to the nations for court-martial, as you tell as the Japanese had done in 97.5% of their case?", "start": 2480.248, "stop": 2492.126, "duration": 11.88}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Our way -- we haven't waived very often.", "start": 2492.126, "stop": 2494.532, "duration": 2.41}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "We have not.", "start": 2494.532, "stop": 2495.407, "duration": 0.88}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 2495.407, "stop": 2495.868, "duration": 0.46}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did --", "start": 2495.868, "stop": 2495.958, "duration": 0.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Solicitor, could you -- if I may carry on the Chief Justice's and Justice Brennan's questions.", "start": 2495.958, "stop": 2501.837, "duration": 5.88}, {"text": "Would it be possible between now and the time this argument closes to have had from the Department of Defense instances that specifically answer the questions put to you.", "start": 2501.837, "stop": 2513.15, "duration": 11.31}, {"text": "Namely, whether charges of major crimes by Canadians, where they're restricted to that, by Canadians stationed on our soil whether in such a case the question has arisen in which we saw or some State, this could normally be a state prosecution, what's -- in which some State of the Union asserted its local jurisdiction and Canada invoked her interest under the Treaty to have the alleged conflict turned over to its authorities, could that be done?", "start": 2513.15, "stop": 2550.228, "duration": 37.08}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm advised Mr. Justice by my associates that we have never been asked to waive.", "start": 2550.228, "stop": 2556.6, "duration": 6.37}, {"text": "That there are only three or four cases of such crimes that have occurred and we were never asked to waive.", "start": 2556.6, "stop": 2564.423, "duration": 7.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Where did they occur?", "start": 2564.423, "stop": 2565.348, "duration": 0.93}, {"text": "Did they occur on some base occupied by foreign troops in this country?", "start": 2565.348, "stop": 2569.994, "duration": 4.65}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'll try to follow that up.", "start": 2569.994, "stop": 2571.744, "duration": 1.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "What did you say?", "start": 2571.744, "stop": 2573, "duration": 1.26}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "We'll see if we have that information in our attention.", "start": 2573, "stop": 2574.829, "duration": 1.83}, {"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2574.829, "stop": 2575.008, "duration": 0.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I was wondering if they were similar unless that were the case.", "start": 2575.008, "stop": 2578.497, "duration": 3.49}, {"text": "Do we have any such situation in this country as there is in Japan for the rest of our troops?", "start": 2578.497, "stop": 2585.304, "duration": 6.81}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I'm getting into a field that I'm not an expert in regard to what maneuvering areas we have.", "start": 2585.304, "stop": 2594.469, "duration": 9.16}, {"text": "But, of course, we have here, I know, troops that are engaged in the -- in the study of various methods that we have in our Defense Department.", "start": 2594.469, "stop": 2606.768, "duration": 12.3}, {"text": "And they might very well be participating in maneuvers that our troops are engaged in but nothing of the character or the size are of a large number of troops that are involved in this particular --", "start": 2606.768, "stop": 2620.65, "duration": 13.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "What I had in mind was that we have in this print here or has there been in this country, foreign troops on a base where the foreign troops are required to guard the base inside the base and where a soldier has been put out on guard duty to guard a point on the base.", "start": 2620.65, "stop": 2646.04, "duration": 25.39}, {"text": "And where they were, under those circumstances, the -- this country has claimed the right to try this foreign soldier who has injured or killed some American who had reached the base.", "start": 2646.04, "stop": 2661.979, "duration": 15.94}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'll try to find out if there's any answer to that whether such an event has occurred, whether that has happened on any (Inaudible)", "start": 2661.979, "stop": 2669.22, "duration": 7.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is that substantial to what occurred here?", "start": 2669.22, "stop": 2674.294, "duration": 5.07}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I -- I'm --", "start": 2674.294, "stop": 2675.57, "duration": 1.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "I mean under the facts.", "start": 2675.57, "stop": 2677.071, "duration": 1.5}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Find the difference, Mr. Justice, in fact that if he was directed to guard certain weapon and certain field jackets.", "start": 2677.071, "stop": 2687.172, "duration": 10.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "But with regard to -- was he to guard that area in which the weapons were located?", "start": 2687.172, "stop": 2692.275, "duration": 5.1}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "The instructions were limited to the machine gun and the field jackets.", "start": 2692.275, "stop": 2698.793, "duration": 6.52}, {"text": "That was all of his instructions.", "start": 2698.793, "stop": 2701.378, "duration": 2.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did I understand that (Inaudible) is apprehended?", "start": 2701.378, "stop": 2705.189, "duration": 3.81}, {"text": "Did I understand that this territory, I'm talking about the geography, was not an exclusive American base which was partly shared with the Japanese?", "start": 2705.189, "stop": 2713.407, "duration": 8.22}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct, Mr. Justice.", "start": 2713.407, "stop": 2715.429, "duration": 2.02}, {"text": "That about 40% of the time, it was used by the Japanese Defense Forces.", "start": 2715.429, "stop": 2720.115, "duration": 4.69}, {"text": "It was used a balance of the portion of the time by the United States and the remainder which was a substantial portion of the time by the Japanese civilians in farming and other activities of various kinds.", "start": 2720.115, "stop": 2734.677, "duration": 14.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Was the base occupied by the troops of two different countries?", "start": 2734.677, "stop": 2738.786, "duration": 4.11}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well -- and also by the Japanese civilians.", "start": 2738.786, "stop": 2741.53, "duration": 2.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "What did they use it for?", "start": 2741.53, "stop": 2742.846, "duration": 1.32}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "For farming and all kinds of civilian activities.", "start": 2742.846, "stop": 2746.812, "duration": 3.97}, {"text": "It was a maneuver area as distinguished from the ordinary base.", "start": 2746.812, "stop": 2750.527, "duration": 3.72}, {"text": "It was a very -- it was a substantially large area.", "start": 2750.527, "stop": 2753.29, "duration": 2.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Was this a firing area?", "start": 2753.29, "stop": 2755.239, "duration": 1.95}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "This particular part was not a firing range.", "start": 2755.239, "stop": 2758.424, "duration": 3.18}, {"text": "But it was being used for maneuvers and there was firing on it during the first portions of the new --", "start": 2758.424, "stop": 2764.83, "duration": 6.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Practice firing?", "start": 2764.83, "stop": 2766.077, "duration": 1.25}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, they used live ammunitions at first.", "start": 2766.077, "stop": 2769.093, "duration": 3.02}, {"text": "And the commander found that that was unsafe because of the Japanese civilians in the area and instructed them to use blanks.", "start": 2769.093, "stop": 2776.016, "duration": 6.92}, {"text": "And they did use blanks from then on.", "start": 2776.016, "stop": 2777.501, "duration": 1.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "And it was then the duty while that was going on of someone to guard the gun at that point from other people and the government property?", "start": 2777.501, "stop": 2787.5, "duration": 10}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That was the instruction to guard the machine gun --", "start": 2787.5, "stop": 2789.263, "duration": 1.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did that include guarding this particular shell?", "start": 2789.263, "stop": 2794.582, "duration": 5.32}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well --", "start": 2794.582, "stop": 2795.332, "duration": 0.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Does -- does the record show that?", "start": 2795.332, "stop": 2797.056, "duration": 1.72}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "The record in the affidavit of the general counsel of Defense Department would show that the practice was to let the Japanese civilians pick up shells before and after this period for sometime.", "start": 2797.056, "stop": 2811.987, "duration": 14.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Will the case -- would the case be different in your judgment if the man had been given an express order, the soldier had been given express order that was conceded?", "start": 2811.987, "stop": 2824.093, "duration": 12.11}, {"text": "To guard this point, keep anybody from getting the shell.", "start": 2824.093, "stop": 2829.992, "duration": 5.9}, {"text": "They only dispute but further, he went further than his judgment that then good judgment require?", "start": 2829.992, "stop": 2838.796, "duration": 8.8}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think there would a very material difference in the case if he'd been instructed to guard this machine and these cartridges or these empty cartridges.", "start": 2838.796, "stop": 2850.603, "duration": 11.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "In that case, would the fact that there is a general immunity so that Japan could try if they can get it?", "start": 2850.603, "stop": 2859.761, "duration": 9.16}, {"text": "Would that be decisive in connection with whether it was the duty of -- of this country's commander --", "start": 2859.761, "stop": 2865.978, "duration": 6.22}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well --", "start": 2865.978, "stop": 2866.032, "duration": 0.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- if they had ordered him to do something, to protect him so far as they could from being tried in another country for that offense?", "start": 2866.032, "stop": 2873.004, "duration": 6.97}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Insofar as the law is concerned, there wouldn't be any difference insofar as -- of the Japanese right to try the man because he -- he would not be immune from their law.", "start": 2873.004, "stop": 2885.094, "duration": 12.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "But would there be any difference in the duty of the commanding officer who had required him to -- to do a specific thing?", "start": 2885.094, "stop": 2892.215, "duration": 7.12}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, then you come into what the rights are under the Treaty which they contend are invalid that the Government had no authority to make them and reduced the rights of the respondent by making them because they claim that he had absolute immunity from the Japanese law.", "start": 2892.215, "stop": 2912.531, "duration": 20.32}, {"text": "So that their case depends upon whether or not you find under international law that there was an absolute immunity from Japanese law.", "start": 2912.531, "stop": 2920.308, "duration": 7.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "The point of my inquiry was that the Government have to stand or does it stand at all on the proposition.", "start": 2920.308, "stop": 2927.959, "duration": 7.65}, {"text": "A soldier who's carried into a foreign country, given orders to obey orders and does obey orders.", "start": 2927.959, "stop": 2936.916, "duration": 8.96}, {"text": "That the country then has the right, that the commanding officers have the right after he's obeyed their orders and done what they said and turn him over to a foreign country to try him for having obeyed the orders of his commanding officer?", "start": 2936.916, "stop": 2953.254, "duration": 16.34}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that case isn't here but the -- the purpose of providing as the Government did in the agreements that in such cases they would have primary jurisdiction is to try to protect against that very situation.", "start": 2953.254, "stop": 2970.253, "duration": 17}, {"text": "So that he is not in conflict between the law of Japan.", "start": 2970.253, "stop": 2974.168, "duration": 3.91}, {"text": "And the fact that he has no immunity under that law.", "start": 2974.168, "stop": 2976.985, "duration": 2.82}, {"text": "And the direction of his superior for which he might be court-martialed if he didn't comply.", "start": 2976.985, "stop": 2983.215, "duration": 6.23}, {"text": "And that is the reason why the Government got the provision in the Treaty to try to protect that situation.", "start": 2983.215, "stop": 2989.716, "duration": 6.5}, {"text": "But even (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 2989.716, "stop": 2989.925, "duration": 0.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Wouldn't that be enough under those circumstances for the Government merely to get a provision to try to protect when he had the power to protect the soldier from them anyhow for obeying an order?", "start": 2989.925, "stop": 3002.905, "duration": 12.98}, {"text": "That is why I'm trying to find out if the Government is required to stand at all on the basis that if a soldier is carried to Japan or any other country, obeys orders for which he could be court-martialed if he disobeyed, the Government can then -- authorities can then turn him over voluntarily on any basis to be tried by another country.", "start": 3002.905, "stop": 3026.734, "duration": 23.83}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, all the way through the agreements and the law there's no question with what the Government has the right to decline to prosecute or -- or to waive the right to prosecute.", "start": 3026.734, "stop": 3043.077, "duration": 16.34}, {"text": "It's a governmental right.", "start": 3043.077, "stop": 3044.532, "duration": 1.45}, {"text": "It belongs to the State and not to the individual.", "start": 3044.532, "stop": 3049.174, "duration": 4.64}, {"text": "So that the Government has the right, even though he was acting in accordance with the instructions.", "start": 3049.174, "stop": 3054.997, "duration": 5.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "How do you go from that (Inaudible) to the position that the Government would have a right to subject the soldiers being tried by another country for obeying the orders of his commanding officer by which he could then court-martial if he disobeys?", "start": 3054.997, "stop": 3068.457, "duration": 13.46}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, the -- the difficulty with your question, Mr. Justice, is that the Government doesn't have any right to keep Japan from prosecuting someone who commits an offense against their law --", "start": 3068.457, "stop": 3082.907, "duration": 14.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "If they can get it him.", "start": 3082.907, "stop": 3083.713, "duration": 0.81}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- within their country.", "start": 3083.713, "stop": 3084.83, "duration": 1.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "If they can get it.", "start": 3084.83, "stop": 3086.59, "duration": 1.76}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 3086.59, "stop": 3087.986, "duration": 1.4}, {"text": "And they have the power either by insisting that he submit himself to their Courts as are -- the Chief Justice Marshall recognized in the Schooner Exchange case or by the use of force because there is no immunity from their laws.", "start": 3087.986, "stop": 3110.18, "duration": 22.19}, {"text": "And he commits the offense against their laws.", "start": 3110.18, "stop": 3113.262, "duration": 3.08}, {"text": "And we can't withhold him from that because there is no international law that recognizes that power.", "start": 3113.262, "stop": 3121.975, "duration": 8.71}, {"text": "Now, the only way we can possibly withhold him is to the extent that we can make treaties, which reduce that sovereign power of the other sovereign country.", "start": 3121.975, "stop": 3133.484, "duration": 11.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "What you're saying is that in any event if Japan forcibly got hold of an American, no matter how he got there, they would have unquestioned right to try him in their courts because we have held, this Court has held again and again that if you can get a man who is in one State into the other State where he committed the crime, it doesn't matter that he was -- as if were kidnapped.", "start": 3133.484, "stop": 3159.822, "duration": 26.34}, {"text": "So that if by force, Japan could get hold of an American who commits a crime in Japan, diplomatically, in international lawly speaking, we would have no case against him.", "start": 3159.822, "stop": 3173.328, "duration": 13.51}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right, Mr. Justice.", "start": 3173.328, "stop": 3174.243, "duration": 0.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And what you say is that to avoid these forcible encounters, a Treaty was made.", "start": 3174.243, "stop": 3178.521, "duration": 4.28}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 3178.521, "stop": 3181.444, "duration": 2.92}, {"text": "Now, even those writers in regard to international law that claimed that there's an implied immunity which they are unable to support by any showing that is recognized by any country of the world or practice, agree that that immunity can be waived by agreement of the country involved.", "start": 3181.444, "stop": 3206.613, "duration": 25.17}, {"text": "So, we have the situation where there is no -- under international law, there is no immunity, in the first place.", "start": 3206.613, "stop": 3214.013, "duration": 7.4}, {"text": "The most extreme position of the theorists in regard to, is that it could be waived by any kind of an agreement.", "start": 3214.013, "stop": 3225.018, "duration": 11.01}, {"text": "So that here we have action by the two countries who are unwilling to recognize immunity or leave it to that, provided -- provided in treaties, how it should be handled.", "start": 3225.018, "stop": 3239.29, "duration": 14.27}, {"text": "And we have the -- the Security Treaty, which was entered into between the two countries and was ratified by the action of the Senate.", "start": 3239.29, "stop": 3253.854, "duration": 14.56}, {"text": "And it came into force on April 28th of 1952.", "start": 3253.854, "stop": 3262.079, "duration": 8.23}, {"text": "Now, at the same time that the Congress considered that Security Treaty which provides in one -- in a paragraph of Article III, the conditions which shall govern the disposition of armed forces of the United States of America in and about Japan shall be determined by administrative agreements between two Governments.", "start": 3262.079, "stop": 3286.429, "duration": 24.35}, {"text": "At the same --", "start": 3286.429, "stop": 3287.254, "duration": 0.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is that the only provision --", "start": 3287.254, "stop": 3288.971, "duration": 1.72}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's the only --", "start": 3288.971, "stop": 3289.329, "duration": 0.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- in the Treaty --", "start": 3289.329, "stop": 3290.283, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "--only provision --", "start": 3290.283, "stop": 3290.79, "duration": 0.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- on which bearing our name that is a right --", "start": 3290.79, "stop": 3294.409, "duration": 3.62}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "In the Treaty --", "start": 3294.409, "stop": 3294.661, "duration": 0.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- to commit trial by the Japanese?", "start": 3294.661, "stop": 3297.723, "duration": 3.06}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, that's the only Treaty, Mr. Justice.", "start": 3297.723, "stop": 3299.542, "duration": 1.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Referring to the disposition of soldiers?", "start": 3299.542, "stop": 3301.988, "duration": 2.45}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "But as the same time that the Senate considered that Treaty, they had before it the Administrative Agreement which provided in detail for the Article XVII which gave exclusive jurisdiction to the United States.", "start": 3301.988, "stop": 3321.436, "duration": 19.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "What does that mean they had before it?", "start": 3321.436, "stop": 3324.005, "duration": 2.57}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "They -- they had and considered, it was already signed and they considered this administrative agreement.", "start": 3324.005, "stop": 3330.908, "duration": 6.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "You mean it was laid before or what, the whole Senate or the Committee on Foreign Relations?", "start": 3330.908, "stop": 3333.825, "duration": 2.92}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes and it -- and it was published twice in the congressional record.", "start": 3333.825, "stop": 3338.332, "duration": 4.51}, {"text": "It was considered in the debates.", "start": 3338.332, "stop": 3341.08, "duration": 2.75}, {"text": "And there was a motion made by Senator Jenner to have this Treaty, this Administrative Agreement brought back to the Senate for action by the Senate before it would become effective.", "start": 3341.08, "stop": 3355.686, "duration": 14.61}, {"text": "And that motion was rejected by a vote of 45 to 22.", "start": 3355.686, "stop": 3361.028, "duration": 5.34}, {"text": "So --", "start": 3361.028, "stop": 3361.052, "duration": 0.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Was that agreement with --", "start": 3361.052, "stop": 3362.646, "duration": 1.59}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I beg your pardon?", "start": 3362.646, "stop": 3363.8, "duration": 1.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "You said an Administrative Agreement between whom?", "start": 3363.8, "stop": 3366.14, "duration": 2.34}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Between Japan and the United States.", "start": 3366.14, "stop": 3369.355, "duration": 3.22}, {"text": "So that the Senate took --", "start": 3369.355, "stop": 3369.975, "duration": 0.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Isn't that the -- that that's the agreement under which all this is -- that's the agreement printed in your brief?", "start": 3369.975, "stop": 3375.906, "duration": 5.93}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, there's only one more step that I have to cover.", "start": 3375.906, "stop": 3378.938, "duration": 3.03}, {"text": "But before leaving the administrative agreement, I want to make it clear that a part of this motion that was made by Senator Jenner was that involved the issue of whether or not the President could declare a war or the Congress could declare a war and so forth.", "start": 3378.938, "stop": 3395.973, "duration": 17.03}, {"text": "But the issue was squarely in the motion.", "start": 3395.973, "stop": 3398.85, "duration": 2.88}, {"text": "Whether or not this particular administrative agreement, which had been signed prior to that time, had to be brought back to the Senate for action.", "start": 3398.85, "stop": 3408.189, "duration": 9.34}, {"text": "And the --", "start": 3408.189, "stop": 3408.312, "duration": 0.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "What was the date of the Treaty when the Treaty was ratified by the Senate?", "start": 3408.312, "stop": 3421.206, "duration": 12.89}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Its on page 7A, March 20th, 1952.", "start": 3421.206, "stop": 3426.612, "duration": 5.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "March 20th.", "start": 3426.612, "stop": 3428.084, "duration": 1.47}, {"text": "The -- the Administrative Agreement I gather from your appendix was signed at Tokyo, March 20, when?", "start": 3428.084, "stop": 3438.143, "duration": 10.06}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "1952.", "start": 3438.143, "stop": 3440.022, "duration": 1.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "The Administrative Agreement was signed at Tokyo on February 28th, 1952.", "start": 3440.022, "stop": 3445.622, "duration": 5.6}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 3445.622, "stop": 3446.925, "duration": 1.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "What you are saying it was entered into force, April 28th, 1952.", "start": 3446.925, "stop": 3452.953, "duration": 6.03}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Which was the same --", "start": 3452.953, "stop": 3453.454, "duration": 0.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That was after the Treaty was ratified by the Senate?", "start": 3453.454, "stop": 3457.265, "duration": 3.81}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, but they both entered into force at the same date.", "start": 3457.265, "stop": 3460.138, "duration": 2.87}, {"text": "You see that on page 7A, the Treaty entered and in force, the last line in April --", "start": 3460.138, "stop": 3465.957, "duration": 5.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh, yes.", "start": 3465.957, "stop": 3466.722, "duration": 0.77}, {"text": "So, what you're saying is, you may have the exact date for all I know, is that while the Security Treaty was under discussion on a motion or appropriate proceedings for ratifications, this Administrative Agreement signed -- signed so far as the Government of United States and the Government of Japan are concerned, it was completed, is that right?", "start": 3466.722, "stop": 3491.743, "duration": 25.02}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 3491.743, "stop": 3492.483, "duration": 0.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And that was before the Senate before it ratified the Treaty.", "start": 3492.483, "stop": 3497.189, "duration": 4.71}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 3497.189, "stop": 3497.819, "duration": 0.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And you further suggest that in connection with or prior to the ratification of the Treaty, a proposal was made by Senator Jenner, I think you said.", "start": 3497.819, "stop": 3508.591, "duration": 10.77}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 3508.591, "stop": 3510.083, "duration": 1.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "To the -- with a view to providing that the agreement should not get into -- become -- go into effect until the Senate itself formally -- whatever you had acted upon, is that right?", "start": 3510.083, "stop": 3521.001, "duration": 10.92}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Mr. Justice.", "start": 3521.001, "stop": 3522.367, "duration": 1.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Harold Burton", "textObjs": [{"text": "And then didn't the Treaty itself provide that same things would have to be done by administrative agreements?", "start": 3522.367, "stop": 3527.282, "duration": 4.91}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, it did.", "start": 3527.282, "stop": 3528.936, "duration": 1.65}, {"text": "Now --", "start": 3528.936, "stop": 3529.035, "duration": 0.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "The Treaty authorized entering into an administrative agreement.", "start": 3529.035, "stop": 3533.29, "duration": 4.26}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is correct, Mr. Justice.", "start": 3533.29, "stop": 3534.268, "duration": 0.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "An Administrative Agreement within process of adoption between the two countries in Japan.", "start": 3534.268, "stop": 3540.63, "duration": 6.36}, {"text": "It was adopted between the two countries.", "start": 3540.63, "stop": 3542.791, "duration": 2.16}, {"text": "It was made before the Senate.", "start": 3542.791, "stop": 3544.749, "duration": 1.96}, {"text": "It was sought to make the legal -- the legal validity of that agreement contingent upon Senate action and the Senate rejected that proposal.", "start": 3544.749, "stop": 3553.12, "duration": 8.37}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is correct and you (Voice Overlap) debate --", "start": 3553.12, "stop": 3554.486, "duration": 1.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Where --where is the provision now in the agreement on which you specifically relied (Inaudible) the page is what, for the specific provision?", "start": 3554.486, "stop": 3568.085, "duration": 13.6}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "On page 18A --", "start": 3568.085, "stop": 3573.808, "duration": 5.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Which part?", "start": 3573.808, "stop": 3574.319, "duration": 0.51}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- the bottom of page of 17A, Article XVII.", "start": 3574.319, "stop": 3582.562, "duration": 8.24}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "So, that's the sort of the Protocol (Inaudible)", "start": 3582.562, "stop": 3585.26, "duration": 2.7}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 3585.26, "stop": 3586.069, "duration": 0.81}, {"text": "(Voice Overlap) --", "start": 3586.069, "stop": 3586.109, "duration": 0.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's got plenty of details.", "start": 3586.109, "stop": 3588.181, "duration": 2.07}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, the agreement provides specifically, first, that the United States should have exclusive jurisdiction.", "start": 3588.181, "stop": 3597.218, "duration": 9.04}, {"text": "And in addition, that it shall have the right to waive any jurisdiction.", "start": 3597.218, "stop": 3602.47, "duration": 5.25}, {"text": "Then the agreement also commits the United States at the time of the signing of the agreement to give to Japan at its request whatever we do in regard to the NATO's -- NATO Status of Forces Agreement when -- when that is completed.", "start": 3602.47, "stop": 3622.374, "duration": 19.9}, {"text": "So --", "start": 3622.374, "stop": 3623.511, "duration": 1.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "But where is it written on that that shows that Congress when it looked at this agreement knew that it was agreed that a soldier who was charged for some offense in the performance of his duty could be tried by defense?", "start": 3623.511, "stop": 3637.902, "duration": 14.39}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, they were given due notice --", "start": 3637.902, "stop": 3639.815, "duration": 1.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Where was it given in this Treaty for this agreement.", "start": 3639.815, "stop": 3642.095, "duration": 2.28}, {"text": "That's what I understood you said.", "start": 3642.095, "stop": 3643.706, "duration": 1.61}, {"text": "Where was it given?", "start": 3643.706, "stop": 3645.658, "duration": 1.95}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "When the motion was under Jenner, it came up.", "start": 3645.658, "stop": 3648.978, "duration": 3.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Where was it given in the agreement if it was?", "start": 3648.978, "stop": 3651.745, "duration": 2.77}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's in Article XVII --", "start": 3651.745, "stop": 3653.167, "duration": 1.42}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, in Article XVII and on page 18A, in paragraph 2.", "start": 3653.167, "stop": 3668.309, "duration": 15.14}, {"text": "It was made clear that the -- that the United States was already committed by this agreement to give Japan, at its request, the benefits of the Status of Forces Agreement when those were consummated.", "start": 3668.309, "stop": 3685.924, "duration": 17.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "It would also provide a good way.", "start": 3685.924, "stop": 3688.055, "duration": 2.13}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 3688.055, "stop": 3688.691, "duration": 0.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "You said (Inaudible)", "start": 3688.691, "stop": 3690.739, "duration": 2.05}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Such jurisdiction may in any case be waived by the United States.", "start": 3690.739, "stop": 3694.444, "duration": 3.7}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that would pending to the coming into effect of the Status of Forces Agreement.", "start": 3694.444, "stop": 3697.794, "duration": 3.35}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 3697.794, "stop": 3698.822, "duration": 1.03}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, one -- one other thing, Mr. Solicitor, did you suggest that in the discussion of the Treaty itself, the Security Treaty, in Article III and more particular, is the language shall govern the disposition of armed forces that there is something in the debates or community hearings or something which indicates that the Congress included within disposition of the armed forces these matters covered by the administrative agreement?", "start": 3698.822, "stop": 3731.624, "duration": 32.8}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, in the -- the base in concerning the Jenner --", "start": 3731.624, "stop": 3737.711, "duration": 6.09}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 3737.711, "stop": 3737.761, "duration": 0.05}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- resolution or motion, Senator Sparkman sought to answer that motion.", "start": 3737.761, "stop": 3744.239, "duration": 6.48}, {"text": "And in his elaboration and he proceeded to say, described the criminal jurisdiction that would be involved that under the administrative agreement, we would have exclusive jurisdiction with the right to waive but we would have the duty and the obligation already committed by the Administrative Agreement to proceed to give Japan at its request the benefit of the NATO Status of Forces Agreement, whatever that was when it finally was -that applied and acted upon by the.", "start": 3744.239, "stop": 3775.904, "duration": 31.66}, {"text": "(Voice Overlap) --", "start": 3775.904, "stop": 3775.938, "duration": 0.03}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "And that can suggest this recognition that -- that that was the kind of Administrative Agreement dealing with \"the disposition of armed forces?\"", "start": 3775.938, "stop": 3783.954, "duration": 8.02}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 3783.954, "stop": 3784.322, "duration": 0.37}, {"text": "And he -- Senator Sparkman proceeded to describe the fact that there would be the problem with the criminal jurisdiction and that it was best handled by Administrative Agreement rather than having it come back to the Senate.", "start": 3784.322, "stop": 3797.179, "duration": 12.86}, {"text": "So that if the Senate was put on due notice that's set out in -- on page 46 and footnote 17, the -- a portion of Senator Sparkman's discussion with the matter.", "start": 3797.179, "stop": 3808.926, "duration": 11.75}, {"text": "So, the Senate had full notice of the nature of the administrative agreement.", "start": 3808.926, "stop": 3814.347, "duration": 5.42}, {"text": "In fact, that it gave exclusive jurisdiction during the interim, that it provided for a waiver, complete waiver and that the Government was already committed by that agreement to give them the benefit of the NATO Status of Forces Agreement.", "start": 3814.347, "stop": 3830.447, "duration": 16.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Harold Burton", "textObjs": [{"text": "In your brief, you also make the point do you not that the Treaty itself provided not merely that there's going to be the Administrative Agreement as to disposition of truth.", "start": 3830.447, "stop": 3839.45, "duration": 9}, {"text": "But the Administrative Agreement was to cover and determine conditions which shall govern this provision of truth, giving it more than disposition.", "start": 3839.45, "stop": 3847.012, "duration": 7.56}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes and it \"The Administrative Agreement sitting before the Senate at that time showed them and completely, exactly what it was.\"", "start": 3847.012, "stop": 3855.213, "duration": 8.2}, {"text": "They had the whole thing there before them.", "start": 3855.213, "stop": 3857.623, "duration": 2.41}, {"text": "It was considered in the Committee as is shown by our brief.", "start": 3857.623, "stop": 3862.557, "duration": 4.93}, {"text": "And it was also considered in connection with this motion.", "start": 3862.557, "stop": 3866.342, "duration": 3.79}, {"text": "And so, they knew that on the question of the conditions as to disposition of truth.", "start": 3866.342, "stop": 3871.625, "duration": 5.28}, {"text": "It isn't just disposition of conditions.", "start": 3871.625, "stop": 3874.18, "duration": 2.55}, {"text": "That it included not only criminal jurisdiction but taxation, the use of electric power, maneuver areas and many other considerations that had to be covered in order to handle problems of that character.", "start": 3874.18, "stop": 3887.66, "duration": 13.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "What was the state of the negotiations for the NATO agreement at the time that reference to it was made in this agreement, roughly that it's well advanced.", "start": 3887.66, "stop": 3899.47, "duration": 11.81}, {"text": "That --?", "start": 3899.47, "stop": 3901.349, "duration": 1.88}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "They had been signed and sent to the Senate not yet since to the Senate, Your Honor.", "start": 3901.349, "stop": 3907.112, "duration": 5.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Harold Burton", "textObjs": [{"text": "They had been signed in 1951 for a long time before this was pending.", "start": 3907.112, "stop": 3913.101, "duration": 5.99}, {"text": "And when was it actually acted upon by the Senate as a Treaty?", "start": 3913.101, "stop": 3918.483, "duration": 5.38}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "My recollection was in 1953.", "start": 3918.483, "stop": 3921.553, "duration": 3.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Harold Burton", "textObjs": [{"text": "But it was back acted on fully as a Treaty by the Senate in the (Inaudible)", "start": 3921.553, "stop": 3925.802, "duration": 4.25}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes and there was a discussion at that time of the effect that we were committed to Japan and would have to give them the benefit of it if they would request it --", "start": 3925.802, "stop": 3937.236, "duration": 11.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "The Protocol --", "start": 3937.236, "stop": 3937.339, "duration": 0.1}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- because the Senate had full knowledge of that.", "start": 3937.339, "stop": 3939.646, "duration": 2.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "The Protocol says that the NATO Treaty became effective August 23, 1953, does it not?", "start": 3939.646, "stop": 3947.165, "duration": 7.52}, {"text": "Page 23A of your brief?", "start": 3947.165, "stop": 3948.849, "duration": 1.68}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct, Mr. Justice.", "start": 3948.849, "stop": 3949.887, "duration": 1.04}, {"text": "Then we have to -- in order to get the complete steps, we have to go to the Protocol, which was executed at the request of Japan as we had already agreed and were committed by the administrative agreement, which gave them the benefit of the same provisions of the Status of Forces Agreement.", "start": 3949.887, "stop": 3976.012, "duration": 26.13}, {"text": "We have such agreements with over 49 different countries throughout the world.", "start": 3976.012, "stop": 3981.94, "duration": 5.93}, {"text": "And Japan got exactly the same, no -- no less and no more than all of the other NATO countries in connection with this Protocol.", "start": 3981.94, "stop": 3994.392, "duration": 12.45}, {"text": "Then we get down to the provisions of a Protocol carrying this particular matter.", "start": 3994.392, "stop": 4001.951, "duration": 7.56}, {"text": "And that is set at -- set forth on pages 24A and 25A.", "start": 4001.951, "stop": 4009.102, "duration": 7.15}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "The Protocol as such never got to the Board of Senate I take it.", "start": 4009.102, "stop": 4013.655, "duration": 4.55}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, I --", "start": 4013.655, "stop": 4015.981, "duration": 2.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "Except to the fact that paragraph 1 of Article XVII declared its conclusion upon (Inaudible)", "start": 4015.981, "stop": 4027.757, "duration": 11.78}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 4027.757, "stop": 4027.93, "duration": 0.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible) into the administrative agreement?", "start": 4027.93, "stop": 4030.697, "duration": 2.77}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, we feel -- the Government feels that the United States was committed and that the Senate had this before in the Administrative Agreement at -- and the Security Treaty so that it knew that it was committed by those instruments to give the benefit of the NATO Status of Forces Agreement to Japan whenever that came into effect.", "start": 4030.697, "stop": 4059.515, "duration": 28.82}, {"text": "And it was also called to the attention of the -- the Senate at the time that they acted upon the NATO Status of Forces Agreement that they were already committed to give the same thing in a -- to Japan.", "start": 4059.515, "stop": 4073.625, "duration": 14.11}, {"text": "So, they had full knowledge about both of them.", "start": 4073.625, "stop": 4076.85, "duration": 3.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Solicitor General, I assume that you had no protocols.", "start": 4076.85, "stop": 4081.983, "duration": 5.13}, {"text": "Then you'd have exclusive jurisdiction in the United States, wouldn't you?", "start": 4081.983, "stop": 4085.32, "duration": 3.34}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 4085.32, "stop": 4086.613, "duration": 1.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "And the right of waiver?", "start": 4086.613, "stop": 4088.038, "duration": 1.43}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 4088.038, "stop": 4089.201, "duration": 1.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "So, the proposal that you may carry it and even under the provisional administrative agreement, (Inaudible) protocols, still the United States could waive and turn over a soldier to the receiving country.", "start": 4089.201, "stop": 4105.687, "duration": 16.49}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is correct, Mr. Justice.", "start": 4105.687, "stop": 4108.006, "duration": 2.32}, {"text": "We take the position that without any agreements whatsoever, Japan would be able to prosecute.", "start": 4108.006, "stop": 4115.111, "duration": 7.1}, {"text": "And there were two British sailors that they proceeded to prosecute against the objection of Britain.", "start": 4115.111, "stop": 4122.774, "duration": 7.66}, {"text": "So, they asserted that they would recognize no immunity under the law or from their law.", "start": 4122.774, "stop": 4131.915, "duration": 9.14}, {"text": "And without any Security Treaty, Administrative Agreement or Protocol, they could proceed to prosecute by reason of international law because there would be no immunity.", "start": 4131.915, "stop": 4144.367, "duration": 12.45}, {"text": "That the --", "start": 4144.367, "stop": 4144.694, "duration": 0.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Subject -- subject to an argument by us, diplomatic I take it, that they were certain implied implications from allowing our troops down there.", "start": 4144.694, "stop": 4155.377, "duration": 10.68}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, we could make that argument.", "start": 4155.377, "stop": 4157.319, "duration": 1.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 4157.319, "stop": 4157.728, "duration": 0.41}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "But we don't -- we are unwilling to concede it to anybody as far as we're concerned.", "start": 4157.728, "stop": 4161.519, "duration": 3.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "What I'm saying is that -- I just want to be meticulously active about the statement you made subject to a claim that there was an implication of consent to have us try by a court-martial somebody who did something within the military jurisdiction of this country.", "start": 4161.519, "stop": 4179.277, "duration": 17.76}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, there would still be --", "start": 4179.277, "stop": 4180.166, "duration": 0.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "This is very important.", "start": 4180.166, "stop": 4181.661, "duration": 1.49}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Voice Overlap) --", "start": 4181.661, "stop": 4181.701, "duration": 0.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "This is a provision in case of conflict between the two countries about which there are conflicts in every lower court in the United States practically everyday of the year of some provision in case of conflict about the facts.", "start": 4181.701, "stop": 4193.63, "duration": 11.93}, {"text": "Is that correct?", "start": 4193.63, "stop": 4194.336, "duration": 0.71}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Mr. Justice.", "start": 4194.336, "stop": 4197.04, "duration": 2.7}, {"text": "Then the Security Treaty and the Administrative Agreement gave the United States the exclusive jurisdiction with the right to waive so it could have acted just as it was done here under that waiver.", "start": 4197.04, "stop": 4212.463, "duration": 15.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "It wouldn't have to have the NATO extension that --", "start": 4212.463, "stop": 4216.076, "duration": 3.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 4216.076, "stop": 4216.295, "duration": 0.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- under your theory?", "start": 4216.295, "stop": 4217.104, "duration": 0.81}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 4217.104, "stop": 4218.347, "duration": 1.24}, {"text": "Then after the Protocol came into effect, it went further insofar as the United States was concerned.", "start": 4218.347, "stop": 4226.509, "duration": 8.16}, {"text": "The Government does not recognize that the respondent had a right as to whether or not the United States would exercise jurisdiction or waive jurisdiction.", "start": 4226.509, "stop": 4239.011, "duration": 12.5}, {"text": "That is a right that belongs to the State and so recognized under the decisions.", "start": 4239.011, "stop": 4245.301, "duration": 6.29}, {"text": "But the State gained the benefit under the Protocol of the right to -- to have a primary jurisdiction in certain situations and to decline jurisdiction and to waive jurisdiction.", "start": 4245.301, "stop": 4260.099, "duration": 14.8}, {"text": "And the -- in this case, the Government has, after considering all of the facts, decided to exercise this right to decline jurisdiction under section 3 (c) and proceed to notify Japan and that is the act in question.", "start": 4260.099, "stop": 4278.437, "duration": 18.34}, {"text": "And there's a -- a number of cases in which the Court -- this Court has taken the position that it will not review that action if it finds that there is a discretion in the Executive to exercise, that it will not proceed to review it and determine whether it should have been decided one way or another because it has not considered the Court competent to pass upon those various questions of foreign relations.", "start": 4278.437, "stop": 4308.502, "duration": 30.07}, {"text": "The Executive had to review this particular situation, the problems as to this respondent, the fact that Japan had waived in some 97.5% of all of these cases.", "start": 4308.502, "stop": 4320.889, "duration": 12.39}, {"text": "That we have secured waivers in 72% of some 3200 cases over a period of three years from all of the NATO Status of Forces countries including Japan.", "start": 4320.889, "stop": 4333.945, "duration": 13.06}, {"text": "And the effect on the foreign relations of this country and Japan, all of those factors and the knowledge that the executive had -- had to come into play and be considered in determining whether to define jurisdiction or to waive jurisdiction.", "start": 4333.945, "stop": 4352.08, "duration": 18.14}, {"text": "And since it was a sovereign right that belonged to the State, the Executive proceeded to exercise it on behalf of the best interest of the State.", "start": 4352.08, "stop": 4362.018, "duration": 9.94}, {"text": "And we think that there could be no abusive discretion here.", "start": 4362.018, "stop": 4364.905, "duration": 2.89}, {"text": "That there's a reasonable action.", "start": 4364.905, "stop": 4367.225, "duration": 2.32}, {"text": "And it was a --a right of the State and -- and the Executive proceeded to exercise it.", "start": 4367.225, "stop": 4374.91, "duration": 7.68}, {"text": "I'd like to reserve the balance of my time.", "start": 4374.91, "stop": 4380.451, "duration": 5.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Robinson.", "start": 4380.451, "stop": 4394.915, "duration": 14.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "May it please this honorable Court.", "start": 4394.915, "stop": 4398.839, "duration": 3.92}, {"text": "It is with deep respect and humility that I speak for the men and women in the armed services of the United States overseas and for those of us at home who live at this sellout program whereby the constitutional rights of American soldiers overseas are stripped from them is wrong.", "start": 4398.839, "stop": 4432.444, "duration": 33.61}, {"text": "It is these men on whom this nation relies for its security, for its honor and for the respective place, which this nation has in the family of nations.", "start": 4432.444, "stop": 4449.782, "duration": 17.34}, {"text": "Directly involved is the person of a humble citizen born in Illinois because this Court well knows the issues in this case probe deeper and the question here to be established will determine the course that this nation will follow for a long time to come.", "start": 4449.782, "stop": 4478.273, "duration": 28.49}, {"text": "This Court recognized the importance of the question by calling this special session.", "start": 4478.273, "stop": 4487.538, "duration": 9.26}, {"text": "Upon the right, record of this case, there is no issue of fact.", "start": 4487.538, "stop": 4495.556, "duration": 8.02}, {"text": "They were stipulated in the court below.", "start": 4495.556, "stop": 4498.765, "duration": 3.21}, {"text": "They are very simple.", "start": 4498.765, "stop": 4505.415, "duration": 6.65}, {"text": "An 18-year old boy born not far at all from the birthplace of Abraham Lincoln, volunteered to serve in the armed forces of this nation, wherever deemed necessary.", "start": 4505.415, "stop": 4525.844, "duration": 20.43}, {"text": "Although, he was uneducated, the spirit of freedom and the realization of the dangers confronted this (Inaudible) without caused him to don the uniform of the American soldier of which he is justly proud.", "start": 4525.844, "stop": 4541.34, "duration": 15.5}, {"text": "He is not militaristic.", "start": 4541.34, "stop": 4544.23, "duration": 2.89}, {"text": "He did what many of the youth of this nation have done before him.", "start": 4544.23, "stop": 4549.618, "duration": 5.39}, {"text": "He desired to do his best, return to his home in hopes that upon return, it may be more secure and that he may live a more abundant life.", "start": 4549.618, "stop": 4562.144, "duration": 12.53}, {"text": "At the end of his three-year term, conditions being what they are, he volunteered for an additional term.", "start": 4562.144, "stop": 4577.471, "duration": 15.33}, {"text": "And the duty which was assigned him was not the easy task.", "start": 4577.471, "stop": 4583.493, "duration": 6.02}, {"text": "He was the foot soldier carrying the gun and the other instruments of destruction.", "start": 4583.493, "stop": 4591.433, "duration": 7.94}, {"text": "During his second term of enlistment and on January 30th, 1957, after a morning of target practice and sweat, he was ordered to guard American property on an American firing range known as Camp Weir.", "start": 4591.433, "stop": 4610.109, "duration": 18.68}, {"text": "Trespassers came on to serve their own purposes.", "start": 4610.109, "stop": 4616.584, "duration": 6.47}, {"text": "He fired an empty shell to scare them off, not to kill.", "start": 4616.584, "stop": 4621.197, "duration": 4.61}, {"text": "And unfortunately, that act resulted in the death of a Japanese national.", "start": 4621.197, "stop": 4629.183, "duration": 7.99}, {"text": "Our Government, being fully competent and equipped to judge on our standards, and I stress on our standards, thus it's a very material issue in this case, whether he acted rightfully or wrongfully, then decided to let the Japanese Court pass judgment on this situation.", "start": 4629.183, "stop": 4654.636, "duration": 25.45}, {"text": "Admittedly, none of the constitutional safeguards which he would have or which he has as American citizen though worthy to be tried before an American Court would be carried forward with him.", "start": 4654.636, "stop": 4667.945, "duration": 13.31}, {"text": "I note that -- that the Solicitor General has been eloquently silent on the subject of the type of trial he would receive and what would happen to this boy before the Japanese Court, who according to the press, have been clamoring to have him brought before them for justice as they understand it and in accordance with their system and under their code which an American lawyer practicing in Germany has declared is an absolute joke and one of the most antiquated systems of -- of justice that exist in any nation of this world, including some of the Arab countries.", "start": 4667.945, "stop": 4705.716, "duration": 37.77}, {"text": "Now, how did this all come about?", "start": 4705.716, "stop": 4708.253, "duration": 2.54}, {"text": "And by what method did the United States, acting through the Executive, turn this boy or agree to turn this boy over to the Japanese Government to stand trial on their system of law?", "start": 4708.253, "stop": 4729.059, "duration": 20.81}, {"text": "And what is the historical background?", "start": 4729.059, "stop": 4736.516, "duration": 7.46}, {"text": "It started in this fashion.", "start": 4736.516, "stop": 4744.545, "duration": 8.03}, {"text": "Before the termination of World War I, the United States exercised exclusive jurisdiction over its troops in every country of the world.", "start": 4744.545, "stop": 4755.737, "duration": 11.19}, {"text": "Despite the statements by the Solicitor of the contrary, the fact remains that the United States exercised exclusive jurisdiction over its troops wherever they were stationed.", "start": 4755.737, "stop": 4767.835, "duration": 12.1}, {"text": "That is the law.", "start": 4767.835, "stop": 4769.559, "duration": 1.72}, {"text": "That has been the international law.", "start": 4769.559, "stop": 4771.889, "duration": 2.33}, {"text": "It has been recognized from time immemorial.", "start": 4771.889, "stop": 4775.567, "duration": 3.68}, {"text": "And on the subject of immunity --", "start": 4775.567, "stop": 4777.37, "duration": 1.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, on that -- on that question, was there any differentiation between where we were conquering troops or --", "start": 4777.37, "stop": 4786.183, "duration": 8.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 4786.183, "stop": 4786.481, "duration": 0.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- whether we were there as hosts?", "start": 4786.481, "stop": 4788.3, "duration": 1.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 4788.3, "stop": 4788.539, "duration": 0.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "I mean as -- as guests of the (Inaudible)", "start": 4788.539, "stop": 4791.163, "duration": 2.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "There was no difference, Your Honor.", "start": 4791.163, "stop": 4793.028, "duration": 1.87}, {"text": "And I -- I -- on that subject --", "start": 4793.028, "stop": 4794.911, "duration": 1.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is there authority to -- what -- what authority do you -- do you point to --", "start": 4794.911, "stop": 4799.716, "duration": 4.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I will in just one moment, Your Honor.", "start": 4799.716, "stop": 4801.161, "duration": 1.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 4801.161, "stop": 4801.857, "duration": 0.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Robinson, may I ask you?", "start": 4801.857, "stop": 4803.547, "duration": 1.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 4803.547, "stop": 4803.885, "duration": 0.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "In those instances, while -- were there covenants under which --", "start": 4803.885, "stop": 4808.283, "duration": 4.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 4808.283, "stop": 4809.231, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "There were not?", "start": 4809.231, "stop": 4809.748, "duration": 0.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "There were not.", "start": 4809.748, "stop": 4810.315, "duration": 0.57}, {"text": "There was the international law.", "start": 4810.315, "stop": 4811.949, "duration": 1.63}, {"text": "And I'll get to that in one moment.", "start": 4811.949, "stop": 4813.738, "duration": 1.79}, {"text": "And while the subject matter of the immunity from foreign jurisdiction both -- both personal and territorial was to be taken up by Mr. Carroll and he will go into that thoroughly, I want to make a few brief comments on that subject in passing since Your Honor raises the issue.", "start": 4813.738, "stop": 4829.905, "duration": 16.17}, {"text": "As we well know, international law does not change overnight or within a few years or because of views entertained by the Solicitor General, the Attorney General or some underlings working in the State Department.", "start": 4829.905, "stop": 4844.495, "duration": 14.59}, {"text": "Let me tell you, Your Honors, what the United States position was, only three and a half to four years before we had this complete turnabout.", "start": 4844.495, "stop": 4858.976, "duration": 14.48}, {"text": "And it appears in the congressional record, a hearing before the House of Representatives had on July 26th, 1935.", "start": 4858.976, "stop": 4871.138, "duration": 12.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is that in your brief?", "start": 4871.138, "stop": 4872.703, "duration": 1.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 4872.703, "stop": 4873.741, "duration": 1.04}, {"text": "This is something Your -- Your Honor must know we burned the midnight oil until dawn.", "start": 4873.741, "stop": 4877.701, "duration": 3.96}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Voice Overlap) --", "start": 4877.701, "stop": 4877.821, "duration": 0.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "And this is one thing I only uncovered the last day or so.", "start": 4877.821, "stop": 4882.01, "duration": 4.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Could you give us a memorandum, please, of that and any other citations that you --", "start": 4882.01, "stop": 4887.61, "duration": 5.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm not referring to a citation.", "start": 4887.61, "stop": 4889.151, "duration": 1.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, -- or -- or any other authority that you referred to so that we may have it (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 4889.151, "stop": 4894.927, "duration": 5.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, I will.", "start": 4894.927, "stop": 4896.631, "duration": 1.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "What are you reading from that congressional record?", "start": 4896.631, "stop": 4898.544, "duration": 1.91}, {"text": "What --", "start": 4898.544, "stop": 4899.512, "duration": 0.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm reading from the brief, which was submitted by the United -- I'm not reading from them.", "start": 4899.512, "stop": 4903.343, "duration": 3.83}, {"text": "I'm just going to give you one of the text of it, a brief which the United States Government gave to the Canadian Supreme Court on this question of immunity from foreign jurisdiction.", "start": 4903.343, "stop": 4914.147, "duration": 10.8}, {"text": "And these were the facts.", "start": 4914.147, "stop": 4917.362, "duration": 3.22}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Where was that in the brief?", "start": 4917.362, "stop": 4918.29, "duration": 0.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It appears, Your Honor, beginning at page 404 of the hearings on H.J.Res.309, Part 1.", "start": 4918.29, "stop": 4933.627, "duration": 15.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "H.J .Res.", "start": 4933.627, "stop": 4935.271, "duration": 1.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Res.309.", "start": 4935.271, "stop": 4937.428, "duration": 2.16}, {"text": "And the dates on the bottom are July 13th, 14th, 19th, 20th, 21st and 26th.", "start": 4937.428, "stop": 4944.513, "duration": 7.09}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What year?", "start": 4944.513, "stop": 4945.909, "duration": 1.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm sorry, Your Honor.", "start": 4945.909, "stop": 4946.698, "duration": 0.79}, {"text": "They're 1955.", "start": 4946.698, "stop": 4948.189, "duration": 1.49}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "1955.", "start": 4948.189, "stop": 4948.945, "duration": 0.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "1955, yes, sir.", "start": 4948.945, "stop": 4952.011, "duration": 3.07}, {"text": "The law up to that point had always been clear and insofar as we know it still is clear.", "start": 4952.011, "stop": 4958.576, "duration": 6.56}, {"text": "But this is what happened in this Canadian situation.", "start": 4958.576, "stop": 4962.854, "duration": 4.28}, {"text": "The Canadian Government was confronted with a large number of American forces on their territory.", "start": 4962.854, "stop": 4970.098, "duration": 7.24}, {"text": "It was not conquered territory.", "start": 4970.098, "stop": 4972.975, "duration": 2.88}, {"text": "It is our neighbor, our friendly neighbor and a country whose laws are more nearly akin to ours than any in the world.", "start": 4972.975, "stop": 4983.731, "duration": 10.76}, {"text": "And our today, armed forces is a naturally -- it would be on bill of actions.", "start": 4983.731, "stop": 4987.373, "duration": 3.64}, {"text": "That'd be events that would give rise to crime.", "start": 4987.373, "stop": 4992.247, "duration": 4.87}, {"text": "And the issue was before the Canadian parliament as to whether or not they may make a law which would deprive our forces in Canada of the immunity which they enjoyed under the recognized principle of international law.", "start": 4992.247, "stop": 5011.281, "duration": 19.03}, {"text": "And the case -- the problem was submitted to the highest court of Canada.", "start": 5011.281, "stop": 5017.479, "duration": 6.2}, {"text": "I don't know the title of the court.", "start": 5017.479, "stop": 5021.624, "duration": 4.14}, {"text": "And the -- the Attorney General, and as far as I really must write it quickly.", "start": 5021.624, "stop": 5026.144, "duration": 4.52}, {"text": "Then I know the chief justice of that court asked for a memorandum on the subject from the United States.", "start": 5026.144, "stop": 5033.661, "duration": 7.52}, {"text": "And we submitted a memorandum.", "start": 5033.661, "stop": 5035.236, "duration": 1.57}, {"text": "It was either 1944 or 1945 or somewhere in that year, just a few years before this turnabout came.", "start": 5035.236, "stop": 5042.775, "duration": 7.54}, {"text": "And the memorandum -- in the covering letter which came from obligation to the -- to the highest court of Canada, this is the position which our Government then took, “I have the honor to enclose for such purposes you may care to make, a memorandum which sets forth the views of the United States Government on the right under international law of the members of the armed forces of the United States on Canadian territory with the consent of the Canadian Government, to immunity from local jurisdiction and criminal matters.”", "start": 5042.775, "stop": 5078.618, "duration": 35.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "Does that say on Canadian file with the consent?", "start": 5078.618, "stop": 5082.101, "duration": 3.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 5082.101, "stop": 5083.592, "duration": 1.49}, {"text": "I -- I think I read it correctly.", "start": 5083.592, "stop": 5084.938, "duration": 1.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "What's the date of this memorandum?", "start": 5084.938, "stop": 5087.517, "duration": 2.58}, {"text": "You said 1955 and 1945 (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 5087.517, "stop": 5088.783, "duration": 1.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm sorry -- I'm sorry, Your Honor.", "start": 5088.783, "stop": 5089.698, "duration": 0.91}, {"text": "The exact date of the transcript of letter was May 27th, 1943.", "start": 5089.698, "stop": 5093.837, "duration": 4.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "1943.", "start": 5093.837, "stop": 5094.543, "duration": 0.71}, {"text": "This was during the war.", "start": 5094.543, "stop": 5096.197, "duration": 1.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "This was during the war.", "start": 5096.197, "stop": 5097.748, "duration": 1.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "1955 as evidenced was the date of the publication in which you found it.", "start": 5097.748, "stop": 5101.668, "duration": 3.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct, Your Honor.", "start": 5101.668, "stop": 5102.374, "duration": 0.71}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 5102.374, "stop": 5103.15, "duration": 0.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 5103.15, "stop": 5103.989, "duration": 0.84}, {"text": "It came to light, as far as I was concerned, only upon my getting the chance after working on this brief under much pressure to read some of these congressional hearings and I may say in passing.", "start": 5103.989, "stop": 5115.672, "duration": 11.68}, {"text": "They are rich with information, which is directly contrary.", "start": 5115.672, "stop": 5119.448, "duration": 3.78}, {"text": "I don't like to say it but it's a fact, directly contrary to the information which my adversary has been given to this Court today.", "start": 5119.448, "stop": 5126.848, "duration": 7.4}, {"text": "Not only contrary.", "start": 5126.848, "stop": 5128.353, "duration": 1.51}, {"text": "Senators have stated in -- in other congressional hearings that information which Mr. Rankin has given and which other high government officials has given.", "start": 5128.353, "stop": 5137.292, "duration": 8.94}, {"text": "I don't like to say it, but it's a fact that it was false, untrue and misleading.", "start": 5137.292, "stop": 5143.727, "duration": 6.43}, {"text": "And I will get to that subject in just a few moments.", "start": 5143.727, "stop": 5148.115, "duration": 4.39}, {"text": "This -- and I only want to quote from a few extracts of this brief and then see what happens from that point on when you wanted to serve some selfish purpose of some small man in the State Department selling out on jurisdiction, they had to reverse the rule to suit their own purposes.", "start": 5148.115, "stop": 5166.21, "duration": 18.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That includes the President of the United States.", "start": 5166.21, "stop": 5167.983, "duration": 1.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir, I said --", "start": 5167.983, "stop": 5168.285, "duration": 0.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Voice Overlap) --", "start": 5168.285, "stop": 5168.534, "duration": 0.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- the small boy in State Department.", "start": 5168.534, "stop": 5170.695, "duration": 2.16}, {"text": "It does not include the President of the United States.", "start": 5170.695, "stop": 5172.415, "duration": 1.72}, {"text": "[Laughs]", "start": 5172.415, "stop": 5173.572, "duration": 1.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the President of the United States is supporting this.", "start": 5173.572, "stop": 5176.753, "duration": 3.18}, {"text": "You hit too hard --", "start": 5176.753, "stop": 5176.777, "duration": 0.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understand that.", "start": 5176.777, "stop": 5177.427, "duration": 0.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- without being discourteous to the officials of the (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 5177.427, "stop": 5179.375, "duration": 1.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I have no intentions of being discourteous to the President of the United States, but he too may be wrong, Your Honor.", "start": 5179.375, "stop": 5183.391, "duration": 4.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "He may be wrong but you can courteous in arguing even serious questions.", "start": 5183.391, "stop": 5186.875, "duration": 3.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Very well, sir.", "start": 5186.875, "stop": 5195.464, "duration": 8.59}, {"text": "Quote on page 405 of the congressional record.\"", "start": 5195.464, "stop": 5206.795, "duration": 11.33}, {"text": "One of these rules recognized immunity from local jurisdiction in criminal matters of members of the armed forces of a foreign sovereignty on the territory with mission or by the consent of the local sovereign.\"", "start": 5206.795, "stop": 5218.607, "duration": 11.81}, {"text": "They cite many, many cases and then make this concluding statement.", "start": 5218.607, "stop": 5226.934, "duration": 8.33}, {"text": "This, mind you, is a brief that the United States.", "start": 5226.934, "stop": 5230.195, "duration": 3.26}, {"text": "I don't know whether it's pled by justice or the judge.", "start": 5230.195, "stop": 5232.545, "duration": 2.35}, {"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 5232.545, "stop": 5233.921, "duration": 1.38}, {"text": "But either one I do know that during the war days --", "start": 5233.921, "stop": 5235.337, "duration": 1.42}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Voice Overlap) --", "start": 5235.337, "stop": 5237.09, "duration": 1.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- there was liaison between the Justice Department and the Judge Advocate's Department.", "start": 5237.09, "stop": 5242.518, "duration": 5.43}, {"text": "And I think at that time Mr. Justice Clark was the Attorney General.", "start": 5242.518, "stop": 5247.065, "duration": 4.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, I -- I became Attorney General on 1945.", "start": 5247.065, "stop": 5249.335, "duration": 2.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "1945?", "start": 5249.335, "stop": 5250.18, "duration": 0.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "Two years --", "start": 5250.18, "stop": 5250.263, "duration": 0.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "To which I blame this on you, Your Honor.", "start": 5250.263, "stop": 5252.162, "duration": 1.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "I was in (Inaudible) at that time.", "start": 5252.162, "stop": 5254.796, "duration": 2.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "But there was liaison because I personally was in the War Department in Washington at that time and I moved many times to the Justice Department to clear on some of these memorandums that had to deal with international properties.", "start": 5254.796, "stop": 5266.656, "duration": 11.86}, {"text": "In any event, it was represented to be the views of the United States when it was sent to the high court of Canada.", "start": 5266.656, "stop": 5275.49, "duration": 8.83}, {"text": "“The authorities whom we have quoted and others who will be referred to here and after unqualifiedly recognized the right of members of the armed forces of a foreign state on the territory with the permission or consent of the local sovereign to immunity from local jurisdiction for any offense they commit.”", "start": 5275.49, "stop": 5299.514, "duration": 24.02}, {"text": "This is nowadays the opinion of the vast majority of writers on international law.", "start": 5299.514, "stop": 5305.933, "duration": 6.42}, {"text": "They then go on to say there are a few dissenting voices and they point out -- they say first these dissenting voices are, one, they're against the weight, the decided weight of authority.", "start": 5305.933, "stop": 5320.835, "duration": 14.9}, {"text": "Two, they are too vague and indefinite to be considered rules of law.", "start": 5320.835, "stop": 5325.332, "duration": 4.5}, {"text": "Three, they are contrary to the principles on which immunity from local jurisdiction for the forces is based.", "start": 5325.332, "stop": 5332.715, "duration": 7.38}, {"text": "And there's a -- there's a fourth reason that they criticized the dissent.", "start": 5332.715, "stop": 5336.198, "duration": 3.48}, {"text": "Four, they are not expresses.", "start": 5336.198, "stop": 5339.459, "duration": 3.26}, {"text": "They are not expressive of the international practice.", "start": 5339.459, "stop": 5342.644, "duration": 3.19}, {"text": "And I'll agree to the Canadian Court concluded with the statement that there was absolute immunity under international law recognizing from time immemorial of the visiting force upon the sovereign territory of another nation whether they are in there by consent or by force.", "start": 5342.644, "stop": 5365.978, "duration": 23.33}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think you told us earlier we were going -- refer to some authorities who supported that.", "start": 5365.978, "stop": 5371.36, "duration": 5.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "This -- this is a brief.", "start": 5371.36, "stop": 5372.964, "duration": 1.6}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, I know.", "start": 5372.964, "stop": 5373.362, "duration": 0.4}, {"text": "I -- you said earlier, I think, that you would refer us to some authorities who supported that proposition.", "start": 5373.362, "stop": 5380.463, "duration": 7.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't -- I don't follow Your Honor's question.", "start": 5380.463, "stop": 5383.129, "duration": 2.67}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "You've just stated that the proposition was, it was an absolute immunity.", "start": 5383.129, "stop": 5387.606, "duration": 4.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 5387.606, "stop": 5388.332, "duration": 0.73}, {"text": "And this is the -- there -- there are wholly --", "start": 5388.332, "stop": 5390.145, "duration": 1.81}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is this the only authority you have in that brief?", "start": 5390.145, "stop": 5391.318, "duration": 1.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- almost they're cited in the brief.", "start": 5391.318, "stop": 5392.6, "duration": 1.28}, {"text": "There are many of them cited under point 2 of the brief.", "start": 5392.6, "stop": 5394.777, "duration": 2.18}, {"text": "There's a whole series of authorities.", "start": 5394.777, "stop": 5397.116, "duration": 2.34}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "And you agree?", "start": 5397.116, "stop": 5397.915, "duration": 0.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 5397.915, "stop": 5399.068, "duration": 1.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Where is that please?", "start": 5399.068, "stop": 5401.325, "duration": 2.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It -- it begins at page -- it begins at -- it's -- its points 2 and 3 of the brief.", "start": 5401.325, "stop": 5412.559, "duration": 11.23}, {"text": "It cites a whole series of (Inaudible) this brief which the Government submitted to the -- which our Government submitted to the Canadian Government, I didn't know about it at that time, but certainly, its as strong in authority as I could get.", "start": 5412.559, "stop": 5424.24, "duration": 11.68}, {"text": "This was the official position of the United States taken only a few years before they decided to take another position.", "start": 5424.24, "stop": 5431.391, "duration": 7.15}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is that the position that we've taken on reference to foreign troops in our soil?", "start": 5431.391, "stop": 5437.286, "duration": 5.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "The question with respect to foreign troops on our soil, Your Honor, I don't know.", "start": 5437.286, "stop": 5442.31, "duration": 5.02}, {"text": "Insofar as I know, we have never tried any foreign troops that happened to be stationed on our soil.", "start": 5442.31, "stop": 5449.252, "duration": 6.94}, {"text": "Besides the number of troops that are on our soil are insignificant as one of the -- how -- of one of the members of the House said, “When we have large bodies of troops on our soil, they would not be here to protect us.", "start": 5449.252, "stop": 5460.342, "duration": 11.09}, {"text": "They will be here to make war with us.”", "start": 5460.342, "stop": 5462.066, "duration": 1.72}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible) during the war, Mr. Robinson.", "start": 5462.066, "stop": 5466.563, "duration": 4.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "As far as I know, Your Honor, we didn't try them.", "start": 5466.563, "stop": 5469.535, "duration": 2.97}, {"text": "I think -- I think we permitted them to be returned to their -- to the -- to the Governments from which they came for appropriate trial.", "start": 5469.535, "stop": 5477.492, "duration": 7.96}, {"text": "I -- I know of no case where we tried a --a foreign soldier in the United States.", "start": 5477.492, "stop": 5481.422, "duration": 3.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Harold Burton", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Robinson, in your brief, the first case that you cited, the Schooner Exchange case in support of your -- of your proposition --", "start": 5481.422, "stop": 5486.838, "duration": 5.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 5486.838, "stop": 5487.385, "duration": 0.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Harold Burton", "textObjs": [{"text": "And the other side cites the same case.", "start": 5487.385, "stop": 5489.075, "duration": 1.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 5489.075, "stop": 5490.149, "duration": 1.07}, {"text": "And I'll tell you how that came about in just a few moments.", "start": 5490.149, "stop": 5493.046, "duration": 2.9}, {"text": "And for your information, Your Honor, in this Canadian brief when they told the Canadian high court that there was absolute immunity from jurisdiction of the local Government over the foreign forces, they cite as their first authority for that proposition, the Schooner Exchange case.", "start": 5493.046, "stop": 5507.212, "duration": 14.17}, {"text": "And now they're cited for the other proposition.", "start": 5507.212, "stop": 5509.061, "duration": 1.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "How do you dispose of this language in the Schooner Exchange case as I -- I see it cited on -- or quoted on page 23 of the Government's brief.", "start": 5509.061, "stop": 5519.426, "duration": 10.37}, {"text": "This language of Chief Justice Marshall.", "start": 5519.426, "stop": 5522.249, "duration": 2.82}, {"text": "The jurisdiction of courts is a branch to that which is possessed by the nation as an independent sovereign power.", "start": 5522.249, "stop": 5529.799, "duration": 7.55}, {"text": "The jurisdiction of the nation within its own territory is necessarily exclusive and absolute.", "start": 5529.799, "stop": 5537.828, "duration": 8.03}, {"text": "It is susceptible of no limitation, not imposed by itself.", "start": 5537.828, "stop": 5543.325, "duration": 5.5}, {"text": "Any restriction upon it, to writing validity from an external source would imply a diminution of its sovereignty to the extent of the restriction and in investment of that sovereignty to the same extent in that power which could impose such restriction.", "start": 5543.325, "stop": 5562.046, "duration": 18.72}, {"text": "All exceptions therefore to the full and complete power of a nation within its own territory must be traced up to the consent of the nation itself.", "start": 5562.046, "stop": 5572.286, "duration": 10.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 5572.286, "stop": 5572.787, "duration": 0.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "They can fall from no other legitimate source.", "start": 5572.787, "stop": 5575.664, "duration": 2.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct --", "start": 5575.664, "stop": 5576.334, "duration": 0.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "And how do you dispose --", "start": 5576.334, "stop": 5577.183, "duration": 0.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Voice Overlap)", "start": 5577.183, "stop": 5577.296, "duration": 0.11}, {"text": "-- the matter of law under international law.", "start": 5577.296, "stop": 5580.328, "duration": 3.03}, {"text": "That consent was implied by the fact that they agreed to have the foreign troops upon their territory.", "start": 5580.328, "stop": 5586.22, "duration": 5.89}, {"text": "There's no question about the general principle that a nation is sovereign if it's its own -- own territory.", "start": 5586.22, "stop": 5591.578, "duration": 5.36}, {"text": "And the only waive in a limited sovereignty is by consent.", "start": 5591.578, "stop": 5596.035, "duration": 4.46}, {"text": "But under international law when it permitted foreign troops to enter upon its territory, it gave consent.", "start": 5596.035, "stop": 5605.048, "duration": 9.01}, {"text": "That is the rule of international law or that is the position which our Government took with the Canadian Government.", "start": 5605.048, "stop": 5611.159, "duration": 6.11}, {"text": "That is the position, which has been supported time and time again.", "start": 5611.159, "stop": 5614.602, "duration": 3.44}, {"text": "And that is the doctrine, which they teach the West Point Military Academy.", "start": 5614.602, "stop": 5621.103, "duration": 6.5}, {"text": "And -- and to give you one of the short quote from what has been taught up there that appears in the brief as shown and the consent is given when you authorize the foreign -- the foreign troops to come on to your territory.", "start": 5621.103, "stop": 5635.012, "duration": 13.91}, {"text": "\"All the members of the United States Army is subject to jurisdiction of its court-martial.", "start": 5635.012, "stop": 5639.34, "duration": 4.33}, {"text": "Yet, while the army is within the territory limits of the United States, the civil or federal and state, have concurrent jurisdiction over the members.", "start": 5639.34, "stop": 5646.601, "duration": 7.26}, {"text": "However, the jurisdiction of courts-martial becomes exclusive when the army leaves its own territorial limits as for instance when the army marches through a friendly country or stationed therein.", "start": 5646.601, "stop": 5659.793, "duration": 13.19}, {"text": "In such cases, consent of the friendly Government from a -- or exemption from its civil and criminal jurisdiction is assumed as a matter, of course.", "start": 5659.793, "stop": 5669.793, "duration": 10}, {"text": "Should it deny this consent and act otherwise, it would give rise to serious consequences.\"", "start": 5669.793, "stop": 5676.573, "duration": 6.78}, {"text": "We told that to the Canadian Government.", "start": 5676.573, "stop": 5678.585, "duration": 2.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 5678.585, "stop": 5679.116, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That has been the principle until the beginning of this program to surrender jurisdiction.", "start": 5679.116, "stop": 5686.386, "duration": 7.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did the Canadian Government accept that view here?", "start": 5686.386, "stop": 5688.131, "duration": 1.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, there was -- there were dissents.", "start": 5688.131, "stop": 5690.845, "duration": 2.71}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did -- did the Canadian Government accept that view then?", "start": 5690.845, "stop": 5692.674, "duration": 1.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, there were some dissents --", "start": 5692.674, "stop": 5693.579, "duration": 0.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "In the decision of its Supreme Court?", "start": 5693.579, "stop": 5695.621, "duration": 2.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 5695.621, "stop": 5696.45, "duration": 0.83}, {"text": "There were some --", "start": 5696.45, "stop": 5696.48, "duration": 0.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Are you sure about that?", "start": 5696.48, "stop": 5698.492, "duration": 2.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, I only know what I read in the congressional record and I can read --", "start": 5698.492, "stop": 5701.18, "duration": 2.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that's not a good place to find out what a court decides.", "start": 5701.18, "stop": 5704.558, "duration": 3.38}, {"text": "[Laughs]", "start": 5704.558, "stop": 5704.691, "duration": 0.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, -- but -- but when -- but when the congressional record quotes from the opinions of the judges up there, I assume that what our Congressmen put into the record and what the record contains is accurate.", "start": 5704.691, "stop": 5722.492, "duration": 17.8}, {"text": "And that is what we're saying.", "start": 5722.492, "stop": 5724.822, "duration": 2.33}, {"text": "It is true that if we have --", "start": 5724.822, "stop": 5726.452, "duration": 1.63}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "What's the citation to the Canadian decision?", "start": 5726.452, "stop": 5728.917, "duration": 2.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't know.", "start": 5728.917, "stop": 5729.554, "duration": 0.64}, {"text": "I don't know but if -- if the case, the name of the case is referred to, the brief is in here.", "start": 5729.554, "stop": 5734.797, "duration": 5.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, is that document you're reading from is part of the congressional record, a report of a House of Committee or is it a speech of some Congressman?", "start": 5734.797, "stop": 5744.871, "duration": 10.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 5744.871, "stop": 5747.401, "duration": 2.53}, {"text": "It -- it is a -- it is a full -- it is the full text of the brief which was submitted to the Canadian Government, the full text quoted --", "start": 5747.401, "stop": 5756.973, "duration": 9.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh.", "start": 5756.973, "stop": 5756.997, "duration": 0.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- right in the congressional record.", "start": 5756.997, "stop": 5757.975, "duration": 0.98}, {"text": "We know very often they put complete documents in it.", "start": 5757.975, "stop": 5761.792, "duration": 3.82}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, but who put it in?", "start": 5761.792, "stop": 5762.796, "duration": 1}, {"text": "That's the --", "start": 5762.796, "stop": 5763.84, "duration": 1.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Some congressman I assume.", "start": 5763.84, "stop": 5764.918, "duration": 1.08}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, doesn't it appear?", "start": 5764.918, "stop": 5765.747, "duration": 0.83}, {"text": "You have the record.", "start": 5765.747, "stop": 5773.028, "duration": 7.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "This was 1955 you have said after the Treaty with Japan of 1952, is that it?", "start": 5773.028, "stop": 5780.235, "duration": 7.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm -- I'm sorry, Your Honor.", "start": 5780.235, "stop": 5781.491, "duration": 1.26}, {"text": "I --", "start": 5781.491, "stop": 5781.561, "duration": 0.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "You said, you're reading from a document --", "start": 5781.561, "stop": 5784.344, "duration": 2.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 5784.344, "stop": 5784.742, "duration": 0.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- which is evidently dated if I followed you, as I've tried hard to, in 1955, is that correct?", "start": 5784.742, "stop": 5792.04, "duration": 7.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 5792.04, "stop": 5792.939, "duration": 0.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "So that in 1955, some Congressman put in views, which are in direct conflict with the Treaty with Japan of few years earlier, is that right?", "start": 5792.939, "stop": 5801.595, "duration": 8.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 5801.595, "stop": 5802.997, "duration": 1.4}, {"text": "What the Congressman did was took an official document --", "start": 5802.997, "stop": 5806.609, "duration": 3.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, I understand that.", "start": 5806.609, "stop": 5807.623, "duration": 1.01}, {"text": "But by that time that this Treaty which you are to discuss it before us and that was then in existence, is that it?", "start": 5807.623, "stop": 5816.119, "duration": 8.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "If you -- if Your Honor is referring to the executive agreement, I will say but it was not achieved.", "start": 5816.119, "stop": 5820.467, "duration": 4.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, but there was a Treaty which referred -- which authorized the making of a -- an executive agreement, a joint agreement which was before the Congress, in the Senate when it ratified the Treaty.", "start": 5820.467, "stop": 5832.663, "duration": 12.2}, {"text": "And what I'm suggesting is that your reading of document, which somebody put in, did not yet had his name, with somebody put in, in 1955 to give expression to views which are in conflict with the Treaty adopted by this -- ratified by the Senate a few years earlier, is that right?", "start": 5832.663, "stop": 5849.563, "duration": 16.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 5849.563, "stop": 5850.631, "duration": 1.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, then put me straight.", "start": 5850.631, "stop": 5853.1, "duration": 2.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "The -- the -- these were hearings before the Congress to -- to -- and for -- on -- on the subject matter of a resolution to call upon the powers that be -- to modify or change the status of forces agreements.", "start": 5853.1, "stop": 5879.635, "duration": 26.53}, {"text": "The main basis to be that having been that in view of the experience with these agreements.", "start": 5879.635, "stop": 5884.635, "duration": 5}]}, {"speakerName": "Harold Burton", "textObjs": [{"text": "You refer to them as agreement not as a treaty, was it not?", "start": 5884.635, "stop": 5886.89, "duration": 2.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "They're not treaties, Your Honor.", "start": 5886.89, "stop": 5888.063, "duration": 1.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Harold Burton", "textObjs": [{"text": "The NATO -- the --", "start": 5888.063, "stop": 5889.266, "duration": 1.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "The NATO -- the NATO --", "start": 5889.266, "stop": 5889.757, "duration": 0.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Harold Burton", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- NATO Status of Forces?", "start": 5889.757, "stop": 5891.099, "duration": 1.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "NATO -- the NATO Status of Forces Agreements within one category.", "start": 5891.099, "stop": 5895.045, "duration": 3.95}, {"text": "This is not a NATO -- NATO Status of Forces Agreement.", "start": 5895.045, "stop": 5897.611, "duration": 2.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Harold Burton", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the NATO Status of Forces Agreement was a treaty, was it not?", "start": 5897.611, "stop": 5901.687, "duration": 4.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 5901.687, "stop": 5902.268, "duration": 0.58}, {"text": "It was a treaty but the question here and we will come to it, whether or not we have the right to enter into such a treaty.", "start": 5902.268, "stop": 5909.081, "duration": 6.81}, {"text": "I am not -- I am not at all of the opinion that the Congress of the United States with the President can enter into a treaty with any nation, which would deprive any of our citizens of constitutional rights.", "start": 5909.081, "stop": 5921.776, "duration": 12.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Harold Burton", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, there were difference of opinion in the Senate about that treaty but it was adopted by a two-thirds vote, was it not?", "start": 5921.776, "stop": 5927.363, "duration": 5.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 5927.363, "stop": 5928.54, "duration": 1.18}, {"text": "And one senator said that it -- it happened in the middle of a summer when the general NATO of forces treaties were submitted along with this one on the jurisdiction that it was hurriedly passed on.", "start": 5928.54, "stop": 5939.833, "duration": 11.29}, {"text": "And he said, “he wishes he had never voted for it”, and on that subject, Your Honor.", "start": 5939.833, "stop": 5947.183, "duration": 7.35}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Am I going to find out who put that in the record?", "start": 5947.183, "stop": 5950.1, "duration": 2.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 5950.1, "stop": 5950.899, "duration": 0.8}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Who was it?", "start": 5950.899, "stop": 5952.162, "duration": 1.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm sorry but they were interruptions, Your Honor.", "start": 5952.162, "stop": 5954.552, "duration": 2.39}, {"text": "A -- a Representative Bow -- Representative Bow.", "start": 5954.552, "stop": 5956.872, "duration": 2.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "Representative Bow.", "start": 5956.872, "stop": 5957.846, "duration": 0.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir, Representative Bow -- Congressman Bow of Ohio.", "start": 5957.846, "stop": 5964.584, "duration": 6.74}, {"text": "On the subject of how this Treaty came how this -- of the NATO Status of Forces Agreements came into effect, it was being debated.", "start": 5964.584, "stop": 5971.632, "duration": 7.05}, {"text": "It was a very serious subject.", "start": 5971.632, "stop": 5974.233, "duration": 2.6}, {"text": "It was tied in with the other agreements.", "start": 5974.233, "stop": 5980.098, "duration": 5.86}, {"text": "And when it appeared that it would not pass, the President of the United States sent a personal letter.", "start": 5980.098, "stop": 5987.02, "duration": 6.92}, {"text": "And this is what it says.", "start": 5987.02, "stop": 5990.437, "duration": 3.42}, {"text": "And I would say that relying on the text of that letter, “Even if I were a senator, I would vote as the President request.”", "start": 5990.437, "stop": 5997.655, "duration": 7.22}, {"text": "Now, this is his language, “I certainly appreciate the concern of those who fear that these agreements might subject American soldiers overseas to systems of civil justice foreign to our own traditions.", "start": 5997.655, "stop": 6016.243, "duration": 18.59}, {"text": "I do not fear -- I do not share such fears, however, because of the many years experience I have had in command of American troops overseas.", "start": 6016.243, "stop": 6026.095, "duration": 9.85}, {"text": "That experience convinces me that our friends abroad will continue to cooperate as they have in the past in turning over those charged with offenses against their laws to our own military courts for trial.”", "start": 6026.095, "stop": 6043.19, "duration": 17.09}, {"text": "That is what President Eisenhower said in a personal letter to the Senate in order to get the necessary two-thirds vote to get these NATO treaties through.", "start": 6043.19, "stop": 6054.201, "duration": 11.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's what these -- that's what these treaties -- that's what the NATO Treaty and the agreement, which we have before us permits.", "start": 6054.201, "stop": 6061.457, "duration": 7.26}, {"text": "And under which we are told 97.5% of the cases that have arisen in Japan have been so turned over at our request.", "start": 6061.457, "stop": 6070.231, "duration": 8.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, that's --", "start": 6070.231, "stop": 6070.474, "duration": 0.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "So that the President was not only -- was not only telling his history but he was indulging in verified prophecy.", "start": 6070.474, "stop": 6077.609, "duration": 7.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think, Your Honor, from my knowledge of what has happened to our boys overseas in the foreign jails where they're still permitted to use the guillotine and the firing squad and the solitary confinement that the President was not making a very fine prophecy.", "start": 6077.609, "stop": 6090.252, "duration": 12.64}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "What countries are those?", "start": 6090.252, "stop": 6092.334, "duration": 2.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "You are permitted to use the guillotine in certain countries in Europe.", "start": 6092.334, "stop": 6095.29, "duration": 2.96}, {"text": "I think France is one.", "start": 6095.29, "stop": 6096.394, "duration": 1.1}, {"text": "Some countries still permit the firing squad or the --", "start": 6096.394, "stop": 6099.142, "duration": 2.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "We use that in this country, don't we?", "start": 6099.142, "stop": 6104.335, "duration": 5.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't think so.", "start": 6104.335, "stop": 6105.751, "duration": 1.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think the State of Utah uses that -- uses that.", "start": 6105.751, "stop": 6109.254, "duration": 3.5}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "What was that?", "start": 6109.254, "stop": 6110.819, "duration": 1.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "If -- if this Court thinks that's constitutional and proper, well I -- I won't go any further in that circuit but.", "start": 6110.819, "stop": 6117.772, "duration": 6.95}, {"text": "[Laughs]", "start": 6117.772, "stop": 6118.71, "duration": 0.94}, {"text": "this -- the -- the subject matter of the 97% of the waivers, Your Honor, is meaningless unless we know how many of those that where there was a waiver did the United States military actually try.", "start": 6118.71, "stop": 6134.125, "duration": 15.41}, {"text": "I tried to get those figures.", "start": 6134.125, "stop": 6135.401, "duration": 1.28}, {"text": "They wouldn't supply them.", "start": 6135.401, "stop": 6136.366, "duration": 0.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't understand that.", "start": 6136.366, "stop": 6137.911, "duration": 1.55}, {"text": "The question is --", "start": 6137.911, "stop": 6138.044, "duration": 0.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I -- I'll rephrase it.", "start": 6138.044, "stop": 6139.605, "duration": 1.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- the question -- I don't understand that.", "start": 6139.605, "stop": 6142.76, "duration": 3.16}, {"text": "As I understand that, I am subject to correction, I know nothing except what I hear and -- and read.", "start": 6142.76, "stop": 6149.543, "duration": 6.78}, {"text": "As I understand it, in 97.5% percent of the cases when we asked Japan to turnover people who might be subject to their jurisdiction, they consented.", "start": 6149.543, "stop": 6163.418, "duration": 13.88}, {"text": "And I don't have to see what the point is of saying you want to know what we did with them.", "start": 6163.418, "stop": 6168.516, "duration": 5.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's important --", "start": 6168.516, "stop": 6168.54, "duration": 0.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "--The question is with Japan -- Japan surrendered her authority.", "start": 6168.54, "stop": 6172.132, "duration": 3.59}, {"text": "That's the vital thing.", "start": 6172.132, "stop": 6173.822, "duration": 1.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's -- it's important -- it's important for this reason, Your Honor.", "start": 6173.822, "stop": 6177.843, "duration": 4.02}, {"text": "Most of these cases that I venture I guess that 99% of them were automobile accident cases on the streets of Japan where Japanese authorities picked up the -- the GI or maybe -- maybe -- who probably had too much too drink or didn't, couldn't read the Japanese sign saying go right.", "start": 6177.843, "stop": 6193.232, "duration": 15.39}, {"text": "He went left to some such event.", "start": 6193.232, "stop": 6194.667, "duration": 1.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Are you speaking -- are you speaking by the book or the (Inaudible)", "start": 6194.667, "stop": 6198.644, "duration": 3.98}, {"text": "Are those -- is that statement of yours verifiable by the instances or is this just a surmise of yours?", "start": 6198.644, "stop": 6205.079, "duration": 6.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I was trying to get those figures, Your Honor.", "start": 6205.079, "stop": 6207.159, "duration": 2.08}, {"text": "I can't get them.", "start": 6207.159, "stop": 6208.939, "duration": 1.78}, {"text": "It appears that it appears in the congressional record that most of these cases involved automobile accidents.", "start": 6208.939, "stop": 6216.259, "duration": 7.32}, {"text": "And then let's assume there's a -- there's a $3 slash on automobile and Japanese authorities have and we say turn them back to us.", "start": 6216.259, "stop": 6223.03, "duration": 6.77}, {"text": "And our military authorities get them.", "start": 6223.03, "stop": 6225.44, "duration": 2.41}, {"text": "They count that as a waiver.", "start": 6225.44, "stop": 6227.005, "duration": 1.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 6227.005, "stop": 6227.417, "duration": 0.41}, {"text": "I should think the Government would be able to tell this Court whether 97.5% of -- of those that in which that Japan waived what she was entitled to try were automobile cases.", "start": 6227.417, "stop": 6238.562, "duration": 11.14}, {"text": "That ought not to be too difficult to ascertain.", "start": 6238.562, "stop": 6240.673, "duration": 2.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "The -- the vast majority of them are automobile cases, Your Honor.", "start": 6240.673, "stop": 6242.85, "duration": 2.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "As long as that a vast majority?", "start": 6242.85, "stop": 6244.162, "duration": 1.31}, {"text": "That's shaving if you are honest with it.", "start": 6244.162, "stop": 6247.234, "duration": 3.07}, {"text": "[Laughs]", "start": 6247.234, "stop": 6248.318, "duration": 1.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm -- I'm not trying to shave it down, Your Honor.", "start": 6248.318, "stop": 6250.767, "duration": 2.45}, {"text": "The -- the figure of 97% is actually meaningless unless we know whether or not there was -- they -- they were offenses which we then brought them to -- for which we brought them to trial.", "start": 6250.767, "stop": 6260.096, "duration": 9.33}, {"text": "And there's another fact in which you want --", "start": 6260.096, "stop": 6260.895, "duration": 0.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But we didn't have those grievance if such should be against this country for not enforcing the law of an authority then if Japan and 97.5% of the cases in which we requested that they turn over those accused of wrongdoing were turned over.", "start": 6260.895, "stop": 6278.867, "duration": 17.97}, {"text": "The fact is that Japan and 97.5% of the cases, they've turned over.", "start": 6278.867, "stop": 6282.495, "duration": 3.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Even -- even using your own -- Your Honor's own argument as a basis of Japan sending over 99 and nine-tenths percent, if under our law, we may not turn over one.", "start": 6282.495, "stop": 6292.782, "duration": 10.29}, {"text": "That's the issue we're concerned with here.", "start": 6292.782, "stop": 6295.927, "duration": 3.14}, {"text": "And for Your Honor's information, I think for the past --", "start": 6295.927, "stop": 6298.174, "duration": 2.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "It depends on your argument.", "start": 6298.174, "stop": 6300.087, "duration": 1.91}, {"text": "I can understand the -- to proposition to the last event.", "start": 6300.087, "stop": 6304.087, "duration": 4}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 6304.087, "stop": 6304.852, "duration": 0.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But it was you who made the argument that these people are being cruelly treated.", "start": 6304.852, "stop": 6309.313, "duration": 4.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'll get to that.", "start": 6309.313, "stop": 6309.526, "duration": 0.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And in backward countries of France and Great Britain and Japan.", "start": 6309.526, "stop": 6312.661, "duration": 3.14}, {"text": "That was your argument.", "start": 6312.661, "stop": 6313.48, "duration": 0.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'll -- I'll get to that, Your Honor and show what -- what treatment they're getting.", "start": 6313.48, "stop": 6316.84, "duration": 3.36}, {"text": "But its not in -- it's not in the course of my argument at the present time.", "start": 6316.84, "stop": 6319.448, "duration": 2.61}, {"text": "I -- I cannot cover the whole ground at the one time.", "start": 6319.448, "stop": 6320.929, "duration": 1.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Don't think it's very desirable, needlessly, to reflect on other countries where their civilizations in many respects are not inferior to our own.", "start": 6320.929, "stop": 6330.101, "duration": 9.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's very well.", "start": 6330.101, "stop": 6330.727, "duration": 0.63}, {"text": "But we must remember that 100 years ago, Japan wasn't even open for civilization.", "start": 6330.727, "stop": 6335.295, "duration": 4.57}, {"text": "Now, we must -- we must also remember that the Japanese courtesy and the Japanese ideas of -- of what is right and what's wrong, we saw an example of it on December 7th, 1941.", "start": 6335.295, "stop": 6346.767, "duration": 11.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And 150 years ago, we dealt with witches.", "start": 6346.767, "stop": 6349.346, "duration": 2.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "We're not talking about a hundred --", "start": 6349.346, "stop": 6349.797, "duration": 0.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Voice Overlap)", "start": 6349.797, "stop": 6350.324, "duration": 0.53}, {"text": "-- history of other -- of our civilization.", "start": 6350.324, "stop": 6352.147, "duration": 1.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "We're not talking about 150 years ago.", "start": 6352.147, "stop": 6354.006, "duration": 1.86}, {"text": "We're talking about the current generation.", "start": 6354.006, "stop": 6358.414, "duration": 4.41}, {"text": "To me, it is weird to take American soldiers who have sworn to sacrifice their life, if necessary, to defend the Constitution of the United States and turn them over to a foreign country for trial, needlessly, and strip them their very constitutional right.", "start": 6358.414, "stop": 6375.031, "duration": 16.62}, {"text": "Now, if that's the rule, which this Court reached the status at present, there's nothing I can say.", "start": 6375.031, "stop": 6378.971, "duration": 3.94}, {"text": "I'm here to --", "start": 6378.971, "stop": 6379.2, "duration": 0.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you think any Member of this Court doesn't agree to the proposition that nobody can be deprived of his constitutional rights?", "start": 6379.2, "stop": 6385.745, "duration": 6.55}, {"text": "Do you think any Member of this Court --", "start": 6385.745, "stop": 6387.329, "duration": 1.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm sure not, Your Honor.", "start": 6387.329, "stop": 6387.588, "duration": 0.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- needs to be instructed on that point?", "start": 6387.588, "stop": 6389.471, "duration": 1.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm sure not.", "start": 6389.471, "stop": 6389.624, "duration": 0.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "The question is what are our constitutional rights?", "start": 6389.624, "stop": 6392.507, "duration": 2.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "When this Court expressed -- if the last word from this Court on what our constitutional rights appeared in Reid against Covert only decided here just about a month ago.", "start": 6392.507, "stop": 6401.941, "duration": 9.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And what did that decide?", "start": 6401.941, "stop": 6403.138, "duration": 1.2}, {"text": "Would you state what that decided?", "start": 6403.138, "stop": 6407.009, "duration": 3.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "On the vote that party as they decide.", "start": 6407.009, "stop": 6409.14, "duration": 2.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That was not a Court opinion.", "start": 6409.14, "stop": 6410.651, "duration": 1.51}, {"text": "It's important to be accurate to these matters.", "start": 6410.651, "stop": 6414.67, "duration": 4.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, it -- it certainly had the effect of turning these two ladies loose.", "start": 6414.67, "stop": 6418.587, "duration": 3.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That -- therefore, I ask you what the decision was.", "start": 6418.587, "stop": 6422.498, "duration": 3.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I think the decision was that the writ of habeas corpus was sustained.", "start": 6422.498, "stop": 6425.444, "duration": 2.95}, {"text": "And that two ladies were -- were turned loose and that there -- there were -- there were several different opinions but the -- the opinion I -- I think of Mr. Justice Black concurred in by the Chief Justice and two or three additional Justices to my mind, stated the law of this Court.", "start": 6425.444, "stop": 6441.964, "duration": 16.52}, {"text": "Now, if I'm wrong, I'm wrong.", "start": 6441.964, "stop": 6442.004, "duration": 0.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "It -- it -- they specifically did not do that.", "start": 6442.004, "stop": 6444.901, "duration": 2.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph S. Robinson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Very well, sir.", "start": 6444.901, "stop": 6445.448, "duration": 0.55}, {"text": "That -- that -- but I -- I think to get on with the subject matter of whether or not --", "start": 6445.448, "stop": 6452.281, "duration": 6.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "We'll recess now, Mr. Robinson.", "start": 6452.281, "stop": 6455.785, "duration": 3.5}]}]}], "decidedBy": "Warren Court", "arguedOn": "Jul 8, 1957", "petitioner": "Wilson", "respondent": "Girard", "docket": "1103", "citation": "354 US 524 (1957)", "justiaLink": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/354/524", "lowerCourt": "", "grantedOn": "", "decidedOn": "Jul 11, 1957", "wikiData": {"title": "Wilson v. Girard", "Litigants": "Wilson v. Girard", "ArgueDate": "July 8", "ArgueYear": "1957", "DecideDate": "July 11", "DecideYear": "1957", "FullName": "Charles E. Wilson, Secretary of Defense, et al., v. William S. Girard, United States Army Specialist 3/C.", "USVol": "354", "USPage": "524", "ParallelCitations": "77 S. Ct. 1409; 1 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 1544", "OralArgument": "https://www.oyez.org/cases/1950-1959/1957/1957_1103", "Prior": "''Girard v. Wilson'', 152 [[F. Supp.]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/152/21/1515578/ 21] ([[D.D.C.]] 1957) (denying writ of ''[[habeas corpus]]'', but granting injunction to petitioner)", "Subsequent": "", "Holding": "", "SCOTUS": "1956-1957", "PerCuriam": "yes", "LawsApplied": "[[U.S.–Japan Status of Forces Agreement]]", "NotParticipating": "Douglas"}}